<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MultipleTransplant     12-07 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Multiple Transplant,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five-Organ Recipient Getting Antibiotics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old recovering from a five-organ
transplant is being given antibiotics to combat bacteria in her
bloodstream, hospital officials said.
   Rolandrea Dodge, of Fruitland, N.M., remained in critical but
stable condition at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh, said hospital
spokeswoman Sue Cardillo said.
   Ms. Cardillo said a bacterium was detected during blood tests,
but doctors were not overly concerned.
   ``She's responding very favorably,'' the spokeswoman said
Tuesday. ``Today has been one of her best days.''
   Rolandrea, who's known as Rolly, received a new liver, pancreas,
stomach, small intestines and part of a large intestine on Nov. 29.
   The only other person to receive a five-organ transplant,
3-year-old Tabatha Foster, of Madisonville, Ky., survived six months
after undergoing the operation in November 1987.
</TEXT>
