<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     12-07 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Stretches Streak to 24 in a Row as `Cosby' Resumes Top Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plenty of new shows were broadcast last week, but
a rerun of ``The Cosby Show'' was the No. 1 prime-time program and
helped NBC stretch its run at the top of the A.C. Nielsen Co. rating
to 24 weeks.
   Barbara Walters helped ABC hold second place with a No. 2 rated
special.
   NBC won the week with an average, prime-time rating of 16.0. ABC
had a 13.4; CBS 12.2.
   The top 10 prime-time shows were: ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC; ``The
50th Barbara Walters Special,'' ABC; ``A Different World,'' NBC;
``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``60
Minutes,'' CBS; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS
and ``Growing Pains,'' ABC.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' continued to be the season's highest-rated new
show. Next-highest were NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and ``Dear John,''
ranked 12th and 13th, respectively.
   Among new shows, CBS' ``TV 101'' had an inauspicious debut at
63rd, just below ABC's ``Murphy's Law.'' CBS did better with
``Almost Grown,'' which ranked 44th.
   NBC has canceled ``Something Is Out There.'' ``Baby Boom'' and
``Tattinger's'' face problems. They ranked 48th and 60th,
respectively.
   Five of CBS' shows are struggling in the bottom 10.
   The week's lowest-rated shows were: ``West 57th'' tied with ``TV
101,'' ``Dirty Dancing,'' ``Knightwatch,'' ``The Van Dyke Show,''
``Police Story,'' ``Burning Questions: Defense,'' ``Trackdown,''
``Annie McGuire,'' ``Simon & Simon'' and ``Raising Miranda.''
   In the news category, the ``CBS Evening News'' was back on top
with a rating of 11.5. ``ABC World News Tonight'' had an 11.3; ``NBC
Nightly News'' 10.7.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with television.
</TEXT>
