<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summit-Bush     12-07 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Bush,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Cold War Stance Absent as He Meets Gorbachev</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Bush-Reagan-Gorbachev meeting begins 1:05 p.m. EST; will be
led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush is backing away
from his declaration that the Cold War is not over and says he is
optimistic about reforms adopted by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Bush was flying to New York to join President Reagan and
Gorbachev in a two-hour meeting on Governors Island today. At a news
conference Tuesday, Bush emphasized that he would participate as
vice president _ not as president-elect _ and that Reagan would be
in charge.
   ``The Soviets know how our system works, and they know that I
become president on Jan. 20,'' Bush said.
   Gorbachev arrived in New York on Tuesday, just minutes after Bush
completed his news conference in Washington. The Soviet leader said
he hoped today's talks would lead to ``an expansion of cooperation''
between Moscow and Washington.
   ``We have not arranged any formal agenda, so either side will be
free openly and frankly to raise any questions that it wishes to,''
Gorbachev said. With the U.S. government in transition, the
administration has said it does not plan to offer or negotiate any
new agreements with the Soviets.
   ``It is only prudent to review foreign policy and to review
national security policy, and certainly to review our relationship
with them,'' Bush said. ``Having said that, I will make clear to the
president (Gorbachev) that we want to go forward. But I'm not going
to be pressed into going beyond that prudent approach.''
   With his national security team still being assembled, Bush said
he did not want to go ``charging off without the benefit of those to
whom I'm going to look for advice.''
   During the presidential campaign, Bush struck a cautious stance
toward the Soviet Union, complimenting the Kremlin on its reforms
but saying it would be judged by its actions over time.
   In a speech last June, Bush declared, ``We've got to remember the
Cold War is not over. We must be bold enough to seize the
opportunity of change but at the same time, as one pundit titled his
column, be prepared for `the protracted conflict.'''
   Asked Tuesday if he still felt the Soviets and Americans are
engaged in a Cold War, Bush said, ``I'm not going to respond in
terms of those words. You have to define for me what you mean by
Cold War.
   ``Do we have any differences with the Soviets? Absolutely. Are
they regional? Yeah. Are they on human rights? Yes. Do we have some
differences on how we ought to approach the arms control agenda?
Certainly.
   ``But do I see _ am I optimistic about what I see in the Soviet
Union? Absolutely,'' Bush said.
   ``And you just take a look at the human rights question. There
have been some good forward steps there, and I want to see more.
   ``I think we come into a great period of opportunity in terms of
reduction of regional tensions,'' he added. ``But there's an awful
lot that the Soviets can do to make me feel I'm right in that. I
think that the arms control agenda is one where we have a chance for
real progress.''
</TEXT>
