<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HillsProfile     12-07 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hills Profile,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Role Model for Today's Superwoman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carla Hills, ex-Cabinet official, lawyer, wife,
mother and top tennis player, is a role model for today's superwoman.
   Mrs. Hills, 54, selected Tuesday by President-elect George Bush
to serve as his U.S. trade representative, is the only woman named
so far to a senior position in the new administration.
   She has been on a fast track since her early days in California.
   The daughter of a wealthy Los Angeles businessman, Hills got her
first top job in Washington in 1975 when President Ford named her
secretary of housing and urban development. Her father, Carl
Anderson, was once chairman of the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce.
   At the time she was confirmed, Mrs. Hills was only the third
woman Cabinet officer in history and the first in 20 years. Since
then, six woman have served in Cabinet posts, including former U.N.
Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, who was given Cabinet status.
President Reagan elevated the trade representative's job to Cabinet
level.
   Ford found Mrs. Hills in the Justice Department, where she was an
assistant attorney general in charge of the civil division. Some
criticized her appointment to HUD, saying she did not know enough
about housing issues.
   While she was serving at HUD, her husband, Roderick Hills, held
another top job in Washington as chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   During her two years, she tried to work with private enterprise
to encourage communities to provide more low-income housing.
   Since leaving government, Mrs. Hills has worked in private law
practice, most recently as co-director of the Washington office of
the New York firm of Weil, Gotshal and Manges. She also serves on
the boards of several large corporations and is active in legal
associations.
   Mrs. Hills was ambitious and hard-working even as a young girl,
according to friends and associates.
   Early in her professional life, she said she was never given
special treatment because she was a woman. ``That certainly wasn't
true in our law firm and it wasn't true in the Justice Department,''
she said.
   ``She is a strong-willed administrator who is receptive to new
ideas and new challenges,'' Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley once said
of her. ``She is bright and perceptive ... And she is hard working.''
   Others who know Mrs. Hills have described her as organized, tough
and determined.
   ``There is a certain amount of iron there,'' said one attorney
who had worked with her.
   Mrs. Hills, who grew up in Beverly Hills, was a honor student at
Stanford University where she met her future husband, an ex-football
player who was attending law school.
   After graduating, she studied at Oxford University in England and
then went to Yale Law School, where she graduated 20th in a class of
167.
   Back in California, she was an assistant U.S. attorney in Los
Angeles, and then was in private practice at a firm where her
husband was a partner.
   The mother of three daughters and a son, ages 19 to 29, Mrs.
Hills insisted on spending two hours every evening with her family
when the children were young.
   She said it was a challenge to juggle demands of both career and
family. ``I used to say that sometimes I feel like a long piece of
salami with a slice here for one and a slice here for another and
there isn't enough to go around,'' she said.
   ``She's combined being a wife and mother with fantastic
contributions to society,'' a former roommate, Beatrice Herrick,
said several years ago.
   Also high on Mrs. Hills' agenda is sports. She is a top-flight
tennis player, regularly beating her husband.
   As the trade representative, Mrs. Hills will be confronted by
numerous challenges involving complex international negotiations.
High on the agenda are the changing U.S. relationship with the
European Economic Community, which is set to integrate in 1992, and
implementation of the U.S.-Canada trade agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
