<DOCNO> AP881207-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MosbacherProfile     12-07 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mosbacher Profile,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Mixes Oil, Politics, Money and Friendship with Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the surface, the biography of Robert Mosbacher
Sr. reads just like George Bush's: born to a wealthy Northeastern
family, attended prep school and ventured off to Texas to make
millions in the oil business.
   Both also have been successful in mixing their money and oil with
politics. But until now, Mosbacher has been content to stay in the
background, raising the money to finance the political career of his
friend of more than 30 years.
   On Tuesday, Bush announced he was bringing his acquaintance from
Texas days into the government, as secretary of commerce in the Bush
administration.
   ``A friend of long standing, a very successful leader in the
business community,'' Bush termed him at a news conference.
   Mosbacher, 61, has raised campaign funds for Bush in every
political race he has entered since his second unsuccessful campaign
for the Senate in 1970.
   Mosbacher served as Bush's finance chairman during the
presidential campaign and raised nearly $20 million to help the vice
president secure the nomination. He also was chairman of the
Republican Party's ``Team 100'' program that raised $24 million from
individuals and corporations in $100,000 donations. He and his
companies directly contributed $47,600 to the Republican National
Committee.
   Like Bush, Mosbacher came to Texas to learn about the oil
business and invest family money. Bush learned the ways of the oil
patch and helped establish tiny Zapata Petroleum Co. which later
became Pennzoil Co.; Mosbacher established Mosbacher Petroleum Co.
in Houston.
   Mosbacher split from his father and older brother explaining, ``I
may not be a very much of a leader, but I'm a lousy follower.'' Bush
also struck out on his own as a young man.
   Mosbacher's father, Emil, began as a runner for the American
Stock Exchange and soon began trading on the exchange himself. By
age 21, he was a millionaire. The elder Mosbacher also managed to
liquidate before the market crash of 1929.
   In an effort to teach his sons to be stern, the father sent
Robert and older brother, Emil Jr., to strict prep schools _ Robert
attended The Choate School in Wallingford, Conn. _ and got them
interested in sailing to instill competition.
   In 1948 at age 21 with an economic degree from Washington and Lee
University, a pregnant wife and about $500,000 from his father,
Robert left the family home in suburban White Plains, N.Y., and
headed to Texas.
   Forty years later with interests also in real estate and
ranching, Mosbacher is worth an estimated $200 million. He lives
near Houston's exclusive River Oaks neighborhood with his third
wife, socialite Georgette Mosbacher, who recently purchased La
Prairie skin care company for $35 million.
   The couple have been married three years; she was once married to
George Barrie, former owner of Faberge, and is a former vice
president of Brut Productions, a Faberge division.
   Mosbacher, 61, becomes the third Texan named to Bush's Cabinet.
Bush previously named his campaign chairman, James A. Baker III of
Houston, as secretary of state and retained Lauro Cavazos of Lubbock
as secretary of education. Former Texas Sen. John Tower also is
being considered for secretary of defense.
   Mosbacher worked for the election of President Ford in 1976 and
was the finance co-chairman of the national Republican Party.
   In 1964, he headed a committee _ Oil Men for Bush _ during Bush's
unsuccessful bid for the Senate and served on Bush's finance
committee during his second unsuccessful race for the Senate in 1970.
   It was Mosbacher and Baker who persuaded Bush to withdraw from
the 1980 presidential race so he could be considered for the vice
presidential nomination by Ronald Reagan.
   Bush has described Mosbacher as a ``close confidant'' ad ``a
friend.''
   Mosbacher's fund-raising abilities have brought him into the
elite of the Republican Party. He took over Ford's campaign when the
coffers were almost empty after David W. Packard resigned following
three unsuccessful months. He immediately asked for help from his
own list of 1,700 people. In the end, Mosbacher raised over $14
million, about $2.5 million more than President Carter raised.
   Among the tasks facing the new secretary will be the
implementation of the new free-trade agreement between the United
States and Canada, assuming the Canadians ratify it.
   Even though most of Mosbacher's life has been centered on the oil
and gas business, fellow independent oilman Michel Halbouty of
Houston is confident he will do a good job.
   ``He has a very good business mind. He knows the relationship of
foreign trade and domestic trade. He's traveled the world and has a
broad viewpoint of other countries,'' Halbouty said of Mosbacher,
whom he has known for 35 years.
   ``You can bring a problem to him and he'll listen. He can get
along with just anybody. He has a strong affinity to people.''
   Mosbacher is no stranger to Washington. He went there often
during the spring and summer to offer advice to Bush. His older
brother Emil, known by his nickname Bus, served as chief of protocol
in the Nixon administration.
   Robert Mosbacher's son, Rob, ran for a U.S. Senate seat from
Texas in 1983, but lost in the Republican primary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
