<DOCNO> AP881207-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoskinProfile     12-07 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boskin Profile,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Choice as Top Economic Adviser Helped Create `Flexible Freeze'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economist Michael J. Boskin, selected by
George Bush on Tuesday to head the president's Council of Economic
Advisers, was a key architect of Bush's ``flexible freeze'' approach
to deficit reduction.
   Boskin, 43, a highly regarded Stanford University professor,
helped develop the plan while serving as a top Bush campaign adviser
on economic matters.
   The political beauty of the flexible-freeze plan is that it
doesn't commit Bush to any specific budget cuts. Instead, it calls
for the growth in overall government spending to be held to the rate
of inflation.
   Critics of the plan have charged that it is unworkable and would
force Draconian reductions in some areas of domestic spending to
make up for faster growth in such programs as Social Security, which
Bush has vowed to leave untouched.
   But in a Washington speech Tuesday, Boskin defended the flexible
freeze and predicted it would be able to balance the budget around
1993, depending on how fast the economy grows in the next few years.
   ``I think you will see the Bush administration take strong action
on the budget deficit quickly after the inauguration and I think it
will be on the spending side of the budget, consistent with the
flexible freeze,'' Boskin said at a policy conference sponsored by
the American Enterprise Institute.
   ``I can assure you that people who are very careful with numbers,
myself included, have gone over this and it is eminently do-able,''
he said. ``So the accusations that this doesn't add up are kind of
silly and not based on economic reality.''
   Boskin has Washington experience, working as a consultant to the
Defense, Treasury, Labor and old Health, Education and Welfare
departments as well as serving on a host of task forces.
   A native of New York, Boskin moved to Los Angeles with his family
when he was 6. His father was working as a construction contractor,
his mother as a bookkeeper and then an accountant. He studied
economics at the University of California at Berkeley, where he was
named the outstanding graduate of the class of 1967.
   Boskin wrote his doctoral dissertation on the effects of welfare
and other income-maintenance programs on the size of the labor force.
   He is described today as a hard-line Republican, but at Berkeley
in the tumultuous '60s Boskin was known as quite liberal.
   ``I was sympathetic with the goals _ freedom of speech, civil
rights _ and I still am,'' he said earlier this year. ``But I was
not sympathetic with the methods,'' such as student sit-ins and
strikes.
   He went from Berkeley to Stanford, where he has been ever since
except for a year of teaching at Harvard a decade ago and brief
periodic consulting jobs for Congress.
   Besides his unpaid campaign work for Bush this year, Boskin has
been busy writing two books on economics, teaching a graduate course
in fiscal policy and an introductory economics course, and acting as
West Coast director of the National Bureau of Economic Research, a
think tank.
   While he acknowledges that growth in wages has fallen behind the
pace of the 1950s and '60s, he contends it is a byproduct of rapid
job growth and says overall living standards have not declined.
   ``We have the beginning of some major transformations in the role
of government in the economy. We've had success in reducing marginal
tax rates. ... We have to build on what we have,'' Boskin said.
   Boskin was sharply critical of President Reagan's early policies
in his book entitled ``Reagan and the Economy: The Successes,
Failures and Unfinished Agenda.''
   But like Bush, who eight years ago branded Reagan's campaign
promises ``voodoo economics,'' Boskin joined the team and now saves
his barbs for the Democrats. Like Bush, Boskin opposes a general tax
increase under any circumstances.
   ``I'm concerned that a big tax increase could lead to a sharp
slowdown in the economy, or that a major new round of spending could
create major new future problems,'' he said.
   Boskin is among those who persuaded Bush to advocate cutting the
capital-gains tax rate. He also played a key role in Bush's call for
``individual savings accounts,'' a plan ridiculed by the Democrats
and some economists during the campaign. The savings plan would
offer tax-deferred interest to low- and middle-income Americans on
long-term savings deposits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WebsterProfile     12-07 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Webster Profile,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Webster Brings Agencies Out Of Shadow Of Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Webster, who was second choice as FBI
director a decade ago and again as CIA director in 1987, has led
both agencies out of the shadow of scandal.
   President-elect George Bush asked Webster on Tuesday to continue
to head the nation's top foreign intelligence agency.
   Webster, 64, pledged at his confirmation hearings last year to
keep members of congressional oversight committees fully informed of
CIA activities. His predecessor, the late William Casey, had been
criticized for hiding details of the Iran-Contra affair from
Congress.
   ``I have total confidence that he is the man, the best man to
build and lead our national intelligence community,'' Bush said in
announcing Webster's reappointment. Bush, who led the CIA himself
for a year under President Ford, said Webster's appointment was
``open-ended.''
   Webster announced before his confirmation that to avoid the
appearance of being ``a political animal'' he had asked to have the
CIA director's post removed from the president's Cabinet. Casey had
been the first CIA director to serve at the Cabinet level. The CIA
job is to remain a non-Cabinet position under Bush.
   Webster, a former federal judge from St. Louis who had headed the
FBI for nine years, was picked by President Reagan for the CIA job
after Deputy CIA Director Robert M. Gates had his nomination
withdrawn because of Senate questions about his role in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Webster agreed during confirmation hearings to review Gates'
testimony to Congress on the affair but deterimined he did nothing
that should prevent him from continuing as deputy. Gates also is to
remain in the No. 2 CIA post in the Bush administration, agency
spokesman Bill Baker said.
   Webster, a Republican, was nominated in 1978 by Democratic
President Carter to head the FBI, whose two previous directors had
been embroiled in political controversy. He was nominated after
Frank M. Johnson Jr., another federal judge, withdrew his name
because of ill health.
   The FBI's image had been sullied by revelations of personal
vendettas the bureau carried out for the late J. Edgar Hoover,
illegal surveillance of Vietnam war protesters and actions by acting
Director L. Patrick Gray III to hamper investigations into the
unfolding Watergate scandal in the early 1970s.
   In nine years asFBI director, Webster was popular with Congress.
His confirmation to become the 14th head of the CIA passed
unanimously in the Senate Intelligence Committee and was approved
94-1 by the full Senate.
   In 18 months at the CIA helm, Webster has improved the agency's
relations with Congress. He has pledged to disclose to congressional
leaders, in all but the most pressing circumstances, covert foreign
intelligence activities within 48 hours after the president approves
them.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., the Intelligence Committee chairman,
praised Webster's reappointment, saying the director had ``helped
restore public confidence in the CIA during a very troubling
period.''
   Last March, Webster told a congressional committee he had
reorganized the spy agency to improve counterintelligence and
strengthen security at U.S. embassies.
   Webster, who grew up in the St. Louis suburb of Webster Groves,
Mo., received a bachelor's degree from Amherst College and a law
degree in 1949 from Washington University in St. Louis.
   He served briefly as U.S. attorney for eastern Missouri and was
appointed to the U.S. District Court bench by President Nixon in
1971 and to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1973.
   Webster, a widower, has three children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PickeringProfile     12-07 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pickering Profile,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Ambassador A Career Diplomat With Experience In Troubled Spots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Pickering, selected by President-elect
George Bush as ambassador to the United Nations, is a veteran of 29
years' service in the Foreign Service with ambassadorships in El
Salvador, Israel, Jordan and Nigeria.
   Pickering, 57, is currently ambassador to Israel, where he can
indulge his interest in archaeology and is trying to add Hebrew to
the languages in which he is already proficient: French, Spanish,
Arabic and Swahili.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Pickering will replace Vernon
Walters, who spent 3{ years at the United Nations after serving as
ambassador at large during President Reagan's first term in office.
   Pickering's primary experience is in the Middle East, where he
also was ambassador to Jordan from 1974 to 1978 during President
Jimmy Carter's administration.
   Jordan's King Hussein called Pickering ``the best American
ambassador I've ever dealt with.''
   His service earlier in this decade in Nigeria and knowledge of
Swahili will help him in his dealings with Africa, the largest
regional bloc at the United Nations.
   But Pickering may be best known for the attention surrounding his
choice as ambassador to El Salvador in 1983.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz was not keen on a potential
candidate for the Salvador post being recommended by National
Security Council aides.
   To head off that choice, Shultz was determined to come up with an
alternate candidate. He reviewed the department's list of its
highest-ranked career diplomats.
   Near the top was Pickering. Shultz selected him, sensing that an
experienced hand was needed in El Salvador at a time when the
country was undergoing a difficult transition to democratic rule,
with both an active rebel movement and right-wing death squads
proliferating.
   Led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., conservatives fought Pickering's
assignment as ambassador to El Salvador, objecting to his previous
ties to Carter administration policies.
   Helms and other conservatives objected to Carter's policies
toward Third World countries, including treaties that the critics
felt did not adequately protect U.S. interests _ agreements that set
standards for deep sea mining, barred the use of the moon for
military purposes and set fishing agreements with Canada and Latin
American countries.
   Pickering cut short his tour of duty in Nigeria and accepted the
assignment in El Salvador, where he remained until he was sent to
Israel in 1985.
   In war-torn El Salvador, Pickering took a low key approach to the
job, but ran into controversy anyway.
   Helms wanted Pickering dismissed from that job, claiming
Pickering had interfered with elections in the Latin American
nation, to the detriment of right-wing candidates, an allegation
Pickering denied.
   Ultimately, when Pickering was named to the Israel
ambassadorship, Helms voted for him, saying his objections in the El
Salvador matter had been related to U.S. policy rather than to
Pickering's capabilities.
   Pickering was ambassador to Nigeria in 1981 to 1983, and
assistant secretary of state for oceans and international
environmental and scientific affairs in 1978 to 1981.
   He was ambassador to Jordan from 1974 to 1978 and previously
served in a variety of State Department and other foreign service
posts.
   He was deputy chief of mission in Dar es Salaam, the capital of
Tanzania, from 1967 to 1969 and was principal officer in Zanzibar _
now part of Tanzania _ from 1965 to 1967.
   In the early 1960s he was political officer in Geneva at the U.S.
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
   Born in Orange, N.J., Pickering graduated from Bowdoin College
and received graduate degrees from the Fletcher College of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University and from the University of Melbourne.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Thumbnails     12-07 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Thumbnails,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sketches of Bush's Latest Appointees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Transition Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are thumbnail sketches of appointees
announced Tuesday by President-elect George Bush.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Mosbacher, Commerce Secretary</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Mosbacher Sr., 61, a Houston oilman, served as finance
chairman during George Bush's presidential campaign. The two men are
close friends.
   Like Bush, Mosbacher was raised on the East Coast, where his
father made a fortune in the stock market. After graduating from The
Choate School and Washington and Lee University, he headed West with
his pregnant wife. He established Mosbacher Petroleum Co.
   Mosbacher, an avid sailor, is now worth an estimated $200
million, with interests in real estate and ranching as well as oil.
His third wife, socialite Georgette Mosbacher, recently purchased La
Prairie skin care company for $35 million.
   Mosbacher's older brother, Emil or ``Bus,'' was chief of protocol
during the Nixon administration.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Carla Hills, U.S. Trade Representative</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Carla Hills, 54, ex-Cabinet official, lawyer, wife, mother and
top tennis player, is a role model for today's superwoman. The
daughter of a wealthy Los Angeles businessman, Mrs. Hills graduated
from Stanford University and Yale Law School.
   She worked as a private attorney and assistant attorney general
in the Justice Department before then-President Ford named her
secretary of housing and urban development in 1975. At the time she
was confirmed, Mrs. Hills was only the third woman Cabinet officer
in history and the first in 20 years.
   Since leaving government, Mrs. Hills has worked in private law
practice, most recently as co-director of the Washington office of
the New York firm of Weil, Gotshal and Manges.
   Her husband, Roderick Hills, is the former chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission. They have four children ranging
in age from 19 to 29.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Michael Boskin, Chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Boskin, 43, a Stanford University professor, served as a top Bush
campaign adviser on economic matters. Over the years, he has worked
as a consultant to the Defense, Treasury, Labor and old Health,
Education and Welfare departments.
   A native of New York, Boskin moved to Los Angeles with his family
when he was 6. His father was working as a construction contractor,
his mother as a bookkeeper and then an accountant. He studied
economics at the University of California at Berkeley, where he was
named the outstanding graduate of the class of 1967.
   Boskin wrote his doctoral dissertation on the effects of welfare
and other income-maintenance programs on the size of the labor force.
   He is described today as a hard-line Republican, but at Berkeley
in the tumultuous '60s Boskin was known as quite liberal.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Webster, CIA Director</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   William Webster, 64, has been director of the CIA since 1987. A
former head of the FBI, Webster was chosen for the slot after the
Senate balked at confirming CIA deputy director Robert M. Gates for
the top job because of the Iran-Contra affair. Gates withdrew his
nomination.
   A native of St. Louis, Webster received his bachelor's degree
from Amherst College and a law degree from Washington University in
St. Louis.
   He practiced law in St. Louis and served briefly as U.S. attorney
for eastern Missouri. President Nixon appointed him to the U.S.
District Court bench in 1971 and to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in 1973.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Thomas R. Pickering, Ambassador to the United Nations</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pickering, 57, is one of the State Department's highest-ranking
diplomats. He has had several ambassadorial assignments, including
Israel, El Salvador, Nigeria and Jordan.
   Pickering's primary experience is in the Middle East, but he has
also worked in other posts at the State Department. From 1978 to
1981, he was assistant secretary of state for oceans and
international environmental and scientific affairs.
   A native of Orange, N.J., Pickering graduated from Bowdoin
College and received a master's degree from the Fletcher School of
Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University. For three years in the 1950s
he was a lieutenant commander in the Navy.
</TEXT>
