<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrunkenTeens     12-07 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drunken Teens,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Suggests Possible Curbs On Advertising For Alcohol</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The portrayal of alcoholic beverages in
national advertising likely contributes to under-age drinking, and
government limits on such ads eventually may be needed, according to
a group studying alcohol use by minors.
   The National Commission Against Drunken Driving suggested in a
report released Tuesday that if the alcohol and advertising
industries do not impose reforms ``legislation should be enacted to
regulate alcohol beverage advertising.''
   The panel did not say what kind of regulation it envisioned or
how much time the industry should be given to make changes in its
alcohol advertising.
   The report is part of a continuing examination by the commission
of efforts to curb drunken driving. The commission was formed five
years ago to continue where a presidential commission on drunken
driving left off.
   During a series of public hearings around the country, repeated
testimony from teen-agers indicated a link between advertisements
and a widespread view among young people that alcohol is a normal
part of a social event, the report said.
   ``With near unanimity, the youths themselves declared that
advertising encourages adolescents to drink,'' the commission said.
   V.J. Adduci, commission chairman, said at a news conference the
panel was not suggesting the need for immediate government
intervention in alcoholic beverage advertising, but wanted to send a
message to the industries involved to ``take a look at your
advertising'' and ``act like a parent'' when putting together ads
widely watched by youngsters too young to legally purchase alcoholic
drinks.
   Bob Hallahan, a spokesman for the National Association of
Broadcasters said his group agreed with Adduci's comments. ``He's
not looking for any legislation, but with working with the
industry,'' said Hallahan. He noted that his organization, which
opposes advertising curbs, also is represented on the commission.
   A spokeswoman for the Association of National Advertisers said
the group would have no comment because it had not seen the
commission report. Officials of the Beer Institute could not be
reached for comment Tuesday.
   The commission report, summarizing the results of its five public
hearings, said that despite grass-roots efforts against drunken
driving, laws in every state against minors purchasing alcoholic
beverages and many anti-drunken driving programs, ``young people
continue to drink and drive with alarming frequency.''
   As a result, young people ``continue to be involved in
alcohol-related crashes at disproportionately high rates,'' the
commission said. ``A young person under the legal drinking age
remains nearly twice as likely to die in an alcohol-related crash as
an adult over 21.''
   The report noted that between 1982 and 1987 the number of
alcohol-related fatalities among people under 21 declined by 21.9
percent, but ``drinking and driving continues to be the number one
killer of teenagers.''
   Last year the alcohol-related highway fatality rate was 19 per
100,000 for those under 21 years of age compared to 11 per 100,000
for those 21 years or older, the report said. It said while youth
under 21 years of age account for only 8 percent of the total
driving population, they account for 17 percent of the drivers
involved in alcohol-related fatal highway crashes.
   The report included these other conclusions, based on testimony
at the public hearings:
   _ ``Drinking is endemic among American youths (and) alcoholic
beverages remain easily accessible to youth under 21.
   _ ``Peer pressure encourages young people to drink and leads many
adolescents to consider alcohol a necessary accompaniment to social
events.
   _ ``Advertising normalizes alcohol consumption and makes it more
difficult to raise concerns about alcohol abuse.''
   In a letter to President Reagan accompanying the release of the
report, Adduci, the commission chairman, wrote:
   ``It is not enough to lament the thousands of young lives that
are lost each year on American highways. We must end the senseless
behavior that makes alcohol-related crashes the American way to die
for youth of driving age.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
