<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRouche     12-07 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fund-raisers Used Scare Tactics Against Texas Retiree</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial resumes at 10 a.m. EST; early afternoon lead likely</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   s
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) _ Political extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche's
fund-raisers warned of Soviet missiles, AIDS, international bankers
and illicit drugs to persuade a skeptical Texas retiree to make
$25,000 in loans that were never repaid.
   The high-pressure telephone tactics used on Max Harrell of
Pasadena, Texas, were disclosed Tuesday at LaRouche's mail and tax
fraud conspiracy trial in U.S. District Court.
   Harrell said he taped the conversations with fund-raisers Rebecca
Jones and Paul Greenberg because he had never received the promised
quarterly interest payments on his first $10,000 loan in April 1986.
   ``I was a bit nervous about getting these loans repaid,'' he told
government prosecutors.
   The lawyers quoted Greenberg as telling Harrell during one phone
call that ``all those dollars and cents you are hanging onto won't
matter a whit if the world collapsed.''
   The transcript of another recorded conversation between Harrell
and Ms. Jones quoted the fund-raiser as saying:
   ``In the scope of human history what you're going to be
remembered for is not whether you got 10 or 15 percent. Right? In
scope of human history what you're going to be remembered for is
that you had the foresight and the courage to back a fight to save
not only this nation but Western civilization...''
   When Harrell balked at making another loan to the LaRouche
organization, Ms. Jones warned that ``the Russians are churning out
three ICBMs every 48 hours'' and said money was needed to ``see the
international bankers defeated.''
   She also cited the AIDS epidemic and LaRouche's war against
drugs. ``Money for us is simply the means to do what we've got to do
politically, and the point right now is if we can escalate now, we
can turn the corner,'' she said.
   Harrell complained that he was ``doing a perpetual give as it is
with these loans,'' but Ms. Jones assured him that ``the loans
you're gonna get back.''
   ``Yeah,'' she said, ``you're taking a risk. But I've never said
anything other than that, so it's not like I'm trying to screw you
out of your money.''
   Harrell said he agreed reluctantly to extend two additional loans
because, even though retired, he could afford it.
   But he told questioners that he had received ``not a penny'' of
repayment.
   Harry Chusid, an accountant and auditor for the Internal Revenue
Service, testified Tuesday that his search of computer files at
LaRouche headquarters in Leesburg, Va., indicated that $33.3 million
had been borrowed from individual supporters from 1983 until
LaRouche's offices were raided by federal agents in October 1986.
   Chusid said $3.7 million in interest and principal had been
repaid during the same period.
   LaRouche, a perennial minor-party presidential candidate, and six
associates _ including Greenberg _ are charged with mail fraud and
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans with
no intention of repaying them.
   LaRouche is charged separately with conspiracy to defraud the IRS
by having all his personal expenses paid by various corporations he
controls and failing to file federal income tax returns since 1978.
   LaRouche denies any wrongdoing. If convicted on all 13 counts
against him, he faces a maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and
fines totaling $3.25 million.
   Wayne Hintz, a former LaRouche finance officer, testified Tuesday
that he resigned in June 1986 when he came to the conclusion that
the growing number of loans to the LaRouche organization weren't
going to be repaid.
   But Hintz said he was unaware of any official policy against
honoring the terms of the loans, which he said had swollen from $10
million to about $40 million during 1985 alone.
</TEXT>
