<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Gorbachev'sApple     12-07 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Gorbachev's Apple,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Gets Tourist-Eye's View of New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev wanted to ``take a bite out of
the Big Apple,'' his aides said, and today's meanderings seemed
certain to give him a pungent taste, seeds and all.
   The Soviet leader is seeing the city at its best, with crisp fall
air, bright Christmas lights and _ for him, at least _ wide open
streets. It's a great time to be a tourist, especially with a 45-car
motorcade and full police escort.
   He's likely to remember the glint of light off the Statue of
Liberty, the day-long dusk of Wall Street, the stomach-plunging
elevator ride to the top of the World Trade Center and the
breathtaking view from the top of the 110-story skyscraper.
   But New York is never pristine, and there's been no frantic
effort to change that. No one has been filling in potholes, painting
over graffiti or sedating city denizens.
   Gorbachev's New York slide show could include hulking tenements
on the Lower East Side, tawdry porn shops in Times Square and maybe
_ just maybe _ some of the city's legions of homeless people.
   Ironically, he may have avoided an encounter with the homeless by
passing up a visit to glittering Trump Tower. Robert Hayes, a
spokesman for the Coalition for the Homeless, said there had been
plans to mount a demonstration until his group learned that
Gorbachev apparently had declined tycoon Donald Trump's invitation.
   Hayes accused police on the East Side _ where the United Nations
and the Soviet Mission are located _ of persuading homeless people
to migrate to the West Side, out of Gorbachev's sight.
   According to Hayes, one officer reportedly told a homeless man,
``Go West, young man.''
   But a police spokesman, Detective Joseph McConville, said he was
unaware of such tactics. ``Why would we do that?'' he asked.
   Today's itinerary included the United Nations, where few New
Yorkers go, and Governor's Island, where few New Yorkers are
permitted (it's a Coast Guard base), particularly at a lunch with
President Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
   Other snapshots from the Gorbachev camera during his two-day
visit could include Carnegie Hall's understated facade and that
bright red restaurant next door _ the Russian Tea Room, where the
spirit of the imperial Romanovs is alive and well.
   There's the Brooklyn Bridge and the Manhattan Bridge, the FDR
Drive and Broadway, Central Park and Battery Park and tiny Gen.
Douglas MacArthur Park.
   And then there's the Metropolitan Museum, one of the spots
Gorbachev was reportedly eager to see. The description in the
American Institute of Architects' Guide to New York could stand as a
description for the city Gorbachev is getting to know:
   ``It is a rich and exciting melange,'' the guidebook says of the
Metropolitan's exterior, ``exciting, grand, controversial, often
elegant, sometimes banal. ... Mandatory contribution on entry.''
</TEXT>
