<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle, Mondale Meet to Discuss Vice Presidency</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: closed meeting begins 8 a.m. EST; may be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle is seeking insights on the vice
presidency from Walter Mondale, a Democrat who held the job for four
years under President Jimmy Carter.
   The vice president-elect was meeting over breakfast this morning
at his office with Mondale for the second in a series of discussions
with men who have held the job.
   Quayle met with former President Richard Nixon last week _ Nixon
served as vice president to Dwight Eisenhower _ and he will see
former President Gerald Ford next week, said press spokesman Jeff
Nesbit. Ford was Nixon's second vice president.
   The purpose of the meeting with Mondale, who along with Carter
was much maligned by Quayle during the campaign, is ``to discuss the
office of the vice presidency ... what's possible, what's not,''
said Nesbit.
   Mondale, a former senator from Minnesota, ran unsuccessfully for
president against President Reagan in 1984, losing in a landslide
that saw Mondale win only the District of Columbia and his home
state.
   Among the topics will be the vice president's role as president
of the Senate. Quayle is interested in exploring ways to develop and
expand the position.
   Quayle also has selected veteran Time magazine correspondent
David Beckwith to be his press secretary when he takes office as
vice president.
   Beckwith, who has been with Time since 1969, recently covered the
Bush campaign for 15 months. He was considered for an appointment as
Bush's White House press secretary, but that job went to current
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, who had worked in that
capacity for Bush before Reagan tapped him.
   The reporter said he is looking at the position with Quayle as
``a great opportunity for me.''
   Noting the barrage of negative press that has rained down on the
Indiana senator since Bush selected him, Beckwith said some of that
negativity is unjustified.
   ``I've talked to him a lot over the last couple weeks. I realize
he's a lot better than his press notices would make him appear,''
Beckwith said.
   Beckwith, a Chicago native, also formerly worked for the
Minneapolis Star and the Houston Chronicle. He has a law degree from
the University of Texas, a masters in journalism from Columbia
University and an undergraduate degree from Carleton College in
Northfield, Minn.
</TEXT>
