<TEXT>
   R. Sargent Shriver and the Baltimore Orioles'
acting president Larry Lucchino have joined two other investors to
buy the baseball team for $70 million.
   The announcement of the sale was made Tuesday at Atlanta, site of
baseball's winter meetings.
   The sale by Mrs. Agnes Williams, widow of Orioles owner Edward
Bennett Williams, must be approved by three-quarters of the American
League owners and a majority of National League owners.
   Bobby Brown, the American League president, said the time frame
for making the decision on the sale is within 90 days, although it
could come sooner.
   The Orioles were sold to a group headed by New York businessman
Eli S. Jacobs, a Wall Street investor who becomes the team's
majority owner. Lucchino, Shriver, the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate in 1972, and Shriver's son, Robert S. Shriver, also will
have ownership interests.
   The senior Shriver, 72, is a brother-in-law of the late President
Kennedy and a good friend of the Williams family.
