<DOCNO> AP881207-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CitiesConference     12-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cities Conference,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Information Please: Citizens Talk By Computer To City Hall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someday, shoppers at a mall may enter a computer
booth to pay a parking ticket or utility bill, register to vote or
check on garbage pickup times, municipal officials say.
   ``The key thing is to make it easier for people to get
information about their government at a place and time convenient to
them,'' Kansas City, Mo., City Councilor John A. Sharp said Tuesday.
``We still operate at the convenience of the bureaucracy, not at the
convenience of citizens.''
   Residents can't yet pay parking tickets or apply for building
permits by computer, but in Kansas City, Charlotte, N.C., and
Hillsborough County, Fla., they can receive a wide array of
electronic information about government services and operations.
   The two cities and the county are taking part in a computer-based
pilot program that gives people easier access to local government,
officials said at the National League of Cities convention Tueday.
   The project's cost was not released.
   Computerized communications between residents and government may
seem impersonal, but officials said the technology is a convenient,
efficient way to provide more, better information.
   Using equipment donated by International Business Machines Inc.,
the three jurisdictions made the information services available this
year. The project was organized by Public Technology Inc. of
Washington, the league's non-profit research and development arm.
   In Kansas City, computer kiosks with a color screen that displays
information and pictures have been set up in two malls for about a
year, connected directly to city hall.
   Residents can touch a screen and get information on recreational
events, licenses and permits, complaints about police, traffic or
trash pickup; neighborhood services; government meetings; or city
jobs. The computers have averaged 700 touches daily, and are on line
15 hours a day.
   In a survey of the computer users, more than half said they had
never been to city hall for the kind of information available in the
computer. During a one-month period, requests for information on
recreational events totaled 1,880, compared with 398 complaints.
   ``We'll be where they do business,'' said Sandra Charbonier,
citizen action center manager for Hillsborough County, which
includes Tampa. ``They won't have to come to where we do business.''
   Charlotte established a telephone system in which people calling
some city hall departments hear recorded messages that direct them
to press numbers to select specific information or record a message
of their own. The result has been better response time from
officials such as building inspectors who get messages from
contractors.
   ``Not everyone is willing to accept one-way communication for
information,'' said Boyd Cauble, executive assistant to the city
manager. ``I see the system (being made) available to pay bills by
entering credit card numbers, getting permits, exchanging
information. All this requires a tremendous amount of refinement of
the system and a tremendous amount of public education.''
</TEXT>
