<HEAD>MCI Cutting Long-DIstance Rates 3.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp., the nation's second
largest long-distance telephone company, announced a package of
price cuts that include a 3.9 percent reduction in basic interstate
long-distance rates.
   The announcement by Washington-based MCI on Tuesday came six days
after industry leader American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and No. 3
US Sprint Communications Corp. announced cuts averaging 3.8 percent
and 3.85 percent, respectively.
   MCI said it was passing on savings that result from a lowering of
access charges that it pays to local telephone companies. It said
the reduction effective Jan. 1 means MCI will have dropped its rates
36 percent since the breakup of the Bell System in 1984.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff is
counseling President-elect George Bush to reject calls for Pentagon
budget cuts as ``inefficient and dangerous.''
   Members of Congress who call for defense reductions say little
``about overseas threats or `military realities' which do not
conform to their version of political reality,'' Adm. William J.
Crowe Jr., the joint chiefs chairman, said Tuesday.
   Crowe said in a speech he wants to help improve Pentagon
management and to convince Congress that stable financing instead of
peak-and-valley cycles could save huge amounts of money.
   Crowe said that while changes may be called for, ``it would be a
grievous _ and probably, ultimately disabling _ error to undertake
those adjustments with an eye only to the concerns of accountants.''
