<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has decided to allow
kids in this city once known as ``Goat Hill'' and won't evict Barney
Junior, a 90-pound pygmy goat.
   Barney's owner, Angela Raj Kumar, had been told that the goat
would have to go because city codes prohibited barnyard animals in
back yards, and a neighbor had complained.
   But she circulated a petition among her neighbors in support of
Barney and submitted it to the council. It asked that the goat be
allowed to stay in the city, whose newsletter is called ``The Goat
Hill Gazette.''
   Raj Kumar pleaded her case before the council Monday night, and,
to make her point, marched Barney into council chambers.
   ``A lot of people are not really informed on animals. We're so
city oriented,'' she said. ``When a goat is fixed, there is no
smell.''
   Former Mayor Norma Hertzog-Wagner spoke on behalf of Barney.
   ``We shouldn't be so pristine that we lose touch,'' she said.
``We should all have kids around all of the time.''
   The council agreed, voting 4-1 to allow some barnyard animals
into the city's back yards with proper permits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The residents of the Leisureville
Delray retirement condominium community have hated the name since
they moved in. They said it made them sound lazy, hedonistic and
near death.
   ``There's always somebody that makes fun of it,'' said Doris
Goldberg, one of the 8-year-old complex's 1,098 residents. ``It
sounds like an old people's home.''
   These senior citizens say they may be retired, but they're far
from retiring. At their annual meeting Tuesday, they voted 598-2 to
change the name to Delray Villas.
   ``We're active, energetic and athletic,'' resident Connie Joseph
said. ``If you saw our tennis courts, you wouldn't believe we were
senior citizens.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the leaders of the two superpowers
discuss peace a few miles away in New York City, croquet players and
lawn bowlers in Greenwich are toasting their new truce.
   Ending four months of sometimes negotiations, representatives of
the Greenwich Croquet Club and the Greenwich Lawn Bowls Club
announced Monday that they will share the lawns at the town's Bruce
Park.
   ``They deserve a lot of credit for working it out,'' Parks and
Recreation Director Frank Keegan said. ``I'm thrilled that it came
to a happy conclusion.''
   Standing on the bowling green at the park Monday, croquet players
Fred Supper, Norman ``Topper'' Cook, David Caulkins and William
Campbell joined lawn bowler leader Charles Morgan at his sport. And
Morgan took a few whacks with a mallet.
   The lawn bowlers have had exclusive use of the green since the
1940s.
   The proposal by the croquet group to share the park began in
August, when Supper's wife, Patricia, presented the Board of
Selectmen with a petition with about 100 signatures asking for
approval to share the field.
   Ensuing negotiations led to the settlement. But as recently as
October, Morgan said the position of his group was, ``there's a
possibility that croquet could exist.''
   As part of the agreement, the lawn bowlers will reserve a 50-foot
wide section of the green for two hours every afternoon. The rest of
the 70-by-120-foot green will be available for croquet at the same
time. Croquet may also be played after 3 p.m. The mornings were
aside for maintenance.
</TEXT>
