<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Rights     12-07 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Rights,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-based Human Rights Group Alleges Abuses In Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has jailed human rights workers for
months and violated international law by transporting Palestinians
detained without trial to a desert camp inside Israel, a U.S.-based
human rights group charged today.
   The Lawyers Committee for Human Rights made the allegations in a
95-page report that features testimony from six Palestinian lawyers
and human rights workers as well as interviews with Israeli
officials.
   The report accuses Israel of arresting Palestinian human rights
workers on secret charges and outlines Israeli abuses in the Ketziot
prison established during the year-long Palestinian revolt against
Israeli's 21-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Ketziot's location in a remote part of Israel proper, its
extremely harsh desert climate and its crowded, inhumane living
conditions combine to create an untenable environment in which to
maintain long-term detainees,'' the report by the New York-based
group says.
   ``The detention of residents of the occupied territories in
Israel proper is contrary to the Fourth Geneva Convention.'' The
1949 convention states that detainees in an occupied country may not
be moved to another country.
   Ketziot, where more than 2,000 detainees from the West Bank and
Gaza are believed held, is in the heart of Israel's southern Negev
desert.
   Last week, Ketziot inmates staged a two-day hunger strike. Arab
reports said the strike was to protest harsh prison conditions. On
Tuesday, Palestinians staged a general strike in the occupied lands
in solidarity with the detainees.
   The Lawyers Committee report alleges that Arabs are routinely
forced to stand in the sweltering desert heat for hours, water
supplies are inadequate and prisoners are sometimes beaten.
   Ketziot inmates made similar complaints when an Associated Press
reporter visited the prison in June.
   The report quotes Army Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron as
saying the location may be a ``contradiction'' of the Geneva
Convention, but that Israel has ``the right to transfer prisoners
into a sovereign part'' of the country.
   Shomron also said the army is trying to improve conditions at the
prison, but that conditions are harsh.
   ``It's not a hotel,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The report says four Palestinian fieldworkers for Al-Haq, an
Arab-run human rights group based in the occupied West Bank, were
detained for over six months on secret charges: ``The administrative
detention without charge of four Al-Haq fieldworkers is a serious
blow to independent human rights monitoring in the West Bank.''
   The report alleges that Israel circumvents the legal process by
routinely detaining Palestinians on the basis of secret evidence:
``The ... secret evidence is not made available to detainees or
their lawyers and therefore can not be effectively challenged by
counsel.''
   An army spokesman said he had not yet received the report and
could not comment on its findings.
   Al-Haq issued a report Monday challenging Israeli claims that the
army was using lawful measures to quell the rebellion, in which 319
Palestinians and 11 Israelis have died since last Dec. 8.
   The Lawyers Committee for Human Rights was established in 1978
and has investigated human rights abuses in more than 25 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
