<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-07 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Shares Hit Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
sharply to a record high as the key index closed about 30,000 for
the first time.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 54.70 points for
a record closing high the previous day, added another 381.44 points
or 1.29 percent to finish trading at 30,050.82 yen.
   The dollar closed at 122.43 yen, up 0.89 yen from Tuesday's close
of 121.54 yen. Opening at 121.82 yen, the currency gradually rose
while ranging between 121.82 yen and 122.60 yen. It was the first
time that the dollar rose back beyond the 122-yen mark since Nov.
29, when it finished at 122.15 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's strength stemmed from speculation that
the United States and the Soviet Union would reach agreement on
reducing conventional military forces during Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's visit to New York.
   ``The dollar began rising gradually after the opening, and
participants continued to buy after it reached the 122-yen level,''
said a currency dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   He said recent bearish sentiment toward the dollar on the Tokyo
market had declined because of the upcoming U.S.-Soviet summit talks
in New York.
   Gorbachev is scheduled to meet with President Reagan and to
address the U.N. General Assembly.
   The dollar's upturn in Tokyo also followed news indicating that
the U.S. budget deficit may be reduced, currency dealers said.
   Michael Boskin, chosen by President-elect George Bush to be his
chief economic adviser, reportedly said Bush will ``take strong
action on the deficit on the spending side of the budget.''
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices rose mainly because of
an overnight gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York,
dealers said.
   Stock investors also were encouraged by the announcement Tuesday
of a 2.2 percent gain in the Japanese gross national product in the
third quarter over the previous three-month period, dealers said.
The GNP rose 9.3 percent on an annual basis during the quarter.
</TEXT>
