<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FBI-DrugCartels Bjt   12-07 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Drug Cartels, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bogus Electronics Co. ShocksDrug Middlemen, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-month FBI ``sting'' had Colombian drug-cartel
point men using a phony electronics company as a clubhouse, leading
to indictments of 93 people and leaving traffickers wondering, ``who
do you trust?,'' authorities say.
   About half of the suspects were in custody Tuesday in Boston,
Houston, Los Angeles, Tampa and Miami, and many were expected to
surrender later, the FBI said. Among those arrested were a Latin
recording star and two former Miami police officers.
   The sting, nicknamed ``Cat-Com'' for Catch Communications, also
allowed federal agents to seize about 5 tons of cocaine, 100 tons of
marijuana and some heroin, authorities said.
   R.A. Communications and Computers Inc. ``essentially was used as
a clubhouse or a meeting place for first-line drug traffickers
associated with the Medellin and Cali cartels,'' said William Perry,
South Florida's acting FBI director.
   He said the traffickers, who were indicted by federal grand
juries in Miami and Tampa, were ``top-of-the-line'' U.S. contacts
for drug lords Pablo Escobar Gaviria, Jorge Luis Ochoa Vasquez and
Jose Gonzalo Rodrigues Gacha, who operate in the Colombian towns of
Medellin or Cali.
   The indictments send a message that drug smugglers can never be
sure who they're dealing with, said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   ``Everything they do in the United States is subject to come back
to haunt them,'' Lehtinen said.
   ``They might have bought their ice cream from an undercover
agent, they might have bought their communications from an
undercover agent.''
   Unsuspecting traffickers became so trusting of the staff at the
Hialeah electronics company that they talked openly about the
narcotics trade, Perry said.
   The company, which was closed following Tuesday's indictments,
sold high-tech equipment to them and soon was arranging
communications that allowed the suspects to talk directly by two-way
radio to smuggling ships and their bosses in Colombia, authorities
said. Only a few of the company's customers were not involved in
drug trafficking, said FBI officials.
   As the traffickers relaxed in a comfortable lounge at the
company, FBI agents and government sources recorded every
conversation with hidden video and audio equipment, Perry said.
   At one point the middlemen even asked the agents to check
properties for electronic bugs, the FBI said.
   The investigation was the ``largest undercover operation ever
directed toward the inter-workings of the drug cartels,'' FBI
Director William Sessions said in Washington, D.C.
   More than $1 million in cash and property has been seized and
total seizures are expected to exceed $4 million, said the FBI
director.
   One of those arrested Tuesday was Raul Alfonso, 39, part of the
popular salsa group Hansel and Raul. Alfonso was charged with
conspiracy to import cocaine and importation of cocaine with intent
to distribute the drug, authorities said.
   Alfonso denied the charges as he and other defendants were loaded
onto a bus at FBI headquarters in North Miami Beach.
   The former police officers, Jorge Luis Canizares and Ramon de
Jesus Perez, were arrested Monday night near R.A. Communications
after buying 6 kilograms of cocaine, authorities said. They had been
out on bond on other drug charges when they were arrested.
   The FBI and other agencies, including the Drug Enforcement
Administration, Customs Service, Coast Guard and local agencies, had
to walk a thin line on the case to both keep the traffickers'
confidence and enforce the U.S. policy of not allowing any drugs to
be imported, even in an undercover operation.
   Information from the sting allowed Navy and Coast Guard vessels
to intercept the drugs, usually in 500-kilogram amounts, before they
reached the United States from South America.
   In one instance, the drug traffickers hired a sailboat named
Naut-For-Fun, piloted by FBI sources, to carry nearly 900 pounds of
cocaine from Colombia.
   The FBI had planned to seize the drugs covertly and tell the
traffickers the sailboat had sunk with the crew lost at sea. Then
bad weather hit and the boat was sunk. The Coast Guard rescued those
aboard and recovered the cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
