<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-CommandCenter     12-07 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Command Center,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal, Local Officials Work Together At Gorbachev Command Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of at least 20 agencies from the
U.S. State Department to the city Fire Department have gathered
under one roof for one purpose: to keep Mikhail Gorbachev safe and
happy ``until he's put to bed.''
   ``We would define success as having nothing to do for the next
three days,'' police Deputy Inspector James Vitti said Tuesday, as
the Soviet president began his three-day visit to New York City.
   The command center at Police Headquarters is in a large room
containing two long tables with banks of telephones and a
26-by-10-foot video screen on the wall.
   In addition to the dozen or so police officials, more than 20
other agencies operate there, including the FBI, the Secret Service,
the Coast Guard, the State Department, the Federal Aviation
Administration, the Fire Department, the city's traffic department
and ambulance corps.
   The brain center is in operation until midnight on each day of
Gorbachev's visit or until ``he's put to bed at the Soviet
Mission,'' Vitti said.
   ``The premise is that we have one location where people who can
speak for their agencies are available to cope with any potential
problem that may develop,'' Vitti said. ``It's an assembly of people
who are problem-solvers.''
   Few authorities could conceive of a greater problem than if the
ebullient Gorbachev indulges his penchant for mingling with street
crowds. Most, however, were confident of the Soviet leader's safety.
   ``We have 6,000 cops out there and he's safe in this city, as
safe as anyone can be,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said on ABC-TV's
``Nightline.'' ``Obviously, there are nuts all around the world. But
I believe we don't have a full moon and it's going to be OK.''
   On Tuesday, the command center officials watched local television
coverage of Gorbachev's arrival on the video screen and several
other television sets in the room.
   The center, which is in constant contact with agents and officers
in the field, was called upon at least three times before Gorbachev
and his wife, Raisa, were safely delivered to the Soviet Mission in
Manhattan from Kennedy International Airport.
   The first call came before their arrival when motorists on the
Long Island Expressway became impatient with detours and drove up on
the grass to avoid roadblocks.
   This problem went to police officials who dispatched extra
patrols to the area to turn back the motorists.
   Another traffic problem arose on the Van Wyck Expressway in
Queens when a propane truck broke down in a southbound lane before
it was to be closed for Gorbachev's motorcade.
   The representative for the city Transportation Department at the
command center ordered the immediate dispatch of a tow truck, which
removed the disabled vehicle 10 minutes before Gorbachev left the
airport.
   As the motorcade traveled down the Grand Central Parkway in
Queens, another call came in _ a private helicopter hired by a news
organization was hovering too close to the procession of 45 cars.
   The FAA representative notified the closest air control tower and
the helicopter was told to pull back.
   When the motorcade arrived at the Soviet Mission, another police
official, Lt. Vincent Kennedy, remarked with relief, ``As an old
friend of mine used to say, it went like ice cream. No problems.''
</TEXT>
