<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-Gorbachev     12-07 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Gorbachev,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says No Plans For Reforms To Be Imposed On Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Soviet official says there are no
plans for Soviet-style economic reforms to be imposed on Communist
Cuba, the island nation's official news agency reported.
   Victor Kompletkov, Soviet deputy foreign minister, made his
statements Tuesday at the press center for Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, who is to arrive in the Soviet client state Friday for a
three-day visit.
   Kompletkov's comments were carried Tuesday by the Prensa Latina
news agency, which was monitored in Mexico.
   On Monday, the 32nd anniversary of the landing of the yacht that
carried Cuban leader Fidel Castro from Mexico to launch the
revolution against dictator Fulgencio Batista, Castro said he would
defend the Cuban form of socialism against friend and foe, Prensa
Latina reported.
   Castro said some of Cuba's problems have been caused by its own
errors, but that others were caused by imitating other socialist
countries.
   Kompletkov said the political and economic reforms Gorbachev has
championed apply to conditions only in the Soviet Union and are not
intended for other countries, the report said.
   Nevertheless, Gorbachev is expected during his visit to encourage
Castro to follow the Soviet model of encouraging individual
initiative by enabling enterprises to make profits and by allowing
people to launch private cooperatives.
   Castro has been cool to such suggestions and has also been
unsympathetic to Gorbachev's policies of encouraging greater
openness of expression and a more competitive system of electing
party and government officials.
</TEXT>
