<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TV-SteinbergTrial Bjt   12-07 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Steinberg Trial, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev In New York, But Murder Trial Captures Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During Mikhail Gorbachev's arrival here, local
programming was pre-empted _ but not only for the Soviet president.
New Yorkers also got to watch hours of live coverage of a murder
trial.
   When Hedda Nussbaum took the stand last week to testify against
her former live-in lover, Joel Steinberg, accused of beating to
death their illegally adopted 6-year-old daughter, Lisa, all three
network affiliates went live with the testimony. The networks have
pre-empted up to three hours a day of regular programming since.
   Cable channels have carried live trial coverage in the past,
notably CNN's coverage of the New Bedford, Mass., gang rape trial in
1984. But the Steinberg case seems to be the first time network
affiliates have pre-empted so much regular programming for such
coverage.
   ``This is compelling television in the best sense of the word,''
said Roger Colloff, general manager of WCBS-TV, which had carried
about 13 hours of live coverage of the trial since Nov. 30.
   ``This is not something being done by actors,'' Colloff said.
``This is a case with real and horrible consequences.''
   Last December, New York joined 43 others states when it enacted a
law allowing cameras in the courtroom under an 18-month experimental
period.
   In New York, judges can have veto camera coverage, and the
Steinberg case is the first trial of major interest in which the
judge has approved coverage during testimony.
   The death of Lisa in an affluent, well-educated household shocked
many New Yorkers and led to a re-examination of the duty and ability
of neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   In two recent, highly publicized cases _ the Howard Beach racial
killing and the Robert Chambers murder trial _ the respective judges
allowed television coverage only during sentencing.
   ``I think it's the `new toy' kind of phenomenon,'' said Everette
E. Dennis, executive director of the Gannett Center for Media
Studies at Columbia University.
   ``This is the first time that the television stations have had an
opportunity to do this kind of live coverage. I do think it's a
passing show, unless the ratings are so high, higher than the soap
operas, that in an economic sense they (the stations) feel it's
warranted.''
   WABC-TV, which has the highest-rated soap operas, resumed regular
programming Monday. According to A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings, trial
coverage was higher-rated on WNBC-TV and WCBS than the stations'
regularly scheduled soap operas.
   On Monday afternoon, trial coverage on WCBS had a rating of 5.2.
In the November sweeps _ key ratings periods that determine
advertising rates _ the station averaged a 3.1 for soap operas
airing during the same time period, and a 4.3 for a syndicated show
called ``On Trial.''
   On Tuesday, the networks pre-empted some programming for
Gorbachev's arrival. Coincidentally, there was no session in the
Steinberg trial scheduled for today, when the networks planned more
extensive live coverage of Gorbachev.
   Even though ratings have gone up, the trial coverage is
unsponsored, so stations lose ``many tens of thousands of dollars''
in advertising revenues, said Colloff. But there is a public
relations value to the coverage, along with a public service one.
   ``There really has been a reaction from people watching this
testimony which may be beneficial and may lead people to get out of
situations that they should be getting out of,'' Colloff said. ``I
don't want to sound to ethereal, but it actually may prevent another
Steinberg case from occurring.''
   The New York Times agreed in an editorial Tuesday: ``This drama
offers, beyond wallowing, a redeeming possibility: reliving on
television one child's terrible death can arouse in a large audience
the will to prevent the deaths of many others.''
   New York's chief administrative Judge Albert M. Rosenblatt, who
favored the new law, told the Times last month, ``The purpose of the
cameras in the courtroom experiment was to show the workings of the
justice system. The more people learn about the system, the more
confidence they'll have in it.''
   ``I think the overall effect is probably good,'' said Dennis.
``The more people are exposed to trials and nuances and questioning,
the better, even if it's fragmented. I'd rather have that than a few
highly sensational details.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
