<HEAD>Madison Avenue Lures Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advertising agency took out a full-page ad in
Russian in today's editions of The New York Times in an attempt to
open negotiations with Mikhail Gorbachev over his budding career as
a television pitchman.
   The Madison Avenue firm of Messner Vetere Berger Carey
Schmetterer wants to lure the Soviet leader into its offices with a
blank check for his inadvertant appearance in a Republican campaign
commercial, in which he is shown greeting George Bush.
   ``You, the Secretary General of the Soviet Union, were the star
of a major commercial in the George Bush campaign this fall and, as
an on-camera principal, are now due a pretty substantial sum of
money in talent payments,'' says the ad, which is written in Russian
and translated into English on the opposite page.
   If Gorbachev can produce a Screen Actors Guild card, he would be
due about $60,000 in talent fees for his appearance, said Ron
Berger, a partner in the firm.
   But since the Soviet leader is not a member of the union, his
compensation ``would be the subject of negotiation,'' Berger said.
   The ad makes no secret of its real reason for the appeal to
Gorbachev.
   ``We have immense experience selling upscale items. We can help
you sell Beluga caviar or help Stoli (Stolichnaya vodka) fight off
Absolut which has been eating into your market share,'' the ad says.
   The ad also offers Gorbachev the firm's services if he decides to
run for re-election.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Waldorf Chef Oversees Luncheon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Patrick Doherty, the man in the kitchen for
today's superpower luncheon, has cooked before for President Reagan,
who he said has personally complimented him on his cuisine.
   ``Last Wednesday, they asked me if I would be interested,'' said
Doherty, 30, a chef at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel for 11 years. ``I
submitted three menus for approval. ... They chose one on Friday. It
was great. I was very happy.''
   That menu for the meeting between Reagan, Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev and President-elect George Bush starts with chicken
consomme and the wild mushroom ravioli to start, followed by
tournedos of veal with smoked quail and lobster sausage, braised
cabbage and leeks, roesti potatoes (julienned and sauteed until
crisp) and sauteed fresh leaf spinach.
   The wine is a California chardonnay. Dessert features a chocolate
tart with almond cream cheese, fresh fruit and raspberry sauce.
   Doherty said it would take 14 people about four hours to prepare
the meal, under the watchful eye of Secret Service agents.
   The chef has cooked for Reagan before, because the president
generally stays at the Waldorf-Astoria when in New York. Twice,
Reagan has personally complimented Doherty on his cooking, Doherty
said.
   ``This style of cooking is what he prefers,'' he said. ``There
are some guidelines for keeping his health in mind. ... But I've
done this many times.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Gorbylock Affects New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The effects of Mikhail and Raisa Gorbachev's
travels in New York City are sending ripples across the Hudson
River, where New Jersey transportation companies fear a massive
stall.
   Henry Atwell, owner of the Kearny-based Schuyler Cab company,
said, ``If the traffic is too bad we won't even take people.
   ``It's not worth the fare to get a car stuck there for three or
four hours. We'll just tell them no and I think they'll understand.''
   About 540,000 people commute from New Jersey to New York City
each day.
   New Jersey Transit bus drivers are setting out from their
terminals a half hour early today and Thursday ``just in case
traffic gets too backed up on the West Side (of Manhattan),'' said
Tracy Munford, a spokeswoman for NJ Transit.
   Peter Farrell, a Wall Street broker and resident of suburban
Millburn, said he was not looking forward to the traffic mess.
   ``It's a lot of extra hassle, but I don't think my commuting
habits will change,'' he said, waiting for the PATH train from
Newark to the World Trade Center. ``There's not much we little
people can do, is there?''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Homeless Say They're Not Welcome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An activist for the homeless says he's been
getting complaints that police are trying to clear the homeless from
parts of Manhattan's East Side, where the Soviet mission is located.
   ``There have been strong activities by police on the East Side to
move homeless people away'' from Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's
temporary residence, said Robert Hayes, counsel to Coalition for the
Homeless.
   Hayes said Tuesday one homeless man told the coalition that he
was approached by a police officer near Grand Central Terminal and
told, ``Go West, young man.''
   Detective Joseph McConville, a police spokesman, responded, ``I
know nothing of that. Why would we be doing that? They have a right
to stay on the East Side, or on the West Side or downtown.''
