<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WWIIPlaneWreck     12-07 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WWII Plane Wreck,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishermen Find Japanese Warplane Wreckage, Pilots' Skeletons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fishermen have found the wreckage of a
World War II Japanese warplane and skeletal remains of its two
crewmen off a coastal village in the southern Philippines, a
Japanese official said today.
   Consul Kaisaku Kawamoto said in a telephone interview from Davao
City that the two-seater fighter plane `Geko' was found Nov. 15
about half a mile east of Talomo village in the province of Davao,
600 miles southeast of Manila.
   Fisherman Mario Calinao, 34, said one of the plane's engines,
radio communications equipment, four machine guns, a 20mm
anti-aircraft gun and revolvers had so far been recovered from the
wreckage.
   Calinao said a Filipino businessman in Davao had offered to pay
him if he could locate and refloat a Japanese warplane.
   ``I got interested in this because I was promised 30,000 pesos
($1,500) if I could refloat any Japanese warplane. I saw this plane.
When my friends learned about it, they offered to help. And since we
all needed the money, I said yes,'' Calinao told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview from the consulate office.
   Calinao said his group lifted the plane from a depth of about 140
feet by using metal drums filled with water. He said rubber hoses
were attached to them and water was pumped out.
   But Calinao said his hopes for new money dimmed because regional
military commander Col. Miguel Abaya had ordered operations to be
suspended and demanded that the objects be turned over to the
military.
   Kawamoto said he had asked the military to permit floating to
resume to enable Japanese embassy officials to identify the pilots.
No response has since been received.
   ``This plane is not Japanese property,'' Kawamoto said, ``I just
want to identify the names (of the pilots) and inform their
relatives and families.''
   He said Calinao brought him an ``old-styled fountain pen'' from
the wreckage with the inscribed name ``Ito.''
</TEXT>
