<1ST_LINE>r a PM-B-52Crash     12-07 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-B-52 Crash,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>B-52s Grounded After Michigan Crash Could Return To Skies Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARQUETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Strategic Air Command lifted its
grounding of its aging fleet of B-52s imposed after the crash of a
bomber during a training flight that sent eight crewmen to the
hospital.
   The cause of early Tuesday's crash at K.I. Sawyer Air Force Base
remained under investigation, said Capt. Paul Bicking, a spokesman
for the SAC base in Michigan's Upper Peninsula.
   Seven of the crewmen remained hospitalized today, four in serious
condition, officials said.
   SAC grounded its fleet of about 260 B-52s as a precaution so
their fuel systems could be inspected. The grounding was lifted
Tuesday night and some of the bombers could be cleared to fly as
early as today, said Lt. Col. George Peck, a spokesman at SAC
headquarters at Offutt Air Force Base in Omaha, Neb.
   Bicking said Sawyer's 20 B-52s would be ready to fly by the end
of the week.
   The B-52 broke into three parts about 1:15 a.m. EST Tuesday
during practice ``touch-and-go'' landings that followed a seven-hour
training flight, said Sgt. Naomi Siegel, a Sawyer spokeswoman. In a
touch-and-go, the plane immediately takes off again rather than
slowing down.
   No weapons were aboard the plane, which is equipped to carry
nuclear bombs, officials said.
   Four crewmen were treated at Marquette General Hospital and three
were transported to the Wright-Patterson Air Force Base Medical
Center in Dayton, Ohio, Bicking said.
   The eighth crewman, 1st Lt. Gregory C. Smith, a 26-year-old
pilot, was released Tuesday from Sawyer's base hospital, Bicking
said.
   Maj. William R. Kroeger, 52, an instructor pilot was in serious
condition with chest injuries, said Marquette General officials.
   Capt. Anthony D. Phillips, 28, a radar navigator; Airman 1st
Class Joseph A. Vallie, 20, a gunner; and 1st Lt. Daniel McCarrick,
25, an electronic warfare officer, were listed as stable, the
hospital said.
   Each crewman transported to Wright-Patterson was listed in
serious condition, said Don Swan, a civilian spokesman. They were:
Capt. Mark Hartney, 29, an aircraft commander; 1st Lt. Michael S.
Debruzzi, 26, a pilot; and 1st Lt. James W. Herrmann, 30, a
navigator.
   Peck said weather apparently was not a factor in the crash. The
National Weather Service said a nearby municipal airport reported
conditions as clear with a temperature of 39 degrees.
   The eight-engine B-52, first deployed in the early 1950s, is the
military's biggest bomber with a wingspan of 185 feet. The last B-52
was commissioned in 1962. The original cost of the aircraft was
$9,955,000, said Capt. Harry Edwards, at SAC headquarters.
   Six crewmen died and 10 were injured Oct. 11 when an Air Force
tanker en route from K.I. Sawyer crashed at Wurtsmith Air Force Base
near Oscoda in Michigan's northeastern Lower Peninsula. The Air
Force's investigation of that crash is incomplete.
   Five of the original 102 B-52s have crashed and one was destroyed
in a ground fire, said Technical Sgt. Alan Dockery, from SAC
headquarters. The most recent crash occurred Oct. 16, 1984, in
Arizona, when a crew practicing low-level flights crashed into a
plateau, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
