<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PearlHarbor     12-07 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pearl Harbor,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Americans Will Remember Pearl Harbor Attack Because of Bush
Faux Pas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Observances scheduled around 12:55 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev should remember Pearl Harbor as they meet in New York,
says a retired Navy captain who survived the Japanese sneak attack
47 years ago today.
   ``I hope they're working for peace as we're remembering war,''
said Forrest Biard, who was to be the keynote speaker at a National
Park Service ceremony marking the Dec. 7, 1941, attack that plunged
the United States into World War II.
   ``We were both on the same side during World War II, but look
what's happened since then,'' the 75-year-old Biard said of the
superpowers. Gorbachev arrived in New York on Tuesday for informal
talks with Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
   Thousands were expected to attend ceremonies across Hawaii today
commemorating the air raid on Hawaiian military installations. The
largest crowds generally gather at Pearl Harbor, which was hardest
hit.
   The Park Service predicted 1,000 people _ sailors past and
present, tourists and history buffs _ would mark the attack at its
ceremony on the harbor shore, and that 5,000 others would attend
special programs and lectures throughout the day.
   More than 2,400 people were killed and 1,200 wounded that Sunday
morning in 1941.
   The Navy planned a private ceremony today aboard the USS Arizona
Memorial, which spans the sunken hull of the battleship as a tribute
to the 1,177 men who went down with the battleship. The Arizona was
one of 21 ships damaged or destroyed in the raid.
   At 7:55 a.m. HST (12:55 p.m. EDT), the moment the first bombs
fell, a moment of silence was to be observed. Then, Hawaii Air
National Guard jets were to fly in the ``missing man'' formation.
   A Navy ship was to pass the memorial, and wreaths and flowers
were to be presented as the national anthem and Navy hymn were
played.
   Remarks by Navy officials were to be followed by prayers, a
21-gun salute and Marine Corps buglers playing ``Taps.''
   Pearl Harbor entered this year's presidential campaign on Sept. 7
when Bush, in a speech to an American Legion meeting in Louisville,
Ky., erroneously reminded veterans that that day was the attack's
anniversary.
   The flub angered many Pearl Harbor survivors, but had a positive
effect, said Dan Martinez, a spokesman at the USS Arizona Memorial.
   ``Unfortunately, so many Americans, especially younger ones, have
forgotten the importance of Pearl Harbor, or never learned it,''
Martinez said. ``So in a way, Mr. Bush's mistake got people to
remember when it really was, and what it really means.
   ``December 7, 1941, is a turning point in history,'' he said,
adding that ``it changed the lives of all Americans, whether they
realize it or not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0649EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Scene     12-07 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Scene,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America's Big Show Plays to Empty House</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle Atlantis
played to an all-but-empty house when it returned from its hush-hush
Defense Department mission, and even its sonic booms seemed quieter
than usual.
   The crowds that have numbered in the hundreds of thousands to
greet previous returning shuttles were forbidden from the base for
Tuesday afternoon's landing on Rogers Dry Lake.
   Only the news media, base workers and 125 invited guests were on
hand, a far cry from the 425,000 that that greeted the shuttle
Discovery when it landed in October.
   The small crowd, some on the roof of NASA's Ames-Dryden Flight
Research Facility building, cheered and clapped, and a minute after
the 3:35 p.m. touchdown the ``Star-Spangled Banner'' blared from
loudspeakers.
   Two booms crackled overhead as Atlantis descended through partly
sunny skies and made its swooping approach.
   ``The sonic boom was not as loud as usual,'' Barbara Selby, a
NASA spoekswoman, told The New York Times.
   For the Oct. 3 landing of Discovery, Vice President George Bush,
who was then in the homestretch of his presidential campaign, rode
out across the dusty clay to greet Discovery's crew. He later
proclaimed them America's new heroes at a red-white-and-blue
ceremony attended by a marching band and famed test pilot Chuck
Yeager.
   Atlantis's five crew members had to make do with greetings from
NASA administrators when they climbed down the stairway from the
orbiter. Instead of a ceremony there was a photo opportunity: A van
pulled up in front of reporters and NASA workers who had waited into
the night and the crew got to say a few words.
   Instead of the vice president they were introduced by the acting
director of the Ames Research Center.
   But that didn't seem to deflate the elation of Atlantis' crew.
   ``It's always great to come visit here and it's especially great
to come visit under these kind of circumstances,'' said Navy Cmdr.
Robert L. Gibson, the mission commander.
   ``Hey, thanks for coming out,'' said Air Force Lt. Col. Guy S.
Gardner as he stepped to the microphone. ``I was stationed here
about 10 years ago and it's great to get another lake bed landing
in. ... We had just a great time and did some good things for our
country.''
   Col. Richard M. Mullane saluted the NASA workers: ``We certainly
do greatly and deeply appreciate the opportunity to ride a rocket
that's supported by such fine people.''
   ``Space flight is something that you can't describe to other
people as hard as we try,'' said Lt. Col. Jerry L. Ross, ``but I
think from the smile that all of us have on our faces you can get a
sense that it was quite an experience.''
   Navy Cmdr. William M. Shepherd agreed.
   ``It's something that leaves you really speechless about trying
to describe it to somebody else,'' he said.
   Though the low-key atmosphere seemed strange it was not
unprecedented.
   The first Department of Defense shuttle mission, designated 51-J
and flown Oct. 3-7, 1985, ended much the same way.
   ``That was probably quieter,'' said Ralph Jackson, a NASA
spokesman at Edwards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
