<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Gorbachev     12-07 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sense Of Loss Expressed Over Reagan's Departure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper, reflecting on the final meeting
of Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan, expressed a sense of
loss today over the departure of the leader who once called the
Soviet Union an ``evil empire.''
   Gorbachev's arrival in New York on Tuesday received front-page
attention in the official press and was broadcast on the morning
television program ``120 Minutes.''
   But because of the eight-hour time difference between Moscow and
New York, Soviets this morning got little more than their
president's arrival statement. Nationwide newspapers printed on
their front pages a picture from Moscow of Gorbachev's departure.
   Gorbachev's speech to the United Nations today was to be shown
live in Moscow, officials of state television said.
   The Soviet leader's gathering shortly afterward with Reagan and
President-elect Bush will be the last of five official meetings
between Gorbachev and the U.S. president.
   Because of his defense build-up and statements labeling the
Soviet Union an ``evil empire,'' the Soviet press portrayed Reagan
in the early years of his presidency as an unstable, missile-toting
cowboy.
   But Yuri Bandura, a columnist for the weekly Moscow News,
expressed ``a feeling somehow close to a feeling of loss'' over the
final Reagan-Gorbachev meeting.
   ``The feeling is more natural if you bring to mind the alarm
caused by Reagan's words and deeds over about half of his
presidency, how dramatically his cooperation with Mikhail Gorbachev
began, and how many long-lost hopes ... were returned to us by the
persistance of these two people in the search for common goals and
movement toward them,'' he wrote.
   Bandura said Reagan, ``least of all for us resembles a kind Uncle
Sam.''
   The Soviet Union has said Gorbachev is hoping during his meeting
with Bush and Reagan to set the groundwork for progress on arms
control issues with the Bush admininstration once it takes office in
January.
</TEXT>
