<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0650EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Cyclone     12-07 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Cyclone,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outbreak Of Water-Borne Disease Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lack of safe drinking water has
triggered an outbreak of water-borne disease in the coastal areas
battered by a cyclone that killed at least 2,200 people, a newspaper
reported today.
   ``The agonies of the cyclone victims have proliferated due to
outbreak of diarrheal diseases,'' said The New Nation, an
independent English-language daily.
   The newspaper did not say how many cases had been reported.
Health Ministry officials could not immediately be reached for
comment.
   The government has said at least 933 people died when the cyclone
roared up the Bay of Bengal on Nov. 29, spawning tidal waves and
lashing 30 of Bangladesh's 64 districts.
   The storm killed another 500 people in neighboring India's West
Bengal state, which abuts Bangladesh, according to officials in
Calcutta.
   The actual number of deaths may never be known because of poor
communications and slow reporting by bureaucrats. The New Nation and
other Dhaka newspapers said at least 2,226 people were killed.
   The Bangladesh Observer said today that another 6,000 people,
most of them fishermen and woodcutters, were still missing. The
newspapers based their figures on reports from officials in the
districts hit by the storm.
   ``Our boats, along with some from local government organizations,
are combing the bay for the missing. But we may abandon the search,
for those in the sea for nine days could not have survived,'' said
an officer at the Titumir naval base in Khulna, 80 miles southwest
of Dhaka.
   The Red Crescent Society, the Islamic equivalent of the Red
Cross, said Sunday at least 1,150 people had died. The organization
has not updated its figures since then.
</TEXT>
