<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     12-07 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patients Allegedly Killed For `Emotional Release'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse's aide suffocated elderly patients
at a nursing home for the ``emotional release'' it brought her, her
alleged accomplice told police, according to court documents.
   Catherine Wood, former nurse's aide supervisor at Alpine Manor
Nursing Home, also told investigators that Gwendolyn Graham killed
six patients in their beds and collected a ``souvenir'' from each,
according to search warrants released this week.
   The women are suspects in the deaths of eight female patients at
the nursing home in this Grand Rapids suburb from January 1987 to
May 1987.
   Wood, 26, was charged Monday with two counts of murder and held
without bond pending a Dec. 16 preliminary hearing.
   Graham, 25, was arrested Sunday near her home in Tyler, Texas,
and arraigned on one count of murder. She was being held on $1
million bond, and was fighting extradition to Michigan.
   Police Chief Walt Sprenger said Tuesday that the six other deaths
were being investigated and that more charges against the women were
likely.
   Under questioning by police Oct. 7, Wood said Graham had told her
``that each of the (six) killings provided an emotional release for
her,'' with the exception of the death of 97-year-old Edith Cook,
who was killed to end her suffering from gangrene, according to the
documents.
   Wood also told police that she and Graham lived together from
September 1986 to July 1987 and were lovers, the documents said.
   Wood told police she witnessed the Jan. 18, 1987, killing of
60-year-old Marguerite Chambers, an Alzheimer's patient.
   She ``observed Gwendolyn Gail Graham suffocating (the patient) by
pressing a washcloth beneath the chin of Chambers and another
washcloth over Chambers' mouth and nose,'' the warrant said. She
told police she did not intervene.
   Wood told police Graham would tell her of the killings either
just before or after they occurred.
   At the time of their deaths, the eight patients were believed to
have died from natural causes and no autopsies were performed.
   Wood, who worked at the home from July 1985 to October 1988, is
charged with killing Cook and Chambers. Graham, who worked at the
home from June 1986 to July 1987, is charged with killing Cook. Both
bodies were exhumed last week, but autopsies have proved
inconclusive.
   Both aides had received good marks from patients and neither was
fired, nursing home officials said.
   Sprenger said he has ruled out mercy killings and financial
profit as motives. He said the women's lesbian relationship was
``part of a complex web that brings the whole thing together,'' but
would not elaborate.
   Wood's ex-husband, Ken Wood sparked the investigation when he
approached police about the deaths last October.
</TEXT>
