<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial     12-07 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Rests at Myerson Trial After Just One Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors took more than 30 days to
present their case against Bess Myerson, but defense lawyers at the
former Miss America's divorce-fixing trial took just one day to make
their point.
   Neither Miss Myerson, the city's former cultural affairs
commissioner and Miss America 1945, nor either of her two
co-defendants testified Tuesday as the defense presented its side.
   The trial will resume Monday when lawyers begin a week of final
arguments to the jury, which could get the case the following week.
   Miss Myerson, 64; her lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43, and
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 75, are charged
with an alleged conspiracy to fix Capasso's divorce.
   Miss Myerson is accused of giving a $19,000 city job to the
judge's daughter in 1983 in exchange for a sharp reduction of
Capasso's temporary support payments to his estranged wife.
   Prosecutors have contended that Miss Myerson, named correspondent
in the divorce by Capasso's wife, Nancy, sought to have the payments
slashed out of greed.
   In his opening statement to the jury 10 weeks ago, Assistant U.S.
Attorney David Lawrence said that Miss Myerson's ``affair of the
heart'' with Capasso ``became an affair of the pocketbook. The gifts
and luxuries that Mr. Capasso previously (had) given to his wife and
his children were now being lavished on Miss Myerson.''
   But Myerson attorney Frederick Hafetz read numerous financial
documents to the jury to show that Miss Myerson had a net worth of
at least $7 million during the period of the alleged conspiracy.
   According to the documents, Miss Myerson, once a television
celebrity and Democratic Senate nomination hopeful, had large sums
invested in Manhattan real estate partnerships and brkerage accounts.
   Capasso lawyer Jay Goldberg introduced documents that showed his
client incurred legal fees of $480,000, backing up his claim that
Capasso wouldn't have spent so much money on lawyers if his divorce
was ``fixed.''
   Former Mayor Robert F. Wagner was among several character witness
who testified on behalf of Mrs. Gabel.
   Asked about the former judge's reputation by defense lawyer
Michael Feldberg, Wagner said it was ``the finest reputation that
anyone could have.''
   Former City Council President Paul O'Dwyer said Mrs. Gabel's
reputation was ``excellent'' and author Robert Caro said she was
kind to him and consented to an interview when New York master
builder Robert Moses, the subject of his Pulitzer prize-winning
biography ``The Power Broker,'' told everyone else in city
government not to cooperate.
   The trial began Oct. 4.
   The prosecution case consisted of 150 exhibits and 34 witnesses,
including Mayor Edward I. Koch and Mrs. Gabel's daughter, Sukhreet.
   All three defendants are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and
other bribe-related charges. If convicted on all counts, they face a
maximum penalty of 25 years in prison and $263,0000 in fines.
   Miss Myerson faces up to five more years if convicted of
obstruction of justice.
</TEXT>
