<DOCNO> AP881207-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan     12-07 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Appointee, 7 Others, File For Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who assumed the
presidency last August after Mohammad Zia ul Haq was killed in a
plane crash, is one of eight candidates to file nomination papers
for the post.
   The presidential election in this nation of 105 million will take
place Monday. The president is elected by Pakistan's Senate,
National Assembly and four legislative assemblies.
   Ishaq Khan, 73, is seeking a full five-year term as president.
His candidacy has the support of both Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto's populist Pakistan People's Party and the rival right-wing
Islamic Democratic Alliance.
   Ms. Bhutto was named prime minister after her party won a
plurality of seats in last month's parliamentary elections.
   Ishaq Khan has served in senior administrative posts for nearly
40 years, including six as minister for finance and commerce. He was
elected chairman of the Senate in 1985, and as the upper chamber's
chairman he assumed the presidency upon Zia's death on Aug. 17.
   Nawbzada Nasrullah Khan, 72, is the second major candidate but
has never been in government. He does, however, have a reputation as
an opposition leader that dates to the 1940s, when the Indian
subcontinent was fighting for independence from Britain.
   Nasrullah Khan was jailed by the British several times. He was
also in jail for several years after Pakistan became a republic in
1956 because of strong views against various governments. He heads
the small right-of-center Pakistan Democratic Party, of which he is
the only member in the National Assembly.
   A third candidate, retired Gen. Tikka Khan, 73, is an old-time
Pakistan People's Party member.
   Ms. Bhutto said in a statement Tuesday that, ``Gen. Tikka Khan's
nomination papers for the office of the president have been filed
only as a cover candidate for President Ghulam Ishaq Khan.''
   By that it means Tikka Khan's name will be withdrawn when Ishaq
Khan's nomination papers receive final approval from the election
commission on Saturday.
   Tikka Khan served as Pakistan's army chief of staff during the
1970s rule of Ms. Bhutto's father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was
overthrown in a 1977 coup and executed nearly two years later.
   Tikka Khan was also commanding general in East Pakistan province,
which broke away in 1971 to established itself as independent
Bangladesh.
   He is known for ordering a brutal military operation against
millions of East Pakistanis in 1970 that fueled separatist
agitation. This agitation was said to have resulted in a
full-fledged war between the Pakistan army and separatists backed by
the Indian Army.
   Ahmed Jaffar, a prominent businessman, also filed his nomination
papers. The other four, relatively unknown, are Mohammed Rafiq
Mohammed, Mohammed Nauroz Malik, Sheikh Mohammed Salim Sethi and Lal
Khan Watti.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
