<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-07 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Brings Cold, Snow into Rockies and Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-pressure system whipped cold Canadian air and snow into
the Rockies and northern Plains early today, and light rain was
scattered along the Pacific Coast and through much of the South.
   Light snow fell from eastern sections of Washington and Oregon
through Montana and Wyoming and into western Colorado and northern
Utah, as well as in the Black Hills of southwestern South Dakota.
   There were no significant accumulations by early morning, but up
to 6 inches were expected at higher elevations near Denver, where a
snow advisory was in effect.
   Patches of light rain continued along the Pacific Coast, and rain
stretched over a large area from north-central Texas to Oklahoma,
northwest Arkansas, central and southern Missouri and western
Kentucky. Thunderstorms developed over southwest Oklahoma and
northwest Texas.
   Dense fog reduced visibility to less than 100 feet in parts of
the San Joaquin Valley in California. Skies were partly cloudy over
the Southwest and the Gulf Coast states and mostly clear in the
Northeast.
   Today's forecast called for snow from Utah to the Rockies and the
central and northern Plains, and in northern Michigan; and scattered
rain in parts of Texas, northern Louisiana, eastern Oklahoma,
Arkansas and southern Missouri.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 20s from the northern and
central Rockies to the Dakotas, Minnesota and northern Michigan; the
30s and 40s from northern New England to the Great Lakes, the middle
Mississippi Valley, the central Plains, southern Rockies, Nevada and
the Pacific Northwest; and in the 70s in Southern California, the
desert Southwest, southern Texas, the Gulf Coast and the south
Atlantic Coast. A few 80-degree readings were expected in extreme
southern Florida and Texas. Elsewhere, highs were expected to be in
the 50s and 60s.
   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 16 degrees at Concord,
N.H., to 73 degrees at Santa Barbara, Calif., and Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 fair; Boston 40 fair; Buffalo 46 windy;
Charleston, S.C. 40 fair; Cincinnati 42 fair; Cleveland 38 fair;
Detroit 34 fair; Miami 72 fair; New York 41 fair; Philadelphia 36
fair; Pittsburgh 43 fair; Portland, Maine 30 fair; Washington 39
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 22 fair; Chicago 34 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 57
partly cloudy; Denver 31 cloudy; Des Moines 32 fair; Indianapolis 40
fair; Kansas City 37 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 30 windy;
Nashville 48 cloudy; New Orleans 48 foggy; St. Louis 50 partly
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 32 partly cloudy; Anchorage 01 fair; Las Vegas
43 fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 56 fair; Salt Lake City 30
snow; San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 52 fair; Seattle 48 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 fair; Toronto 39 fair.
</TEXT>
