<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-07 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major currencies in
nervous European trading early today, buoyed by hopes
President-elect George Bush will act decisively to trim the nation's
budget deficit. Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the market was boosted by a rally that sent the
dollar up sharply in New York trading Tuesday. They said the upward
move was triggered by new hopes Bush is intent on cutting the
massive budget deficit.
   Traders said rumors of a Soviet arms reducation initiative also
propelled the dollar higher. Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev
arrived Tuesday in New York for his final official meeting with
President Reagan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.89 Japanese yen to a closing 122.43 yen. Later, in
London, it rose further to 122.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.7452 West German marks, up from 1.7290
   _1.4663 Swiss francs, up from 1.4480
   _5.9580 French francs, up from 5.9015
   _1.9675 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9470
   _1,289.50 Italian lire, up from 1,277.12
   _1.1925 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1887
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8535 from $1.8675 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $425 a troy ounce, down
from $427.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $425.35.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $425.30, down from $427.75 bid
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.07 to close at a bid $426.66.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.13 a troy
ounce, up from $6.12 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
