<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ITTFraud     12-07 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ITT Fraud,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ITT Fined $200,000 For Guilty Plea In Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ITT Corp. has been fined $200,000 for treating Air
Force officials to golf games, meals and theater tickets to obtain
confidential government information used to bid on $180 million in
military contracts.
   U.S. District Judge David S. Nelson imposed the fine Tuesday on
the New York-based conglomerate, which pleaded guilty in October to
conspiring to defraud the government. ITT had faced a maximum fine
of $500,000.
   ITT admitted an employee in 1984 and 1985 spent about $15,000 and
was reimbursed for illegal gifts to Air Force officials at Hanscom
Air Force Base in Bedford.
   In exchange, ITT received documents with confidential procurement
information on two Air Force programs ITT was interested in
purchasing.
   ``We agreed to plead guilty to one charge of fraud. The
government agreed to drop three other charges,'' said ITT spokesman
James Gallagher.
   ITT was indicted in 1987, several months before a separate
federal investigation began into the use of consultants by
corporations to get information for use in bidding on contracts.
   Edward M. Vincenzi, a senior marketing representative of ITT's
Van Nuys, Calif.-based Gilfillan subsidiary, which specializes in
radar technology, also pleaded guilty to conspiring to defraud and
was placed on probation for a year.
   Vincenzi, who cooperated with federal authorities, had faced up
to 35 years in prison and a $500,000 fine.
   Prosecutors charged that ITT Gilfillan executives tacitly
approved of attempts by Vincenzi to defraud the government and tried
to cover up his activities by destroying or concealing Air Force
documents.
   According to the indictment, Vincenzi was hired in 1983 to pursue
two Air Force contracts _ an anti-radiation missile decoy system
valued at more than $80 million and a mobile air traffic control
radar system worth between $100 million and $150 million.
   Four employees at the Air Force's Electronics Systems Division at
Hanscom who received gratuities from Vincenzi gave him copies of
documents with information on the contracts, as well as general
planning and funding documents.
   ITT won a preliminary $6.4 million development contract for the
missile decoy system, which was never built.
   Vincenzi met with one Hanscom official several times and bought
him lunches, paid for him to play golf and gave him theater and
sports tickets and liquor, the indictment said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PuertoRico-Riot     12-07 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Puerto Rico-Riot,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 Injured In Prison Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS R. VARELA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUAYAMA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five inmates were wounded by gunfire
and eight others were injured during fighting among 400 prisoners in
a maximum-security unit of the Guayama Regional Prison south of San
Juan, police said.
   Hundreds of inmates rioted Tuesday when a gang war broke out at a
penitentiary 51 miles south of San Juan, and police said prisoners
took the warden hostage before surrendering.
   The seven-hour prison takeover ended when the prisoners
surrendered weapons and released their hostage.
   ``They didn't hurt me but at one point I was scared for my
life,'' said the warden, Roberto Sanchez Camareno.
   Department of Corrections administrator Mercedes Otero, who
headed negotiations with the prisoners, said in exchange for the
warden's release prison officials agreed to transfer 130 inmates to
other institutions beginning today.
   Osvaldo Medina Lugo, a leader of the rebellion, said in a
telephone interview, ``We also received assurances that there would
be no reprisals or punishment'' for the prison takeover.
   Inmates surrendered homemade weapons, including knifes, and
returned to their cells, officials said.
   Medina Lugo said the wounded prisoners were shot at by prison
guards during the melee and that inmates had no guns inside the
prison.
   The injured, suffering from gunshot wounds, burns and broken
bones, were treated at local hospitals.
   Rodriguez Fonseca said the rebellion flared at around 3:50 p.m.
(4:50 p.m. EST) when one gang tried to break into the new
maximum-security section of the prison where another gang was being
held.
   He said many inmates went on a rampage during the fighting and
set fire to part of the prison. A wing of the prison appeared gutted.
</TEXT>
