<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Irish     12-07 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Terrorism Act Made Permanent In Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special powers police have used for 14 years to
fight terrorism in Northern Ireland have been made permanent by the
House of Commons.
   The Commons voted 305-45 on Tuesday in favor of the proposed law,
under which Parliament no longer would have to renew the 1974
Prevention of Terrorism Act every year. The act gives police
sweeping powers to detain terrorist suspects without trial for up to
a week and restrict their movements.
   Dissident members of the opposition Labor Party cast all 45 votes
against the measure. Labor Party leaders had ordered their 226
legislators to abstain, rather than vote against the bill.
   The measure was intended mainly to counteract the Irish
Republican Army's guerrilla campaign against British forces in
Northern Ireland.
   It was expected to be approved by the 650-member Commons, where
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party has a 101-seat
majority.
   Later the bill is to be examined by a bipartisan committee. It
was expected to pass all legislative stages without difficulty and
become law next year.
   Before the vote, Mrs. Thatcher told Parliament: ``I can think of
nothing more important to indicate that people are determined in
fighting terrorism.'' ``Not to have the powers of this bill would
enlarge the opportunities for terrorism,'' said Ian Stewart,
minister for Northern Ireland.
   However, opposition legislator Barry Sheerman said every
repressive measure passed by the government was celebrated by
terrorists as a symptom of their success. ``The bill represents
further encroachment on the rights and liberties of all people of
our country and a step further down the tragic path to a less
democratic and less free society,'' Sheerman said.
   The act allows suspected terrorists to be detained without charge
for 48 hours, although the government can extend that for five days,
and to bar suspects in Northern Ireland from entering mainland
Britain.
   On Monday night, the Commons approved a bill that would make all
candidates for local and provincial assembly offices in Northern
Ireland sign a declaration disavowing violence.
   The measure, which passed by a 274-41 vote, was seen as aimed
mainly at Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political arm.
   It will permit the prosecution and possible ouster of council
members who publicly support the IRA's violent campaign to drive the
British government out of Northern Ireland.
   More than 2,700 people have been killed in almost 20 years of
political and sectarian violence in the province.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA aims to unite Protestant-dominated
Northern Ireland with the Catholic Republic of Ireland under
socialist rule.
   Sinn Fein commands about one-third of the Catholic vote in
Northern Ireland and captured about one-tenth of the seats in 17 of
the province's 26 local councils in May 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
