<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Torture     12-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Torture,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Pay Priest To Settle Alleged Torture Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Roman Catholic priest
who says he was tortured by police has announced the matter was
settled out of court for $11,000.
   The Rev. Smangaliso Mkhatshwa said Tuesday that authorities
decided to resolve the ``brutal, shameless and degrading assault''
without a trial to avoid bad publicity.
   Mkhatshwa was secretary-general of the South African Catholic
Bishops' Conference when the alleged assault took place Aug. 21,
1986, after police detained him without charge in Pretoria.
   Mkhatshwa, now secretary-general of the Institute for Contextual
Theology, said police took him to an unknown destination and forced
him to stand blindfolded and handcuffed for about 30 hours while
authorities used an unspecified instrument to hurt his genitals.
   His interrogators repeatedly insulted him and fired shots near
his ears, Mkhatshwa said.
   His allegations were made in a civil damage claim. The attorney
general told Mkhatshwa's lawyers that six men were charged with
criminal injury in the case. One police captain paid a $90 admission
of guilt fine and the other men were absolved of any wrongdoing
without a trial.
   Police did not comment on the case Tuesday.
   The government has paid thousands of dollars in out-of-court
settlements this year to resolve cases of alleged police torture.
Under the arrangement, the government does not admit liability.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying lengths during the 29 month-old state of emergency. About
1,000 people still are in detention.
</TEXT>
