<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Netherlands-Environment     12-07 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Netherlands-Environment,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Containers With Toxic Chemicals Adrift In North Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dutch coast guard today tried
to locate nine containers with dangerous chemicals that have been
adrift in the North Sea since the weekend, a Transport Ministry
spokesman said.
   One is filled with copper oxyde, which is lethal to marine
micro-organisms, according to spokesman Benno Bruggink.
   The containers, which also contain highly flammable chemicals,
were lost Sunday night in a raging storm by the French roll-on
roll-off ferry Aquila. Bruggink said there is no immediate danger of
explosions because the containers are believed to be in good
condition.
   The Aquila, which is owned by the Union Industrielle et Maritime
of Marseille, France, was on its way from West Germany to an
unidentified British port when it lost the containers 37 miles off
the northern Dutch coast, Bruggink said.
   A warning has been issued to all ships in the area, Bruggink said.
</TEXT>
