<2ND_LINE>PM-Switzerland,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Elects Swiss President for 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today elected Economics
Minister Jean-Pascal Delamuraz to the ceremonial post of Swiss
president for 1989.
   Delamuraz will succeed Finance Minister Otto Stich in the
presidency, which rotates annually among the seven members of the
Federal Council, Switzerland's top executive body.
   Justice Minister Elisabeth Kopp, the first woman elected to the
Federal Council, was made vice president, putting her in line for
the presidency in 1990.
   Delamuraz, like Mrs. Kopp a member of the conservative Radical
Democratic party, was elected with a comfortable majority of 201 in
the 246-member Federal Assembly.
   Mrs. Kopp's majority was smaller, 165. Legislators of the Green
and Socialist parties abstained on the vote on Mrs. Kopp, saying
allegations about her husband's business dealings had not been
cleared up.
   Her husband, Hans Kopp, resigned in October from the board of
Shakarchi Trading A.G., a Lebanese-controlled, Zurich-based company
that a Swiss prosecutor says was part of a $1 billion drug money
laundering operation. The company has denied the allegation.
   Kopp has said he was not familiar with the day-to-day business of
the company and rejected suggestions of any wrongdoing. Kopp, a
lawyer, has said he resigned because he had too much other work.
</TEXT>
