<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0929EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Fundamentalists     12-07 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Fundamentalists,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egyptian Police Detain 61 Fundamentalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided the homes of Moslem
fundamentalists at dawn today and rounded up 61 men on suspicion of
plotting sabotage, security sources said.
   They said officers found two incendiary bombs, many knives and
anti-government leaflets in the homes. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The detentions were made under an emergency law enacted after
Moslem extremists assassinated President Anwar Sadat during a
military parade in Cairo on Oct. 6, 1981. Police exercise wide
powers under the law, including detention and search without
warrants. The law also bans strikes and street demonstrations.
   The government blamed Sadat's killing and a subsequent abortive
coup attempt on Jihad, a Moslem extremist group. A nationwide
crackdown on Moslem fundamentalists followed Sadat's assassination,
with thousands detained and hundreds put on trial.
   After being convicted in two trials, five men were executed and
more than 100 received prison terms up to life, which under Egyptian
law is 25 years. Some who received lesser sentences have been
released.
   Fundamentalists want a strict implementation of Sharia, the
Moslem legal and ethical code laid down in the religion's holy book,
the Koran, and in the sayings of the Prophet Mohammed.
   President Hosni Mubarak has said that 90 percent of Egyptian laws
already conform to Sharia.
   Since Sadat's assassination, the government has kept close tabs
on the fundamentalist movement, with a systematic crackdown on those
prone to violence. Officials suspect they are trying to destabilize
the government as a step toward establishing an Iranian-style
religious state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
