<DOCNO> AP881207-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Orbison 6thLd-Writethru a0537 12-07 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Orbison, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0537,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roy Orbison Dead At Age 52</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to ADD that album is No. 8 on the charts
and CORRECT title of song to ``Cryin'''; PICKS UP 11th graf pvs, `In
a ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY22</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSONVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Orbison, a balladeer of lost
love whose piercing, three-octive voice on songs like ``Pretty
Woman'' and ``Cryin''' pioneered early rock 'n' roll, died of a
heart attack at age 52.
   The singer-songwriter, known for his black pompadour and
ever-present sunglasses, was brought by ambulance to Hendersonville
Hospital late Tuesday, said Melanie Lamb, a hospital spokeswoman. He
died just before midnight.
   Orbison achieved fame more than two decades ago with the hits
``Only the Lonely,'' his first million-seller, then ``Blue Angel''
and ``I'm Hurtin.''' ``Oh, Pretty Woman,'' in 1964, sold more than 7
million copies, and was recently a hit for the group Van Halen.
   At his death, he was again on the charts, with the single
``Handle With Care,'' a collaboration with artists including Bob
Dylan, George Harrison and Tom Petty. Their album, recorded under
the name The Traveling Wilburys, is No. 8 on the charts.
   Orbison, who played guitar, gave a concert Sunday in Akron, Ohio,
before 2,000 people. On Tuesday, Orbison was at the Nashville-area
home of country singer Jean Shepard, who said he had been with her
husband, ``having a great time.''
   During his heyday in the early 1960s, Orbison had 27 straight
records on the charts. In May 1963, he toured Britain with the
Beatles, then a smash in England but still virtually unknown in the
United States.
   In 1977, Elvis Presley introduced him as ``the greatest singer in
the world.'' Bruce Springsteen saluted him in his song ``Thunder
Road.''
   Orbison once estimated he had sold 30 million records, but added,
``I don't normally keep tabs.''
   Some of his other hits include ``Cryin,''' ``It's Over,'' and
``Blue Bayou.'' Last year, he re-recorded his 1963 hit ``In Dreams''
after the song had been revived in the movie ``Blue Velvet.''
   In a 1986 Associated Press interview, Orbison said the biggest
thrill in his career was ``just being in the business itself.''
   As for being called a legend, he said: ``I did say facetiously
once that being a legend meant being old. But someone pointed out
that not all old people are legends. Anyway, it's nice to have had
longevity and to have influenced a few people for the good.''
   On Sept. 30, 1987, Orbison gave a concert at Los Angeles' Coconut
Grove nightclub, called ``Roy Orbison and Friends: A Black-and-White
Night.'' The friends were Springsteen, Elvis Costello, Jackson
Browne, Tom Waits, T-Bone Burnett and J.D. Souther, with Bonnie
Rait, Jennifer Warnes and K.D. Lang singing backup. The concert was
taped for a cable television special.
   In 1980, Orbison teamed with Emmylou Harris on the duet, ``That
Loving You Feeling Again,'' and earned a Grammy award. He also was
inducted into the Rock 'n' Roll Hall of Fame and the Hall of Fame of
the Nashville Songwriters Association.
   Orbison grew up in Wink, Texas, and was taught to play guitar at
age 6 by his father, an oil field worker. He played guitar on a
radio station at age 8 and was in a country music band by age 14.
   He got his early recording experience in the 1950s with Sun
Records of Memphis, the company that launched the careers of
Presley, Johnny Cash and Jerry Lee Lewis.
   He was one of the first ``rockabilly'' singers _ a hybrid of rock
'n' roll and hillbilly music, as country music was known then.
   Orbison began wearing sunglasses publicly all the time in 1963
when he accidentally left his regular glasses at home and had to
wear shades while in London. His appearance was well-received and he
kept it a tradition.
   His career plummeted in the late 1960s in the aftermath of two
personal tragedies. His wife died in a motorcycle accident in 1966.
Two of his three sons, ages 10 and 6, died in a fire that destroyed
his $150,000 lakeside home in 1968. His third son is now in his
twenties.
   His most successful songs focused on broken romance and his ``Too
Soon to Know'' was written after the death of his wife. ``A little
hurt went a long way,'' he said in the 1986 interview.
   Orbison remarried and had two sons from that marriage.
   Asked in the 1986 interview how he would like to be remembered,
he replied:
   ``One day when they are mentioning people who had an impact, if
they just mention me among the rest of the guys and gals, it would
be great.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     12-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 90 Guerrilla Groups Uncovered In Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister announced today that
Israel's security forces have uncovered 93 guerrilla groups and
arrested more than 600 people believed responsible for scores of
anti-Israeli attacks.
   The groups included a 13-member squad of Israeli Arabs uncovered
Tuesday in the coastal city of Haifa that police blamed for a
grenade attack there in August in which 25 civilians were injured.
   Two of those arrested in Haifa were Bedouin soldiers in the
Israeli army. Police said they suspect the squad planned to kidnap
and kill other soldiers. Bedouins and Druse are the only Arabs
allowed to serve in Israel's army.
   The security operation could help the Israeli army reduce
violence in the occupied lands where Palestinians, led by
underground groups, have been waging an uprising against Israeli
rule. Since the uprising began last December, 319 Palestinians and
11 Israelis have been killed.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin praised Israel's security forces
for uncovering the guerrilla groups believed responsible for 87
anti-Israeli attacks in the past year. He made the comment in a
letter to the head of the Shin Bet security agency.
   Twenty-nine of the guerrilla groups named have been linked to the
Fatah faction of the PLO headed by Yasser Arafat, a Defense Ministry
statement said. Forty-nine were described as locally organized.
   The statement put the number of arrests at 610, including 310 in
the West Bank, 283 in the Gaza Strip and 17 in Israel.
   ``These numbers speak for themselves, your success merits great
praise,'' Rabin said in his letter, according to the ministry
statement. ``The security services conduct their hard work behind a
screen of secrecy and only rarely do their members win gratitude and
praise.''
   ``I see you doing your daily work in the alleys of Nablus,
through Tulkarem, the streets of Gaza and Khan Yunis. I am watching
your efforts made with daring, determination and courage,'' Rabin
said.
   Among the attacks attributed to the groups is an Oct. 31 firebomb
assault on an Israeli passenger bus in the West Bank city of Jericho
that killed a woman and three of her children, the statement said.
   Other attacks include the slayings of at least three Palestinians
accused of collaborating with Israeli authorities.
   Some detainees surrendered weapons, including 16 grenades, 14
pistols, seven rifles, six machine guns and explosives, the
statement said.
   The 13 Israeli Arabs, whose arrests were announced Tuesday, are
among those mentioned by the statement. This group is suspected of
involvement in an Aug. 20 grenade attack in northern Israel in which
an Israeli boy lost a foot and 24 other people were wounded, the
statement said.
   Police said the suspects belonged to Fatah, and that their
leader, identified in news reports as 21-year-old Samir Sarsawi,
joined the Palestine Liberation Organization group while visiting
Egypt a year ago.
   In the occupied territories today, soldiers shot and wounded six
Palestinian teen-agers during at least two confrontations with
stone-throwing demonstrators in the Gaza Strip, hospital officials
said.
   Troops also clamped a curfew on the commercial center of the West
Bank city of Ramallah and detained about 200 Palestinians after a
firebomb was thrown at an Israeli patrol, Arab news reports said.
   In the hills surrounding Kfar Malik near Ramallah, soldiers blew
up caves used as hideouts by Palestinian youths fleeing arrest, news
reports said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
