<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Layoffs     12-07 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Layoffs,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One-Fourth Of China's Construction Workers Could Lose Their Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-fourth of China's 24 million construction
workers could lose their jobs next year because of a
government-ordered halt to thousands of building projects, the
official Xinhua News Agency said today.
   The agency quoted Zhang Qinglin, director of the government's
Construction Management Bureau, as saying construction companies
should start finding alternate jobs for their workers.
   In late September, the government ordered a halt to construction
of all hotels, office buildings, stadiums and other projects that
were not part of the five-year economic plan. Only construction of
projects that are more than half-completed is being allowed to
continue.
   The measure is part of an economic package designed to reduce
inflationary borrowing and control economic growth. The October
inflation rate was 26 percent higher than in the corresponding month
of 1987, and officials have said prices are expected to keep rising
this month.
   Provinces and cities nationwide have canceled thousands of
projects in the past two months, including many that have already
been started. The Beijing municipal government said it was ending or
suspending 60 projects worth a total of $429,000. The prosperous
commercial city of Canton canceled the construction of 66 hotels,
restaurants and office projects valued at $456,000.
   A leading construction company in Beijing said it has found new
jobs for all its laid-off workers. However, Xinhua quoted Zhang as
saying the job situation will become critical after March, when many
projects are to be completed.
</TEXT>
