<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Orbison     12-07 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Orbison,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paul McCartney Pays Tribute to Roy Orbison</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Orbison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Beatle Paul McCartney, whose rock group
stole the limelight from Roy Orbison during a 1963 tour of Britain,
said today the singer-songwriter was ``one of the greats of rock 'n'
roll.''
   When the Beatles opened their national tour on May 18, 1963,
Orbison topped the bill. But by the end of the 21-concert itinerary,
the ballad-singing Texan had been eclipsed by the Fab Four.
   Orbison died of a heart attack aged 52 in Hendersonville, Tenn.,
on Tuesday night.
   McCartney said in a statement released by his publicist that
Orbison's death ``is a great shock.''
   ``We toured with Roy in the early days and he was a really good
guy,'' the 46-year-old McCartney said. ``It is particularly sad when
he seemed to be enjoying such a comeback recently.
   ``He was and always will be one of the greats of rock 'n' roll,''
he said.
   Orbison traveled to Britain last month to promote an album
compilation of his hit songs and an album he made with former Beatle
George Harrison, singers Bob Dylan, Tom Petty and others, under the
name ``The Traveling Wilburys.''
   Orbison told reporters on his departure from London's Heathrow
Airport on Nov. 30 he was surprised at the recent upturn in his
career.
   ``I've been taken aback by the way things are going,'' Orbison
said.
   ``I've been rediscovered by young kids who had never heard of me
before the Wilburys,'' he said. ``They are getting into my original
songs and apparently the old stuff is selling at the rate of 20,000
copies a day.''
   ``It's very nice to be wanted again but I still can't quite
believe it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
