<1ST_LINE>r w PM-O'Neill-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0545 12-07 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Neill-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>O'Neill Rejected Irish Envoy Offer; Cited Wife's Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush offered former
House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill the job of ambassador to Ireland, a
post in which the Massachusetts Democrat once expressed an interest,
but O'Neill turned it down for personal reasons, a Bush aide
confirmed today.
   Transition press secretary Sheila Tate said that Bush was
disappointed O'Neill declined the offer, made during a private
meeting Friday, because the vice president felt O'Neill ``would have
been a wonderful ambassador.''
   The offer was first reported in today's editions of the Boston
Globe.
   Ms. Tate confirmed the accuracy of the account, saying, ``The
vice president did indeed offer the ambassadorship to Tip O'Neill.''
   The post is held by Margaret Heckler, a former congresswoman from
Massachusetts.
   O'Neill, 76, told the newspaper that he met with Bush and his
wife, Barbara, but did not discuss details of the session.
   One factor in O'Neill's decision was the health of his wife,
Millie, the Globe said. O'Neill told the newspaper Tuesday that she
was suffering from pneumonia.
   Ms. Tate said O'Neill ``felt, apparently quite regrettably, that
he would be unable to serve because of concern for his wife.''
   When O'Neill left office in 1986, he told reporters that the only
other government service he might consider would be the job of
ambassador to Ireland, suggesting it was a post he had often thought
of fondly.
   However, when President Reagan mentioned press speculation over
such an appointment, O'Neill jokingly replied:
   ``What? And have your picture on the wall of my office? No way.''
</TEXT>
