<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Thatcher     12-07 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Thatcher,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Office Suspends Official for Criticizing Thatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office said it suspended a second
secretary today for criticizing Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in
a letter published in The Guardian newspaper.
   Patrick J. Haseldine, who has served in France and West Africa,
is likely to face severe disciplinary action for breaching civil
service strictures against expressing political opinions.
   He accused Mrs. Thatcher of ``self-righteous invective'' in
attacks on Belgium and Ireland for their failure to extradite an
Irish priest suspected of terrorism.
   The letter also charged Mrs. Thatcher connived to let four white
South Africans suspected of arms smuggling go free in 1984.
   ``It is all very well for Mrs. Thatcher to inveigh against the
Belgians and the Irish with such self-righteous invective,'' the
letter said. ``In the not too distant past her allegations of being
soft on terrorism and allowing political considerations to override
the due legal process could have been leveled against Mrs. Thatcher
herself.''
   It cited the case of the four South Africans who were granted
$540,000 bail by a magistrate in Coventry, central England, and
allowed to return to South Africa.
   The South African government, which provided the bail, refused to
send them back and forfeited the money.
   ``Mrs. Thatcher failed to denounce Mr. Botha's refusal to
surrender the four,'' the letter added.
   The Foreign Office said Haseldine has been suspended pending an
investigation.
   Mrs. Thatcher has accused the Belgian and Irish governments of
failing to live up to anti-terrorist declarations over the
extradition of the priest, the Rev. Patrick Ryan. British police
suspect him of involvement in Irish Republican Army bombings.
   Belgium, where Ryan was arrested last summer, refused a British
extradition request this month and sent him to the Republic of
Ireland, which says it is still considering the issue.
</TEXT>
