<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeputyKilled     12-07 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deputy Killed,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Stressed Out' Sheriff's Deputy Shot To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREAUX BRIDGE La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy suspected of making
threatening telephone calls to state troopers and taking potshots at
law officers was shot to death after daring authorities to try to
capture her, officials said.
   Elizabeth Laperouse, 22, of St. Martinville, a dispatcher for the
St. Martin Parish Sheriff's Office, was gunned down Tuesday night on
a desolate road near the Atchafalaya Swamp, said State Police
spokesman Lt. Ronnie Jones.
   ``Investigators were told last night that when she came to work
yesterday, she was acting somewhat irrationally,'' Jones said. ``I
think the words they used were `stressed out.'''
   The woman was told to go home, and superiors took her pistol from
her, but she apparently got another from a friend, Jones said.
   The woman apparently called a State Police post in Lafayette and
warned, ``I'm across the street, and I'm going to shoot the first
trooper who comes out of the building,'' Jones said.
   The woman fired at a trooper and another officer leaving the
building, Jones said. Neither was hurt. Shen then sped off in a car,
the lieutenant said.
   About an hour later, the caller asked, ``Did you hear the
shots?'' gave a highway location and added, ``I dare any trooper to
try to stop me,'' Jones said.
   State police pursued the car onto an empty stretch of road, where
she stopped and jumped from her car, Jones said.
   ``After being told to drop her weapon, she began to make
offensive moves, and two shots were fired, one striking her in the
head,'' Jones said.
   He said investigators determined that State Police acted properly.
</TEXT>
