<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   12-07 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0663</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Dec 6
   The Indianapolis Star on the B-2 bomber:
   The Air Force's new B-2 stealth bomber may be a technological
military wonder, but it costs too much.
   The sophisticated plane, 10 years in development, is intended for
attacks on the Soviet mobile-missile force. Its radar-proof design
is intended to enable it to penetrate far into Soviet airspace, and
find and destroy missile-launchers.
   However, the technology it is supposed to use to find the
missiles does not yet exist.
   The price of a single B-2 is more than $500 million. The cost of
a fleet of 132 B-2s and their base equipment is reportedly $57
billion. ...
   This is an astronomic price _ unduly high considering that huge
fleets of advanced cruise missiles would probably be able to perform
the same kind of mission at a fraction of the cost.
   We hope that the Bush administration and the new Congress will
give the B-2 program a long, hard look.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 6
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on political campaigns:
   As the echoes of blistering invective from the campaign continue
to fade, President-elect George Bush has made a wide-ranging effort
at mending fences, indicating he may really plan to be president of
all the people.
   If his round of conciliatory post-election meetings is a
harbinger of his behavior after Inauguration Day, the Bush
administration could bring some welcome surprises. ...
   It's easy to be gracious in victory, of course, and ... Bush
should not think that his program of outreach will entirely erase
the memory of his bitter attacks on his opponents during the
ill-tempered campaign.
   But if he can follow the symbolic meetings he has had in recent
days with substantive action, perhaps a kinder and gentler
administration will take root in Washington after all.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 6
   The Miami News on U.S.-Cuba relations:
   U.S. Sen. Claiborne Pell, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, called for the normalization of U.S.-Cuba
relations after returning from a five-day trip to the island at the
end of last month.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev will meet with Cuban boss Fidel
Castro this weekend in Havana where they will discuss normalizing
Soviet-Cuban relations.
   Now that we have everyone's attention, the Pell and Gorbachev
visits deserve a harder look because they are related.
   The Democratic senator from Rhode Island is serious about
breaking down the barriers between Cuba and the United States, about
restoring diplomatic relations between the two countries, and
debating whether to lift the trade embargo which can be more
official than real, and sometimes paper-thin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 5
   St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch on Iran-Contra:
   President Reagan last week wisely rejected pardons for either
Oliver North or John Poindexter, the key defendants in the
Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages case. The president has ... praised
them for their ``patriotism'' and said he believes the justice
system will exonerate them.
   Yet his subsequent action belies that belief. In one breath, he
ruled out pardons; in another, he blocked the progress of a fair
trial.
   The president refused to disclose information about the case that
... North says he needs to build his defense. The White House,
(Reagan) said, has a ``duty'' to protect ``state secrets of the
highest order.''
   But withholding that sensitive material could result in dismissal
of the conspiracy charges. Should that happen, the public will never
know whether crimes were committed. Justice would not be served.
   The president denies that he is attempting a ``back door''
approach to pardoning the principals in the scandal, but it has the
same effect. It appears that ... Reagan's goal is to clear the men,
but avoid taking direct responsibility.
   Americans should not be fooled by such subterfuge.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
