<DOCNO> AP881207-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan-Convoy     12-07 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Convoy,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Food Convoy, 7 People Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A land mine explosion and repeated attacks
by rebels killed seven people on a truck convoy carrying food to the
southern Sudan town of Juba, a U.N. official said today.
   The attacks in the jungles north of the Uganda border came
despite the signing of a peace agreement last month between the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army and a party in Sudan's
governing coalition.
   Planes flying with safety guarantees from both sides were not
attacked as they carried supplies to starving civilians in
government-held and rebel-controlled towns for a fourth day.
   The south's 6 million civilians have been the main victims of the
civil war. Relief officials said today that new information leads
them to believe that at least 500,000 people have died this year.
   Most perished while trying to flee the battle zone for safety or
food because the war has driven them from their agricultural lands.
Previous estimates had put the year's civilian death toll at 260,000.
   The U.N. official, in daily radio contact with Juba, 750 miles
south of Khartoum, said the civilian convoy of 25 to 30 trucks left
Yei, 100 miles southwest of Juba, on Thursday.
   Except for a few U.N. trucks, it carried food owned by merchants,
not relief supplies, he said. Despite an army escort, the trucks
``encountered five, maybe six, ambushes by the SPLA,'' he said on
condition of anonymity.
   He said three civilians and a soldier died in the attacks, which
were carried out with automatic weapons and rocket-propelled
grenades. He said three other civilians died and 14 were wounded
later when a truck hit a land mine.All the victims were Sudanese.
   ``As far as we can tell, the food remains intact,'' the official
said. ``Our offices also have a few trucks carrying supplies to
Juba, which are OK.
   ``This morning they were 44 miles away from Juba. This is a
100-mile journey, which should take five hours, but it takes ages
because they move at a walking pace to let men with manual mine
detectors proceed in front of them.''
   The attacks came as the government assembled a delegation to send
to Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, to meet with renegade Col. John Garang,
the rebel leader.
   He organized his rebellion in 1983 to press for a better
economic, political and administrative deal for the non-Moslem
majority in southern Sudan. The Moslem-dominated central government
imposed Islamic law six months later, which exacerbated the war.
</TEXT>
