<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BugAccident     12-07 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bug Accident,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Motorist Bugged By Insect Wasn't In Emergency Situation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist's excuse that he was bugged by an
insect moments before his car collided with a tractor just won't
fly, an appeals court ruled in ordering a new trial in a lawsuit
against him.
   A jury had decided Verryl Bunnell was not negligent in the 1986
accident that fractured the knee of 22-year-old Rose M. Garceau, and
it awarded Garceau $118,500 in damages. Garceau, who had asked for
$200,000, sought a new trial.
   Bunnell contended that an insect flew into his car and struck his
cheek as he approached a rise in the highway. As he swatted the
insect, he said, he drove his car into the opposite lane and struck
the tractor operated by Garceau.
   But an appeals court Tuesday said, ``Bunnell's testimony fails to
support a finding that a bug striking his cheek leaving his vision
unobstructed creates a danger.''
   Even if Bunnell was stung by the bug, the court said, he was
never placed in an emergency situation.
</TEXT>
