<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Mitchell-Homecoming     12-07 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mitchell-Homecoming,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Majority Leader To Visit Tiny Town That Backed His Opponent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN O'QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERVILLE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiny Talmadge, the only one of Maine's
672 voting precincts to reject U.S. Sen. George J. Mitchell in the
Nov. 8 election, will get a visit this week from the new Senate
majority leader.
   Mitchell, who returned in triumph Tuesday to his hometown of
Waterville, plans to spend the rest of the week in Maine. He plans a
stop Thursday in Talmadge, the Washington County community that
voted 18-12 for Republican Jasper Wyman in the Senate race in which
Mitchell swept 81 percent of the vote.
   Mitchell, a Democrat appointed to the Senate in 1980 and elected
in 1982, wrote letters to Talmadge residents and plans to meet them
in the basement of the Bethel Chapel, said Town Clerk Gail Thornton.
   ``He just wants to know anything that's on their mind, anything
that bothered them that he didn't do,'' she said. The town has 36
registered voters, many of them elderly Republicans.
   At his first stop, Mitchell was cheered by relatives and friends,
many of whom have known him since his childhood in Waterville's Head
of Falls neighborhood across the Kennebec River from City Hall.
   ``This is a very moving moment for me,'' he told more than 100
well-wishers who jammed the lobby of City Hall.
   After brief remarks, the senator was presented with a white
T-shirt that read, ``From Head of the Falls to Head of the Senate.''
   Mitchell, 55, defeated fellow Democratic Sens. J. Bennett
Johnston of Louisiana and Daniel K. Inouye of Hawaii to win the
powerful majority leader's post last week.
   Former Sen. Margaret Chase Smith, the 90-year-old matriarch of
Maine's Republican Party, joined Mitchell on the podium in the lobby
and praised his integrity.
   ``He gives you the feeling of being direct and honest. That's a
great asset for a politician,'' she said.
</TEXT>
