<HEAD>Chemical Pollution Flows From Romania to Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pollutants from a chemical plant leaked
into a Romanian river that flows into a waterway in southern
Hungary, the state news agency reported.
   The pollutants in the Maros River, which flows into the Tisza
River, came from a plant about 30 miles east of the Hungarian
border, the agency MTI said.
   The Lower Tisza Environmental Protection and Water Management
Directorate has declared an alert for the Hungarian section of the
Maros, the report said.
   In July, chemical waste in the Szamos River in Romania flowed
into Hungary, killing thousands of fish. Romanian officials denied
they were aware of the pollution on their side of the border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
