<HEAD>Soviet TV Carried Gorbachev Address Live</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's United Nations
speech Wednesday was carried live on Soviet radio and TV, with an
announcer saying delegates gave him an ovation that was unlike any
other in memory.
   ``The professional quality of those sitting at the delegation
tables dictates restraining a display of feeling, the stormy
expression of which is just not acceptable here,'' a TV announcer
said after Gorbachev's speech, the first at the world body by a
Soviet leader since Nikita S. Khrushchev in 1960.
   ``But such a reaction which you the television viewers witnessed
is difficult to recall,'' the announcer said, in explaining the
delegates' response.
</TEXT>
