<DOCNO> AP881207-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1349EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Protest     12-07 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Protest,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protester Sits on Utility Pole 24 Hours For `Democracy'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man perched on a utility pole in western
Poland for 24 hours displaying a banner that demanded democracy,
then ended his protest peacefully Wednesday, the opposition and the
state media reported.
   According to the Solidarity Information Service, Robert Korcz
climbed the approximately 30-yard-tall pole in Gorzow Wielkopolski
at noon Tuesday and climbed down at noon Wednesday.
   He displayed two banners saying, ``I, Korcz, Demand Democracy in
the PRL'' and ``I, Korcz, Demand Justice in the PRL,'' said
Solidarity spokesman Robert Maziarski. PRL in Polish stands for the
Polish People's Republic.
   Solidarity said the pole was surrounded by police and
sympathizers were barred from giving Korcz food or water.
   The state-run PAP news agency said Korcz, 23, returned home after
the protest.
   According to Maziarski, Korcz said he had been released Nov. 1
after being jailed 1{ years for reporting late for civil militia
duty and for disobeying orders. He said Korcz's protest was to call
attention to alleged mistreatment in prison.
   Gorzow Wielkopolski is about 30 miles east of the East German
border.
</TEXT>
