<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Island Welcome,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Islanders Give World Leaders Small Town Welcome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0669 to fix slugline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors Island, a rocky outcrop with a closeup
view of Manhattan's skyline and the Statue of Liberty, gave a
small-town welcome Wednesday to the leaders of the world's two
mightiest nations who came for lunch.
   School kids got the day off, the golf course was turned into a
helicopter landing pad, and 22,000 trash bags full of fallen leaves
were carted away in preparation for the meeting.
   ``Feelings run a range anywhere from gross inconvenience to
having a place in history,'' said Tom Brodksy, a Coast Guard petty
officer reporting for morning duty.
   The 173-acre speck in the nation's busiest harbor is reachable by
a seven-minute ferry ride from the city, where the glass and
concrete of the World Trade Center and Wall Street tower as citadels
of capitalism.
   Once an Army fortress, Governors Island has been a U.S. Coast
Guard base since 1966 and is home to 3,500 military personnel and
their families. It's open to the public for tours only two days a
year.
   On Wednesday, a sign rimmed by red poinsettias just off the ferry
read: ``Coast Guard Welcomes President Reagan, Chairman Gorbachev
and Vice President Bush.''
   Having the three most powerful men in the world over for lunch
meant disruptions like closing the elementary school, P.S. 26, and
allowing presidential helicopters to land on the nine-hole golf
course, which is used as a military parade field when officers
aren't chipping and putting.
   Eric Fields, 14, shot baskets outside with a chum before all
residents were asked to go inside at 10 a.m. for security purposes.
   ``Gorbachev's coming to say goodbye to Reagan and hello to Bush.
We get the day off, and we might have a better chance at being
friends,'' Fields said.
   Satellite dishes ringed the gymnasium, which was converted into a
giant media center with rows of tables and telephones under
basketball hoops. The Boy Scout sale of Christmas trees was shut
down for the day.
   Coast Guard Lt. Nicholas Dujmovic, said everybody below the rank
of 1st class petty officer helped clean up in preparation for the
visit, including the picking up of dead leaves all over the island.
   Louis Diaz, who runs a delilunch. But he made the most of free
enterprise, fixing sandwiches in the back of his station wagon and
hustling them for $4 to the media from a folding table under a tree.
   ``They were going to make me close. I'd lose money like that,''
said Diaz, tossing ham and cheese onto bagel rolls. ``I got to make
my money.''
   Diaz also said he had ``plenty of Russian dressing.''
</TEXT>
