<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Church     12-07 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Church,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church, Leftist Groups Compete In Celebrating Nicaraguan Holiday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist government and the Roman
Catholic Church are at odds, but both are taking the day off
Thursday to celebrate the religious feast of the Immaculate
Conception of the Virgin Mary.
   It's one of the nation's most important holidays, celebrating the
Roman Catholic belief that Mary was conceived without original sin.
   Traditionally, Nicaraguans take to the streets the eve of the
feast, visiting altars erected in front of homes and chanting hymns
of praise. Owners of a home where the altar is erected distribute
candy, fruit and toys and offer pastries and cocoa drinks to
visitors who go on to other altars for additional goodies.
   Fireworks explode through the night and groups meet each other
chanting: ``What causes so much happiness? Mary's Immaculate
Conception.''
   The chants and celebration are known as the ``Griteria,'' or
``the Shouting.''
   The Roman Catholic Church has celebrated the feast for centuries
and the Sandinista government, accused by the church of following a
Marxist ideology, has yielded to popular tradition.
   Devotion to the Virgin Mary, rooted in the soul of Catholic
Spain, is common in the Spanish-speaking countries, notably among
them Mexico and its patron saint, the Virgin of Guadalupe.
   The Nicaraguan Church says the government is trying to capitalize
on the people's religiosity for its own political ends.
   ``They try to take the religious aspect away to concentrate more
on the giving of candy, bread and sugar cane and the secular
celebrations,'' said Monsignor Bismarck Carballo, director of the
Catholic Radio Station.
   The church encourages the faithful to celebrate the old way with
neighborhood altars and gatherings.
   Government officials including President Daniel Ortega, who has
called Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo a reactionary and a
counterrevolutionary, visit altars built by government agencies and
join in celebrating and distributing gifts.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge, a critic of the Church and its
hierarchy, has said that ``as long as there is a revolution there
will be a celebration of the Immaculate Conception.''
   Government newspapers filled pages this week with interviews with
old Managua residents who recalled the folkloric celebrations of the
early century in a bucolic Managua that had not yet heard of
revolution.
   Chico Gurdian, 75, told the newspaper Barricada that after the
religious celebration in the old days, ``We turned the (statue of)
Virgin around so she would not see and everybody started dancing.''
   On Wednesday, soldiers in blue berets were busy building the
Sandinista Army's altar just off a wide avenue lined by eucalyptus
trees. Behind the Virgin was a large painting showing Nicaraguan
mountains with army helicopoters flying over them.
   Another government agency built an altar that bore the sign,
``Mary, energy for reconstruction.''
   Religious or political, the feast is a brief respite in a country
hard hit by civil war, a hurricane, runaway inflation and low wages.
A few blocks from the altars, a store advertised simple two-slice
toasters for $60 _ more than a secretary earns in a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0136 </DOCNO>
