<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Summit-FirstLadies 3rdLd-Writethru a0608 12-07 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-First Ladies, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0608,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush Keeps Mood Light at Raisa-Nancy Lunch</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with luncheon gathering. Picks
up 9th graf pvs, bgng: `Mrs. Gorbachev'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush took charge at an exclusive U.N.
luncheon today for Raisa Gorbachev and Nancy Reagan, putting
everyone at ease with her good humor and jokes.
   ``How do you say `cheese' in Russian?'' Mrs. Bush, the wife of
President-elect George Bush, quipped as the three women stood for a
formal picture with Marcela Perez de Cuellar at her posh East Side
townhouse.
   Mrs. Bush, standing next to the Soviet first lady, seemed intent
on defusing any problems at the gathering, the last for the U.S. and
Soviet first ladies, who have had their run-ins on previous
occasions.
   As the translator interpreted the word ``cheese'' for Mrs.
Gobachev and Mrs. Bush, the group broke out in smiles and laughter.
   As photographers encouraged the women to smile, Mrs. Gorbachev
said, ``We can't see you. That's why we don't smile.''
   The women posed for their portrait prior to joining 20 other
women at an elegant luncheon downstairs in a room with a marble
fireplace, crystal chandelier and tall windows overlooking the East
River. Each place was set with crystal bearing the U.N. insignia and
at every place setting lay a small present wrapped in a peach bow.
   Mrs. Gorbachev spoke through an interpreter inside the town house
but outside had responded to reporters' entreaties to speak with
them and spoke partially in English.
   ``I'm happy to be here in this city you call `The Big Apple,'''
she told reporters, saying the words the big apple in English.
   The Soviet first lady was expected to continue her sightseeing in
New York with a vist to the Estee Lauder cosmetic headquarters and
an automobile tour of Manhattan with her husband, who had lunch at
Governors Island with President Reagan and Bush.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Reagan pooh-poohed reports that she and Mrs.
Gorbachev had feuded in the past. She said she intended to wish the
Soviet first lady _ an avowed Marxist-Leninist and atheist _ a merry
Christmas.
   During a tour of the U.N. earlier today, Mrs. Gorbachev, dressed
in a sober grey suit with an aqua blouse, strolled with Mrs. Perez
de Cuellar through the modern glass and steel building, pausing to
chat repeatedly and look at many of its international artworks. Mrs.
Perez de Cuellar, attired in a green and black Harlequin-like suit
ruffled at neck and cuff, explained several of the works that have
been donated to the international organization by member nations.
   Mrs. Gorbachev noted that the Soviets intended to donate a bronze
sculpture later in the day.
   She viewed a tapestry reproduction of Picasso's famed artwork of
the Spanish civil war bombing of a village, ``Guernica,'' and used
the occasion to say the Soviet Union is interested in peaceful
endeavors.
   Listening to an explanation of how the tapestry was made, Mrs.
Gorbachev said, ``It also symbolizes the terror of war.''
   Pausing at one point to greet about 150 U.N. workers, she said
through a translator, ``I wish you every success in your work. You
work in an organization that makes great contributions to the cause
of peace.''
   ``We like you,'' someone called out from the crowd, a comment met
by smiles on the part of Mrs. Gorbachev and her hostess, as well as
applause from the assemblage.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Reagan said she hoped Mrs. Gorbachev would have
a good time in New York, which is decked out for the holiday season.
   As to talk of a feud, she said, ``I think there's been too much
attention paid to it. I do. I really do.''
   Asked whether they were really ``on the same wave length,'' Mrs.
Reagan replied, ``Oh, of course not.'' And asked if they shared
similar philosophies, she answered,``Of course not, that's a given.''
   At their last meeting in Moscow, Mrs. Reagan had made repeated
attempts to discuss the religious implications of the icon artworks
that she saw, while Mrs. Gorbachev chose to discuss their
sociological or historical importance.
   The two women ended the Moscow summit last spring contesting for
time with reporters at an icon gallery.
   The two first ladies have come together 16 times according to a
count kept by Mrs. Reagan's press secretary Elaine Crispen. Mrs.
Crispen said she knew of five events at the first summit in Geneva
in November 1985, five at the December 1987 summit in Washington,
and six last spring in Moscow. They include arrival or departure
ceremonies, one-on-one meetings or social gatherings that the two
women attended together.
   Mrs. Reagan did not attend the October 1986 U.S.-Soviet summit in
Iceland.
</TEXT>
