<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GeorgeToGeorge 1stLd-Writethru a0626 12-07 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-George To George, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Inaugural To Blend Old With New</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX18</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, Subsequent ceremonies ...,with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with program announced</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flags, the U.S. seal, the decor and the
Bible for George Bush's inauguration will look a lot like those from
George Washington's oath-taking 200 years ago at Federal Hall in New
York.
   But the bicentennial inauguration Jan. 20 will also be marked by
some departures from tradition _ including security screening for
the more than 140,000 guests expected to attend the ceremony.
   ``My worst nightmare is that 50,000 people will show up at 11:20
a.m. for a ceremony that starts at 11:30,'' said Michael Ruehling,
executive director of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural
Ceremonies.
   For the first time, those with inauguration tickets will have to
walk through metal detectors to get to their seats. The four gates
will open at 9 a.m. and a musical prelude is scheduled to start 90
minutes later, all in an attempt to get people to come early.
   ``The only thing we're not providing is popcorn,'' Ruehling said.
``I don't know what else we can do, but it does scare me.''
   The inauguration will wait for no one, invited guest or not,
since the Constitution stipulates the oath must be taken at noon.
   The security precautions are the most obvious change from past
practice, but there are other new twists as well. For the first time
ever, the inaugural program will contain the names of the president
and vice president; in the past they were referred to by title only.
Another first: The program will include a four-page history of
inaugurations in commemoration of the bicentennial.
   ``We want to make it a little extra special if we can,'' Ruehling
said of the Bush inauguration.
   Capitol historians and architects have thoroughly researched the
Washington inauguration, and the design for the ceremonial backdrop
reflects their work.
   For example, the archway of the door to the West Front, where
Bush and Vice President-elect Dan Quayle will enter, will be draped
in red bunting similar to the bunting used on the Federal Hall door
in 1789.
   Two flags with 13 stars representing the original 13 states will
be part of the backdrop along with two 38-star flags from 1889 and
the current 50-state flag.
   Bush will likely take the oath of office on the Bible used by
Washington and several presidents since, including Jimmy Carter. And
all inaugural materials will be imprinted with the First Great Seal
of the United States, used as the national emblem from 1782 to 1841.
   At the first inauguration, Washington simply bowed to his
audience, repeated the 35-word oath of office and added at the end,
``I swear, so help me God.''
   Subsequent ceremonies were more elaborate, with music, speeches
and services, and this year is no exception. Participants include
the U.S. Marine and Army bands, the Harlan (Ky.) Boys Choir, and the
Rev. Billy Graham, who will deliver the invocation and the
benediction.
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist will administer the oath of
office to Bush, while Justice Sandra Day O'Connor will swear in
Quayle, the committee said Wednesday.
   More than 500 choruses, bands, bell-ringers and other groups
inundated the congressional committee with requests to perform, most
of them seeking to participate in the inaugural parade to the White
House. Their letters were dispatched to the Presidential Inaugural
Committee, the private group in charge of the parade and other
festivities.
   The Bush inauguration marks only the second time the ceremony has
been held on the Capitol's West Front. From his podium, Bush will
have a panoramic view of the grass-carpeted Smithsonian Mall, the
soaring Washington Monument and many grand buildings of the city.
   President Reagan was sworn in there in 1981. But most
inaugurations have taken place on the East Front, which overlooks
the asphalt Capitol parking area as well as the carefully landscaped
Capitol grounds.
   The inauguration platform and stands under construction on the
West Front are costing $323,000 to build. Taxpayers are footing the
bill for the inaugural preparations and also for an hour-long
catered lunch that precedes the traditional parade down Pennsylvania
Avenue to the White House.
   The quadrennial meal in the Capitol's Statuary Hall will be
attended by about 200 people, among them the president and vice
president, their families, and congressional leaders. Following long
custom, Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the congressional
inaugural committee, will toast the new president and present him
with a gift.
   ``We've got a good one,'' Ruehling said. `You'll find out what it
is on Jan. 20.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
