<HEAD>Barbara Bush Makes Surprise Stop At Tiffany's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush surprised Christmas shoppers
Wednesday with a stop at Tiffany's before her luncheon meeting with
first ladies Nancy Reagan and Raisa Gorbachev.
   Secret Service agents stationed in front of the famed jewelers on
Fifth Avenue first attracted a crowd as Mrs. Bush went inside to
browse.
   ``We're not shopping,'' she called out with a smile as customers
stopped to wish her well. Mrs. Bush made a quick stop at the store
to have her watch repaired, a store spokeswoman said.
   ``It's Mrs. Bush,'' one woman discreetly whispered to a friend as
the soon-to-be first lady peered into display cases.
   She engaged in small talk with those who stopped to congratulate
her on her husband George's election victory and signed an autograph
for Joshua Steinberg, 9, of Brooklyn.
   Referring to advance predictions of monumental traffic problems
because of the visit of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Mrs.
Bush said, ``I didn't think the traffic was so bad _ but it's pretty
bad in here.''
   Then she told the crowd, which was pressed shoulder-to-shoulder
in the crowded jewelry store: ``Now you all go shop.''
