<HEAD>Brite & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Magazine publisher Malcolm Forbes was a
shoo-in for ``most capitalips,'' President Reagan for ``most
outgoing lips,'' and Britain's royal baby Beatrice for ``most
bea-utiful lips.''
   Basketball star Michael Jordan won for ``most Bull-ish lips,''
but actor Kevin Costner of the movie ``Bull Durham'' has the ``most
adora-Bull lips.''
   At least that's the way folks at suburban Chicago-based Blistex
Inc., see things in the company's eighth annual ``Most Beautiful
Lips'' awards.
   Other winners included Los Angeles Dodger pitcher Orel
Hersheiser, named ``most dogged lips'' for pitching 59 consecutive
scoreless innings, and actor Michael Crawford, named ``most
phantasmagoric lips'' for his portrayal of the lead in ``Phantom of
the Opera.''
   Diver Greg Louganis possessed the ``splashiest lips'' for winning
two gold medals at the Seoul Olympics and hotelier Leona Helmsley
had the ``most Harried lips'' for operating the family's hotel
empire with husband Harry Helmsley.
   Among other winners, comedian Jay Leno had ``one-liner lips,''
actress Jamie Lee Curtis of the movie ``A Fish Called Wanda'' had
the ``most Wanda-ful lips'' and author Tom Clancy had the ``most
novel lips.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's The Brent Farris Morning Shows _
all three of them.
   There used to be just one Brent Farris Morning Show, and that was
the adult contemporary music program on radio station KZST. But then
Brent Farris grew tired of getting junk mail addressed to his show.
   ``These underwear companies kept mailing me these underwear
catalogs and I didn't want them,'' he explained.
   So, he offered $1,000 to the first person who legally changed
their name to The Brent Farris Morning Show. He figured that person
would start getting his underwear ads.
   This prompted Donna Johnson to file a fictitious business
statement with the county saying she was doing business as The Brent
Farris Morning Show. Then Cynthia Machado legally changed her name
to The Brent Farris Morning Show.
   After some negotiations, the women agreed to split the money. As
the disc jockey explained it, the one who was first had not legally
changed her name, and the one who legally changed her name wasn't
first.
   And will all this keep the real Brent Farris from getting
underwear ads? Of course not.
   ``It won't keep me from getting them,'' he said. ``But at least
now I have someone to send them to.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters on Miami's Metromover could have heard
wank-wank-TUNK or tinker-tee-tink every time the doors opened on the
mass transit system this week.
   Instead, they'll hear the same old ding dong.
   Dade County transit officials rejected plans to set up a sound
exhibit that was to begin Sunday as part of the New Music America
Festival, calling the bongo drums, Indian chants and other sounds
signaling the door opening unsafe because they might cause the doors
to open unexpectedly.
   Canadian artist Gordon Manahan, who created a set of 11
pre-recorded sounds, called the decision ``blatant censorship.''
   Jeffrey Kaplan, the agency's deputy director, acknowledged he
wasn't thrilled with the Eskimo mouth harp that sounded like an
alarm or a radio disc jockey jabbering in Italian, but was only
concerned about safety.
   Some commuters didn't seem to notice during a test run of the
music, and others noticed but couldn't tell what they were hearing.
   ``I was wondering if there was some kind of subliminal message
behind it,'' downtown commuter Ralph Pujol said after hearing an
electronic ``cha cha'' and some tribal music. ``It's definitely
strange, but it's strange in a neat way. It adds to the mystique of
Miami.''
</TEXT>
