<HEAD>Geremek Receives Passport to Go to France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close adviser to Lech Walesa obtained a
passport Wednesday to accompany the Solidarity leader to France on
his first foreign visit in seven years, an opposition activist said.
   Historian Bronislaw Geremek picked up the passport in Warsaw,
said Jacek Czaputowicz, a founder of the Freedom and Peace
opposition group who said he ran into Geremek at the passport office
while applying for his own passport.
   Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize laureate, has been invited by
French President Francois Mitterrand to attend observances Saturday
of the 40th anniversary of the Declaration of the Universal Rights
of Man. The date, Dec. 10, is observed as International Human Rights
Day.
   Walesa was told Saturday that he could make the trip, but he said
it also was necessary for Geremek, who speaks fluent French and
whose specialty is French medieval history, to accompany him.
   The trip marks the first time Walesa has received permission to
leave Poland since the imposition of martial law at the end of 1981.
His last foreign trip also was to Paris, in October 1981.
   Geremek said Sunday that he has been refused a passport on all
five occasions recently when he applied. But a government spokesman
signaled Tuesday that this time it would be granted.
   Walesa was to leave for Paris on Friday and return Sunday,
accouring to a senior adviser, Adam Michnik.
   Another intellectual adviser to Walesa, Andrzej Wielowieyski, a
leader of the Club of Catholic Intelligentsia in Warsaw, said by
telephone Wednesday that he too would be part of the Solidarity
leader's entourage in France.
   Czaputowicz, a longtime peace and ecology activist, has been
invited by West German President Richard von Weizsaecker to take
part in Bonn's observances of International Human Rights Day on
Saturday.
   He did not receive his passport Wednesday, but said he expected
to pick it up on Thursday.
</TEXT>
