<2ND_LINE>AM-Trump-Eastern,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump, In Court, Defends Purchase of Eastern Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Donald J. Trump offered his
philosophy of business success and vowed Wednesday to give employees
a ``major boost in morale'' if he were allowed to buy Eastern
Airlines' Northeast shuttle.
   Trump flashed a wide smile at the judge's female law clerks and
shook hands with the bailiff during a short break in his testimony
at a federal court hearing on the $365 million deal that is being
challenged by Eastern's unions.
   ``The most important asset of the enterprise is the employees,''
Trump said. ``They are wonderful. They need a major boost in morale
_ that's 90 percent of the problem.''
   But Trump, who insisted he has already befriended Eastern's
shuttle employees during his frequent travels, declined to guarantee
current wages for flight attendants, pilots and other workers.
   ``I can't answer that question now,'' Trump replied. ``I want my
employees to be happy, I want my employees to be well paid, I want
my employees to do a good job.''
   ``In order to have a competitive and successful airline, I do not
know what's going to have to take place,'' he said.
   Trump, whose Manhattan hotels and Atlantic City gambling casinos
have become glittering symbols of business success, said he wanted
to purchase the shuttle to restore ``a great institution'' to the
grandeur it once enjoyed.
   ``Over the last number of years, I've seen it deteriorate very
unfortunately,'' Trump testified.
   Trump compared the Boston-to-New York-to Washington shuttle to
New York's Plaza Hotel, ``which hadn't been run right'' until he
purchased it.
   ``I really look forward to the chance of putting it back on track
and doing something with it,'' Trump said.
   Trump decried the shuttle's loss of customers, which he
attributed to deteriorating service and the stormy relationship
between Eastern and its unions.
   It would take $50 million, which Eastern can't afford, to
refurbish dilapidated airplanes and terminals to attract new
customers, he said.
   ``If I can take the shuttle and turn it around, I think the deal
that I made would be an OK deal,'' Trump said, acknowledging that he
agreed to pay a high price.
   Trump insisted the deal was good for both Eastern and its
employees as well.
   ``If I were on the Eastern side, I would rush like hell to make
this deal,'' he said. ``Without this deal, I think Eastern is
finished.''
   While projecting a common touch, Trump was also combative with
union lawyers who contend that Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., is
selling the shuttle as part of a larger effort to liquidate the
financially troubled airline.
   The Air Line Pilots Association, the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, and the Transport Workers Union of
America contend that the sale violates the Railway Labor Act because
the unions were not consulted.
   ``You think so negatively,'' Trump replied when machinists' union
attorney Joseph Guerrieri Jr. suggested that the sale would reduce
employees' protection from layoffs.
   Trump said Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo sought him out as an
investor in the shuttle earlier this year ``because he knows I have
money.
   ``He would have come to you if he thought you had money,'' Trump
told Guerrieri.
   Trump said he declined Lorenzo's initial offer, saying he would
want to operate the shuttle himself, without partners. ``Generally,
I don't have partners _ it's easier that way.''
   At several points, Trump was reminded by U.S. District Judge
Barrington D. Parker that his jocular banter was inappropriate for
the witness stand.
   ``This is a courtroom, this is not a boardroom,'' Parker said.
   The judge, however, paid tribute to Trump's abilities as a
witness and entrepreneur when he overruled objections that the real
estate developer was being badgered by union lawyers.
   ``Mr. Trump is no babe in the woods, he is no neophyte. He is a
well respected businessman of no little experience,'' Parker said.
``Mr. Trump can take care of himself.''
</TEXT>
