<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavannahRiver-OMB     12-07 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savannah River-OMB,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OMB Denies Energy Department Money for Weapons Plant Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of Management and Budget has turned
down a Department of Energy request for $200 million in additional
funds to pay for urgently needed reactor repairs at the troubled
Savannah River Plant, a White House official said Wednesday.
   DOE's three reactors at the plant near Aiken, S.C., have been
shut down due to safety concerns and maintenance needs. They are the
nation's only source for tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen
used in modern nuclear warheads.
   Because tritium decays at a rate of 5.5 percent a year, it needs
to be regularly replenished.
   A report issued Tuesday by the Energy Department outlined more
than 160 separate tasks for restarting the plant's K reactor. It
called for a complete overhaul of training, safety, management,
operating and inspection procedures.
   The White House official, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified, said, ``Energy came in and asked for new money to fund
some of the cleanup.''
   ``In the (fiscal 1990) budget review, what happened is that they
were told they can't have new money. You have to find the money
within your own budget, which is the same case as every federal
agency has now under the Gramm-Rudman restrictions,'' he said.
   The official added, ``It's not that it isn't a good cause and
that everyone doesn't support doing it _ it's where you get the
money from.''
   With the start of the 1990 fiscal year 10 months off, there are
no indications that OMB's rejection of the extra money means that
the work will not be done.
</TEXT>
