<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     12-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Expects Coalition Talks With Likud to Reopen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres predicted
Wednesday his party would reverse itself and agree to talks with the
rival Likud bloc over forming a coalition government.
   Peres said Labor could agree to a coalition if the right-wing
Likud gives Labor an equal voice in the government, pursues a Middle
East peace pact and stops building settlements in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Last week, Labor's 110-member Executive Bureau vetoed further
negotiations with Likud, defying calls by Peres and Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
   The center-left party's 1,432 member Central Committee was to
meet Thursday to reconsider that decision. ``I estimate the proposal
will be approved,'' Peres said on Israel Television.
   Still, Likud continued efforts to try to form a narrower
coalition with right-wing and religious parties before Labor meets.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, the Likud leader, reached
agreement Wednesday on some sticking points with the National
Religious Party and the Tehiya Party, Israel radio reported.
   Under the agreement, Likud would commit the new government to
build 10 new settlements in the occupied lands and to give both
parties ministries in the new government in exchange for their
support, the radio said. Likud leaders say they hope to form a
narrow government, then invite Labor into a partnership.
   But the agreement to increase settlements in the territories
jeopardizes possible negotiations with the Labor Party.
   ``Of course I will not enter a government that will create
settlements,'' said Peres, who is Israel's foreign minister. ``Of
course I will not go to a government that has no peace process.''
   ``I propose a government with the two major parties at its
center, but I'm not ready to join like a fifth column or a comet
that only has its tail,'' he said in the television interview.
   The issue of negotiations with Likud has deeply divided Labor.
   Israel radio predicted acrimonious discussions continuing into
the night on Thursday, with the old guard of Peres and Rabin finally
triumphing over younger Labor members. The margin could be narrow,
the radio said.
   Labor leaders scheduled the Central Committee meeting after
President Chaim Herzog, a veteran Laborite, called Peres to his
office Monday to request a reopening of coalition talks. Herzog said
he had received thousands of letters demanding a joint government
and a change in Israel's election laws.
   In the Nov. 1 parliament elections, Likud won 40 seats to Labor's
39, with the other 41 seats divided among 13 smaller parties. Likud
has been asked to form a government and must get backing either from
Labor or from several of the smaller right-wing and religious
parties to do so.
   Shamir's efforts to form a narrow government have been stymied by
the stiff demands of the religious parties, which are pushing for
changes in religious legislation that could alienate secular
Israelis and non-Orthodox Jews.
</TEXT>
