<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Summit-Demonstrations     12-07 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Demonstrations,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousand Mass Outside UN to Mark Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-six people protesting the treatment of Jews
in the Soviet Union were arrested Wednesday when they crossed
barricades and sat in the street outside the United Nations building
during Mikhail S. Gorbachev's speech.
   They were part of a throng of chanting, flag-waving 1,000
demonstrators who massed outside the UN in an effort to remind the
Soviet leader of his various problems back home. Besides Jews, there
were supporters of dissidents in the Baltic states, Ukrainians,
Afghans and Armenians.
   The arrests were made while Gorbachev addressed the UN General
Assembly. The demonstrators, members of an organization called
Students Struggle for Soviet Jewry, were taken away in vans, issued
summonses for disorderly conduct, and released.
   ``There's a changed atmosphere, but it's far from being enough,''
said Rabbi Haskel Lookstein, a leader of the demonstration. ``We
appreciate the initial steps ... but there's much more to be done.''
He cited a need for greater freedom for Jews to practice their
religion and emigrate.
   Comptroller Harrison Goldin, one of the city's highest elected
officials, was among those who addressed the crowd.
   ``We hope that as (Gorbachev) pursues glasnost he will be equally
vigorous in implementing a fundamental human freedom: the right to
emigrate and freely practice one's religion. For Jews, that is
fundamental ... to maintain Jewish identity.''
   Franklin Smiles, a rabbinical student, was asked whether he
thought Gorbachev _ who stepped directly from his limousine to the
UN building _ even heard the demonstrators' message.
   ``It's more important that it reaches Americans'' so that they
will pressure U.S. officials to pressure their Soviet counterparts,
he replied.
   Another group of demonstrators carried large banners calling for
the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan. Some protesters
chanted, ``Death to Gorbachev!''
   Members of an Estonian group waved their national flag and
chanted ``One two three four, open up the iron door.'' Estonia is
part of the Soviet Union, but is in the midst of a nationalist
revival.
</TEXT>
