<HEAD>Belgium to Decide Whether to Build Another Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium should not build another nuclear
power plant because it is cheaper to use energy sources such as coal
and natural gas, an Economics Ministry study said Wednesday.
   The government is to decide this week whether to build a proposed
$2.1 billion plant, said ministry spokesman Philippe Demeyer. ``At
this stage the decision could still go either way.''
   Using traditional energy sources could save the country up to
$915 million. the study says. Electricity producers, who support the
construction of what would be Belgium's eighth nuclear plant, have
said non-nuclear options would cost $2.1 billion more than atomic
power.
   Critics have underlined the possible environmental damage from
building the new plant about six miles from downtown Antwerp, near
four other nuclear units and a cluster of chemical plants.
   Belgium derives 66 percent of its energy from nuclear power and
its electricity consumption is increasing by about 3 percent a year.
</TEXT>
