<1ST_LINE>r a eer activities by church congregations,
including clergy, were valued in the study at $13.1 billion.</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>   ``This study makes clear how very large their community services</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   are, dwarfing all funds contributed to and by other voluntary
organizations for local human services,'' Independent Sector
president Brian O'Connell said in the foreward to the report. ``The
report documents that religious congregations are the primary
voluntary service providers for neighborhoods.''
   According to the survey by The Gallup Organization, nearly nine
out of 10 of the nation's 296,000 congregations had one or more
programs in human services and welfare, with a heavy focus on family
counseling activities.
   Seventy percent were involved in overseas charitable activities,
and 56 percent were involved institutional care such as hospitals,
nursing homes or hospices.
   The $19.1 billion given by congregations, mostly in the form of
collections and pledges, was in addition to the approximately $11
billion contributed by other sources to religiously affiliated
organizations such as schools, nursing homes and day care centers,
the group said.
   Of the $48.1 billion of total expenditures by congregations in
1986, $8.4 billion was donated directly to other organizations and
individuals, the study said. Of that, $5.5 billion went to
denominational organizations and charities, such as Catholic
Charities; $1.9 billion went to other charitable organizations in
the community and $1 billion was given directly to individuals.
   ``This compares to the total of financial support from all U.S.
foundations in the same year of $5.9 billion and of U.S. business
corporations of $4.5 billion, making religions a primary source of
financial grants,'' Independent Sector said.
   More than 100 denominations _ Protestant, Roman Catholic, Mormon,
Jewish, Muslim and others _ and regions were represented in the
sample.
   The survey, conducted from May 1987 through March 1988, included
telephone interviews with 4,205 local congregations and more
detailed questionnaires given to a smaller sampling.
   Details on giving by individual congregations were kept
confidential.
   O'Connell said the study was undertaken before the outbreak of
scandals involving television evangelists and was not intended to
offset the negative publicity they caused.
