<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     12-07 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Praise Gorbachev's Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets watching President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
speech that was televised live from the United Nations on Wednesday
praised his decision to reduce troop and tank levels in Eastern
Europe.
   But a few others grumbled that the decision was unnecessary, or
that the Soviet Union had more pressing problems.
   ``It's a really good idea to cut down the amount of troops abroad
because it will save our country some money,'' said Oleg Abramov, a
mechanic from the provincial city of Tula 150 miles south of Moscow.
   Abramov was in a crowd that watched the speech on color TV sets
in the waiting hall of Moscow's Kiev railway station.
   ``We have a big army and a great army. We can afford to bring
some of the troops home and even things out with the Americans a
bit,'' said Alexander Yermakov, a truck driver from suburban Moscow.
   Gorbachev proposed that 500,000 troops be withdrawn from Eastern
Europe and well as 10,000 tanks. He also called for a cease-fire in
Afghanistan starting Jan. 1.
   The main evening news program ``Vremya'' opened with a six-minute
report on the speech, including excerpts of meetings and other
activities. The official news agency Tass carried separate stories
on different aspects of the speech.
   There have been no official comments on Gorbachev's speech yet,
but a television commentator offered an explanation of the reaction
of U.N. delegates shown applauding Gorbachev.
   ``The professional quality of those sitting at the delegation
tables dictates restraining a display of feeling, the stormy
expression of which here is just not acceptable. But such a reaction
which you have witnessed is difficult to recall,'' the commentator
said.
   Tass quickly carried congratulatory remarks on Gorbachev's speech
from various world leaders and prominent public figures, including
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Television later interrupted regular programming with Gorbachev's
arrival at Governor's Island for a meeting with President Reagan.
   Others who watched Gorbachev's speech were more restrained in
their assessment.
   ``I like to watch Gorbachev, but I would really rather have a
look at his wife,'' said a Moscow factory worker.
   ``How could I possibly listen while waiting in line at the
grocery store,'' said another Muscovite.
   ``This is not the kind of thing we need to hear and not the sort
of thing I support,'' said an army soldier who refused to give his
name.
   Muscovites were unable to watch the speech at several traditional
spots. A huge TV screen on a building on the busy Kalinin Prospekt
remained dark throughout the speech and all the TV sets in the Orbit
electronics store were turned off.
   The viewers got a rare glimpse of New York with pictures of
Gorbachev's limousine arriving at the United Nations, a panorama of
the bustling city streets, and Reagan's warm welcome on Governor's
Island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
