<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1541EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-UN     12-07 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-UN,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls For Expanded U.N. Role In Peacekeeping, Monitoring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on
Wednesday called for a vastly expanded role for the United Nations,
from sending peacekeepers into Afghanistan to barring weapons from
outer space.
   Gorbachev also proposed a ``peace corps'' to rebuild Afghanistan,
a team of international scientists to solve environmental disasters,
giving the World Court jurisdiction in human rights cases and
U.N.-sponsored talks between debtor and creditor nations.
   The United Nations gave the Soviet Union an honorable way to
withdraw more than 100,000 Red Army troops from Afghanistan in the
Geneva Accords, which call for U.N. monitoring of a total Soviet
pullout by Feb. 15.
   ``The recent reinvigoration of its peacemaking role has again
demonstrated the United Nations' ability to assist its members in
coping with the daunting challenges of our time and working to
humanize their relations,'' Gorbachev told the General Assembly.
   Gorbachev proposed a complete cease-fire in Afghanistan effective
Jan. 1, along with ``sending to Kabul and other strategic centers of
the country a contingent of United Nations peace-keeping forces.''
   Currently, about 50 officers of the U.N. Good Office Mission to
Afghanistan and Pakistan are monitoring the Soviet troop withdrawal
and investigating complaints of violations of the Geneva Accords.
   ``We also request the secretary-general to facilitate early
implementation of the idea of holding an international conference on
the neutrality and demilitarization of Afghanistan,'' said Gorbachev.
   ``We shall continue most actively to assist in healing the wounds
of the war and ... support the proposal to create under the auspices
of the United Nations a voluntary, international Peace Corps to
assist in the revival of Afghanistan,'' he pledged.
   The world body has embarked on an 18-month, $1.166-billion
program to move Afghan refugees home and revive the shattered
agricultural economy of Afghanistan.
   Turning from war on the ground to peace in the heavens, Gorbachev
said, ``The Soviet Union is also ready to cooperate in establishing
an international space laboratory or manned orbital station designed
exclusively for monitoring the state of the environment.''
   ``All activities in outer space must rule out the appearance of
weapons there. ... There is already a strongly felt need to develop
an all-embracing regime for peaceful work in outer space. The
verification of compliance with that regime would be entrusted to a
World Space Organization,'' an idea that the Soviets have been
promoting in the United Nations for several years.
   ``We are prepared to incorporate within its system our
Krasnoyarsk radar station'' in Siberia, which the United States says
violates the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   ``Soviet scientists are prepared to receive their foreign
colleagues and discuss with them ways of converting it into an
international center for peaceful cooperation by dismantling and
refitting certain units and structures, and to provide additional
equipment. The entire system could function under the auspices of
the United Nations,'' he said.
   President Reagan has insisted on the destruction of the radar
installation.
   A major function of the space laboratory would be to keep track
of pollution, for which Gorbachev had another proposal:
   ``Let us also think about setting up within the framework of the
United Nations a center for emergency environmental assistance. Its
function would be promptly to send international groups of experts
to areas with badly deteriorating environment,'' he said.
   The Soviets have for years been promoting the concept of making
the World Court's human-rights rulings mandatory, particularly on
the five permanent members of the Security Council _ the Soviet
Union, United States, China, Britain and France.
   Currently the opinions of the court, formally called the
International Court of Justice, are now advisory.
   ``We believe that the jurisdiction of the International Court of
Justice at The Hague as regards the interpretation and
implementation of agreements on human rights should be binding on
all states,'' Gorbachev said.
   ``Our ideal is a world community of states which are based on the
rule of law and which subordinate their foreign policy activities to
law,'' he said.
   Developing nations have been crushed by debt repayment schedules
during the 1980s; the total Third World debt is over $1.2 trillion
and many nations can't even repay the interest on their loans.
   Gorbachev proposed ``limiting their official debt-servicing
payments depending on the economic performance of each of them or
granting them a long period of deferral in the repayment of a major
portion of their debt.''
   He backed the appeal of the Geneva-based U.N. Conference on Trade
and Development for reducing debts owed to commercial banks, which
are almost exclusively in Western nations.
   ``The Soviet Union favors a substantive discussion of ways to
settle the debt crisis at multilateral forums, including
consultations under the auspices of the United Nations among heads
of government of debtor and creditor countries,'' Gorbachev added.
</TEXT>
