<HEAD>Faculty, Students File Complaint Over Racial Remarks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Language in 3rd graf may be offensive to some readers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OSHKOSH, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 faculty members and students
have filed a complaint against two University of Wisconsin-Oshkosh
professors who used racist phrases during a Faculty Senate debate.
   Thomas Grogan, university legal counsel, said Wednesday the
university would not comment on the complaint since it deals with
personnel items and is considered confidential.
   Barbara Sniffen, a history professor, and Gerard Grzyb, a
sociology professor, used the terms ``yassir boss'' and ``house
nigger,'' respectively, during a Nov. 8 Faculty Senate debate on a
proposal by the administration that had no racial overtones.
   Both professors were suggesting that the proposal would make the
faculty slaves to the administration.
   Ms. Sniffen is president of the faculty group, and Grzyb the
president-elect.
   The complaint, received by Chancellor Edward M. Penson Dec. 1,
asked that the two be reprimanded for their comments.
   Penson must either dismiss the complaint or order a formal review
by Monday.
   ``I deeply regret the racial crisis that has occurred here, and
has damaged the senate and UW-Oshkosh,'' Ms. Sniffen said.
   Grzyb said he has taken a major step to make peace with the black
students and faculty in the community. But he wouldn't say what he
had done, until he had worked out all the details.
   ``My first responsibility is to the black community and not to
the senate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
