<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Prague-Rights     12-07 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prague-Rights,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hajek Favors Official Reconsideration of 1968 Events</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAZ, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Czechoslovak foreign minister
indirectly called Wednesday for Prague leaders to reconsider the
1968 Soviet-led invasion and hardline policies still considered
legitimate.
   Jiri Hajek arrived in Austria on Monday, on his first Western
trip in almost 20 years, to speak at a seminar organized by several
peace groups to mark international Human Rights Day on Dec. 10.
   The human rights activist traced developments since the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights emerged 40 years ago.
   ``I do not so much care about the rehabilitation of individual
people, but about whether one wants to make a clean sweep of the
events of 1968,'' he said in subsequent comments.
   Hajek referred to the invasion, the subsequent purge of a
half-million Communist Party members and the banning from public
life of thousands of dissident and other non-conformist
intellectuals, artists and politicians since then.
   The Czechoslovak leadership, headed by Communist Party chief
Milos Jakes, upholds the validity of ``Lessons to be Learned,'' a
conservative and dogmatic analysis defending the invasion, the
stationing of Soviet troops and the repressive policies pursued
under what was officially termed the program of ``normalization.''
   ``I do not challenge my homeland's leadership on the right to
recognize mistakes and carry out changes,'' Hajek said.
   ``The most important thing is the re-emergence and reawakening of
the civil society,'' said Hajek, 75, a signatory to the Charter 77
human rights manifesto.
   ``Modernization of the economy has the highest priority in
Czechoslovakia, but that is not possible without a democratization
of society,'' said Hajek, who has refrained from criticizing the
Prague establishment.
</TEXT>
