<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     12-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Councilor Says State Broadcasting Network Broke Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A right-wing town council
leader Wednesday filed complaints accusing state radio of violating
emergency laws by reporting on a black boycott protesting the
council's resegregation campaign.
   The regulations, often disregarded by local and foreign
journalists, outlaw calls for boycotts and prohibit news reports
about their extent.
   Blacks living near the industrial town of Boksburg, east of
Johannesburg, launched a boycott of white-owned stores last week to
protest the Conservative Party-controlled town council's decision to
resegregate public facilities that had been opened to all races in
recent years.
   The governing National Party, which drafted South Africa's
segregation laws during 40 years in power, has joined in the
widespread condemnation of the Conservative Party move even though
councils under Nationalist control still maintain some whites-only
facilities.
   The state-controlled South African Broadcasting Corp., which
generally gives scant coverage to anti-government protests, has
reported extensively on the Boksburg controversy and has mentioned
the boycott.
   Complaints against the network were lodged by Gideon Fourie,
chairman of the Boksburg council's management committee. He filed
similar complaints against Beeld, a pro-government daily newspaper,
and against the Save Boksburg Committee, led by business leaders
seeking to force the council to reverse its racist decision.
   Ferdi Hartzenberg, deputy leader of the Conservative Party, said
the ``obvious unwillingness or inability of the government'' to deal
with the boycotts ``gives the impression that it covertly supports
the actions.''
   Hartzenberg said Boksburg's Conservative Mayor Beyers de Klerk
has filed complaints accusing the Natal Building Society of
intimidation because the savings-and-loan association closed its
Boksburg agency in response to the segregation controversy.
   The Conservative Party, which depicts the government's limited
reforms as capitulation to the black majority, took control of
dozens of town councils in nationwide local elections Oct. 26. A few
of these councils have followed Boksburg's lead by resegregating
amenities while others have said such moves were unnecessary because
the Nationalist-controlled councils they ousted had not integrated
any amenities.
   In Carletonville, a mining town where Conservatives control the
council, councilors decided Tuesday to drop consideration of a
nighttime curfew for blacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
