<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Jordan     12-07 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Jordan,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordanian Soldier Sentenced to 20 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOD, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jordanian soldier who deserted his unit to
plan an attack on Israel in support of the Palestinian uprising was
sentenced to 20 years in prison Wednesday.
   Riyad Musa Abu Higa was arrested May 18 after he infiltrated
Israel from Jordan near the northern kibbutz of Kfar Ruppin, the
army prosecutor, Capt. Reuven Wolf, told a military court in Lod.
   Wolf gave no details of Higa's planned attack.
   He described the 18-year-old Jordanian soldier as a Moslem
fundamentalist who believed he would go to paradise if he died in an
anti-Israeli assault. He said the Jordanian soldier had bought a
revolver so he would not have to use his army rifle and implicate
his unit.
   The soldier had convinced two others in his unit to participate
in the attack, but they abandoned him in Israel and returned to
Jordan.
   When Israeli troops saw him, Higa fired in the air and they shot
back, wounding and capturing him, Wolf said.
   He said Higa had planned the attack to demonstrate his solidarity
with the year-long Palestinian revolt in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   During the trial, Higa refused to recognize the court and would
not rise when the judges entered.
</TEXT>
