<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2104EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilyPoisoning     12-07 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Poisoning,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca Cola Bottles, Plant Being Tested For Links To Poisonings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTURAS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities tested eight bottles of
Coca-Cola on Wednesday for traces of a deadly and outlawed rat
killer blamed for poisoning three family members, leaving one
comatose.
   Investigators were unsure whether the poisoning was accidental.
   ``We won't know until we hear back from the FBI lab,'' said Steve
Hulsey, Polk County sheriff's spokesman. Lab results were not
expected before Friday.
   Authorities also made plans to inspect a Tampa plant where the
Coca-Cola was bottled, said Rob Martin, a company spokesman.
   High concentrations of thallium sulfate, a rat poison and toxic
insecticide banned from general use in 1965, were found in four
empty 16 oz. bottles of Coca-Cola at the Polk County home of Peggy
Carr, police said.
   Mrs. Carr, 41, remained in critical condition at Winter Haven
Hospital, unresponsive and on a respirator. She was admitted Oct.
31, Hulsey said. Stepson Travis Carr, 16, was stable, and Mrs.
Carr's son, Duane Dubberly, 16, was released Friday.
   It was unclear where the family bought the soda or when it was
consumed.
   Martin said there have been no other reports of poisoning related
to Coca-Cola.
   ``We do not have any evidence it occurred in the bottling
plant,'' he said.
   The four bottles were part of a lot of nearly 200,000 shipped to
Central Florida markets six weeks ago. Authorities were testing the
four empty bottles and four others that were full.
   ``We believe the rest of the lot is safe, but we want local,
state and health authorities to draw the conclusions,'' Martin said.
   Earlier this week, samples of the batch in question were tested a
second time and no traces of thallium sulfate were found, Martin
said.
   Dr. Sven Normann, director of the Florida Poison Information
Center, said thallium sulfate can be found in the form of a crystal
powder or a paste which dissolves in water. One gram of the chemical
is considered a fatal dose.
</TEXT>
