<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StolenCar-Baby     12-07 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Car-Baby,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thief Swipes Car With Baby In Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thief who swiped a Cadillac apparently
had a change of heart after discovering a 7-day-old baby in the back
seat.
   The infant, Jarell Farmer, was wrapped in a blanket in the back
when the thief hopped in Tuesday night and sped away from a San Jose
gas station. The car was found about 45 minutes later, with the
unharmed infant inside, three blocks from police headquarters.
   ``As soon as he heard the baby crying, I'm sure (the thief)
pulled over,'' said police Capt. Bill Lansdowne.
   An anonymous tipster, who police suspect was the thief, phoned
police to report the location of the car where he said he heard a
baby crying.
   Police then reunited the baby with his mother, Erlinda Farmer.
   The incident began about 6 p.m. when Rufus Love, the car's owner
and a friend of Ms. Farmer, stopped at the gas station for a pack of
cigarettes.
   Love left the car _ engine running and the driver's door open _
and walked 15 feet to the cashier's window. Love was counting change
when he heard the car door slam and saw it speed off, according to
police and witnesses.
