<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeputyKilled     12-07 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deputy Killed,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Stressed Out' Deputy Killed After Taking Potshots At Troopers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREAUX BRIDGE La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state trooper killed a sheriff's
deputy after the woman allegedly made threatening telephone calls
and fired shots at law officers, police said Wednesday.
   Elizabeth Laperouse, 22, was killed Tuesday night after pointing
a gun at officers following a chase that ended near Breaux Bridge,
50 miles west of Baton Rouge, State Police Lt. Ronnie Jones said.
   Investigators were told Laperouse, a dispatcher with the St.
Martin Parish Sheriff's office since June 1987, ``was acting
somewhat irrationally'' when she came to work Tuesday, Jones said.
``I think the words they used were `stressed out.'''
   Laperouse was told to go home, and her pistol was taken away. But
she apparently visited a friend and got another weapon, Jones said.
   Later Tuesday, according to Jones, a woman called State Police
Troop I headquarters in Lafayette threatening ``to shoot the first
trooper who comes out of the building.''
   Trooper Chet Robichaux and a member of the Scott police
department then walked out of the building, and three shots were
fired at them, Jones said.
   The shots missed, and the officers saw a woman jump into a red
car and speed away. About an hour later, a caller asked police at
Troop I, ``Did you hear the shots?'' Jones said.
   ``I'll be on I-10 in St. Martin Parish traveling east, and I dare
any trooper to try to stop me,'' Jones quoted the caller as saying.
   Robichaux spotted the red car, and he and two other troopers
pursued it to near the Atchafalaya Swamp, Jones said.
   Laperouse jumped from her car and pointed her pistol at the
troopers, he said.
   ``After being told to drop her weapon, she began to make
offensive moves, and two shots were fired, one striking her in the
head,'' Jones said. Investigators determined that State Police acted
properly, he said.

</TEXT>
