<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Ford-Budget     12-07 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford-Budget,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Ford Urges Budget Process Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ford on Wednesday lobbied
congressional leaders to reform their budget procedures to help
combat the federal deficit and ensure a strong economy.
   ``The budget process is in shambles,'' said Ford, who had
breakfast and lunch with congressional leaders concerned with budget
matters.
   The former president appeared at a press conference with former
Congressional Budget Office director Rudolph G. Penner and political
scientist Alan J. Abramson, two Urban Institute scholars who have
written a new book on budget reform. Ford wrote the foreword for the
book.
   ``I'm concerned that unless you do something to correct the
process, there is no way to get the White House and Congress to
achieve the (deficit reduction) results for a healthy economy,'' the
former president said.
   Among the book's suggestions is giving the president more sway
over budget decisions, including the power to veto the congressional
resolutions that guide the drafting of spending and tax bills.
   It also calls for giving the president more power to cancel
spending already approved by Congress.
   Currently, the president proposes cuts but Congress can stop them
by ignorning them. The authors propose requiring Congress to vote to
block the president's proposals.
   The book also calls for making the budget process less prone to
political tampering, including the use of an outside board of
experts to make economic forecasts.
   Ford had breakfast with House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas,
Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., Minority Leader Bob
Michel, R-Ill., incoming House budget chairman Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole.
   He later lunched with Senate budget writers, including incoming
budget committee chairman James R. Sasser, D-Tenn., and the senior
Republican on the panel, Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico.
   Ford and another former president, Jimmy Carter, have together
proposed steps for reducing the federal deficit including some new
taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
