<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last item to CORRECT references to son's role in purchase
of the property and CORRECT son's age to 8 sted 10.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ADAIRSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bavarian Prince Hubertus Fugger plans to
slowly renovate the 1,100-acre Barnsley Gardens estate, and
eventually may install a 70-acre lake and a museum.
   Fugger bought the northern Georgia estate through representatives
in an Atlanta-based company, Stonewall Limited Partnership, for
$1.35 million earlier this year, according to records at the Fulton
County Tax Assessor's office.
   He said in a telephone interview from Bavaria that his son also
has high hopes for the property.
   ``I brought my 8-year-old son along the last time I visited. He's
a nature-loving little guy, and when he saw the property he told me
he wanted to build a cabin out there and have a pickup to drive
around,'' Fugger told the Rome News-Tribune in a telephone interview
from Bavaria on Monday.
   ``It's a kid's dream and I do understand it very much because
it's a super place,'' he said.
   The property originally was developed to be the home of Godfrey
Barnsley, who in 1844 was a wealthy English cotton buyer.
