<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Mandela 1stAdd   12-07 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Mandela, 1st Add,a0760,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa: any details.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mandela, leader of the outlawed African National Congress, has
been in prison since 1962 and is serving a life sentence for
sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-dominated government.
The ANC is the largest guerrilla organization fighting the
government and its apartheid policy of racial segregation.
   The transfer of Mandela, made without any advance warning,
appears part of a phased release. The government has said Mandela
will have greater access to his family and visitors after he was
moved from the hospital.
   But no details about the conditions of his stay at the prison
farm were immediately available.
   Mandela, the country's best known black leader, was hospitalized
in August and has been in the Constantiaburg Clinic since Aug. 31.
His doctors said recently that his health was good and that he was
exercising regularly.
   The government recently has released colleagues of Mandela,
fueling speculation that Mandela could be freed shortly.
   Late last month, authorities released Harry Gwala, a longtime
member of the ANC, and Zeph Mothopeng, president of the
Pan-Africanist Congress, another outlawed guerrilla group.
   The government also has released several prominent detainees in
recent days in an apparent attempt to reduce international and
domestic pressure.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
