<DOCNO> AP881207-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2108EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade-Hills     12-07 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Hills,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lack of Experience No Problem for Mrs. Hills, Danforth Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney Carla Hills shapes up as an good
choice for the nation's chief trade negotiator despite her lack of
experience in that field, a senator active in trade issues said
Wednesday.
   ``What I want is someone who is a tough negotiator and does not
come to the job with a prefabricated philosophy,'' Sen. John C.
Danforth, R-Mo., said in an interview. He said that described Mrs.
Hills.
   Danforth scoffed at the notion that Mrs. Hills, who was secretary
of housing and urban development in the Ford administration, might
be hampered in the post of U.S. trade representative by her lack of
trade experience.
   President-elect George Bush announced his selection of Mrs. Hills
on Tuesday.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter is wrapping up three
years in the job in which President Reagan vetoed three trade bills
despite congressional clamor over record deficits in global markets.
Reagan finally signed a wide-ranging, 1,000-page bill co-sponsored
by Danforth this year.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, another
co-sponsor, said Tuesday that Mrs. Hills is ``a very able person''
but added a reservation.
   ``I had hoped, frankly, that we'd have someone from the business
world who had extensive international experience in trade,'' Bentsen
said.
   Danforth, who had lunch with Mrs. Hills on Wednesday, noted that
most previous trade representatives came to the post with trade
experience but that Mrs. Hills had proven herself as a Cabinet
member.
   ``My impression is that she is a very able person with a very
keen mind and that she's energetic and she certainly has a lot of
experience in Washington,'' Danforth said.
   He declined to speculate on whether she would be able to prevail
in a policy dispute with Secretary of State-designate James A. Baker
III, who as treasury secretary often was the Reagan administration's
guiding hand on trade.
   ``I think it remains to be seen what the trade policy of the new
administration will be and who the key players are,'' Danforth said.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., said he ``would imagine that
Secretary Baker is going to have a lot to do with trade as he did
when he was secretary of the treasury.''
   ``He has a deep interest in it and a high degree of skill at
it,'' said Gibbons, who chairs the House Ways and Means trade
subcommittee. He said, however, that Mrs. Hills might well prove
effective in her job.
   ``You have to have one of two things to be a good trade
representative,'' Gibbons said. ``You either have to have a high
degree of technical skill and be a good bargainer or you have to
have the ear of the president.''
   ``I imagine that Hills has the president's ear,'' he said. ``I
say that because her appointment came early in this and because I
think George Bush listens to her. At least that is what I'm told.''
   He said that one of the best trade representatives was Democratic
attorney Robert Strauss, ``and he didn't know a thing about it when
he walked into the job, but Jimmy Carter would listen to him and
that's what it takes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
