<DOCNO> AP881207-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1704EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DeficitCommission     12-07 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Commission,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Commission Told of Economic Effects of Deficit Cutting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Economic Commission, trying to
break the seven-year deadlock over huge budget deficits, was told
Wednesday that it matters little to overall economic performance
whether the deficit reduction comes from spending cuts or tax
increases.
   The high-level advisory panel received a study prepared by the
Congressional Budget Office which showed that a full-scale assault
on the budget deficit will not cause a recession as long as the
Federal Reserve helps out by lowering interest rates to offset the
reduced federal spending.
   The CBO report rejected arguments often raised by critics that
the current economic recovery could be thrown into a recession if
the budget deficit is brought down too rapidly or if politicians
rely too heavily on tax increases to close the gap between revenues
and spending.
   Commission Co-chairmen Robert Strauss and Drew Lewis said they
believed the CBO report showed that the commission had wide leeway
from an economic standpoint in selecting a mix of spending cuts and
tax increases to close the budget gap.
   But the two men said the economic models did not take into
account the political realities of crafting a package acceptable to
Congress and President-elect George Bush, who has vowed to reject
any new taxes.
   ``We are right where we were at first. The problem is 10 percent
economic and 90 percent political,'' Lewis said.
   The deficit panel was created by Congress a year ago to provide
advice to Congress and the president-elect on ways to eliminate the
federal budget deficit, which climbed to $155.1 billion in the
fiscal year which ended on Sept. 30.
   The CBO ran four types of deficit reduction efforts through
computer simulations of the U.S. economy to see what the impact
would be.
   All of the options would achieve deficit cuts of $120 billion to
$130 billion by 1994 but would arrive at that goal in different
ways. One option got all of the reductions from domestic programs,
exempting Social Security and defense from any cuts. This proposal
also ruled out any tax increases.
   At the other extreme, a fourth proposal got half of its deficit
savings from cuts in defense, Social Security and other entitlement
programs and other domestic programs and the other half from higher
taxes.
   Fred Ribe, assistant director for fiscal analysis for the CBO,
said that the various computer models showed little difference on
economic growth regardless of the mix of spending cuts and tax
increases which were used.
   He said that all of the models assumed that the loss of economic
stimulus from the various combinations of reduced government
spending and higher taxes would be offset by a more stimulative
policy on the part of the Federal Reserve.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has indicated that the
central bank would be willing to pursue a looser monetary policy,
pushing interest rates lower, if Congress cooperated by reducing the
borrowing demands of the federal government.
   Ribe said that if the Fed did not keep its part of the bargain,
the economic models forecast that economic growth, as measured by
the gross national product, would be 1 percentage point lower than
it otherwise would be over the next five years.
   The CBO projections used economic computer models developed by
Data Resources Inc., a Lexington, Mass., consulting firm; Washington
University in St. Louis and Yale professor Ray Fair.
   The revenue options ranged from no increases in taxes to a
package of tax hikes on personal income and increases in taxes for
energy, beer, wine and cigarettes.
   The commission's Wednesday hearing was scheduled to be the last
public meeting for the panel this year. The panel had planned to
hold a closed-door session next Monday to give the 12 members an
opportunity to discuss various deficit cutting options.
   Several news organizations have gone to court in an effort to
force that meeting to be opened to the public. U.S. District Judge
Joyce Hens Green heard arguments on the dispute Wednesday and
indicated she would issue a ruling later this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
