<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Summit-Glance     12-07 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Glance,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Developments at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the major developments in
Soviet president Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit Wednesday to New York:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GORBACHEV SPEECH AT UNITED NATIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev announced the Soviet Union will unilaterally cut its
military forces by a half-million troops and reduce its conventional
arms, saying the military ``no longer can or must be an instrument
of foreign policy.''
   Gorbachev also called for a total cease-fire in Afghanistan
beginning Jan. 1, proposed ending arms supplies to both sides, and
asked for a United Nations peace-keeping force to oversee formation
of a broad-based Afghan government.
   In other parts of his hour-long speech, Gorbachev spoke about
third world debt, the global environment, human rights, and the U.S.
denial of a visa for Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAGAN-GORBACHEV-BUSH MEETING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan welcomed the Soviet leader's initiatives, saying
the proposal for Soviet conventional-force reductions ``is a
unilateral action on their part.''
   Reagan, asked his view of the meeting, said, ``Read our smiles.''
   Gorbachev said, ``In developing our relations we can work only
together so we do hope that the United States and the Europeans will
work with us and will also take certain steps.''
   After lunch on Governors Island, the two leaders and
President-elect Bush rode to a point on the island offering a
handsome view of the Statue of Liberty and lower Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOVIET-AKHROMEYEV</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Soviet foreign ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov denied
reports that the chief of the Soviet General Staff resigned in
protest over Gorbachev's troop cutback plan, saying Marshal Sergei
Akhromeyev stepped down for ``health reasons.''
   Akhromeyev and other top Soviet generals reportedly argued that
the cuts should be done simultaneously with reductions by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Gorbachev, asked whether he was getting resistance from the
military establishment, replied with a smile: ``Nyet, nyet, nyet.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMONSTRATIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-six people protesting the treatment of Jews in the Soviet
Union were arrested when they crossed barricades outside the United
Nations building during Gorbachev's speech. The demonstrators were
taken away in vans, issued summonses for disorderly conduct, and
released. They were part of a throng of 1,000 demonstrators massed
outside the UN.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FIRST LADIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The three leaders' wives, Nancy Reagan, Barbara Bush and Raisa
Gorbachev, joined hostess Marcela Perez de Cuellar, wife of the U.N.
general-secretary and 20 New York socialites for lunch at her East
Side home.
   ``I am happy to be in the city you call the Big Apple,'' Mrs.
Gorbachev said.
   The Soviet first lady's itinerary Wednesday also included a visit
to the Estee Lauder cosmetic headquarters and an tour by car of
Manhattan with her husband.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSH-GORBACHEV</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush stuck to his plan to attend the
Gorbachev-Reagan meeting only in his role as vice president,
withholding any public assessment of Moscow's new troop cutback plan.
   When Reagan greeted Gorbachev on the steps of Admiral's House on
Governors Island, Bush remained inside the building, allowing the
two leaders to pose for pictures together. Bush then stepped outside
and joined Reagan and Gorbachev, shaking hands with the Soviet
leader.
</TEXT>
