<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Helicopter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0740,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Pilot Flies Helicopter to Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Honduran foreign minister comment,
Nicaraguan broadcast, details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras said the air force
intercepted a Soviet-built Nicaraguan attack helicopter in its air
space Wednesday and the leftist Sandinistas government said an army
defector flew it across the border.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras told a news conference in
Tegucigalpa the ``very sophisticated aircraft was intercepted by
Honduran fighters when it illegally penetrated our territory.''
   He said the Mi-25 helicopter was forced to land at the Toncontin
air base outside Tegucigalpa, the capital, and authorities were
investigating.
   Nicaragua's Defense Ministry said an army defector flew the
chopper to Honduras. It demanded the return of both aircraft and
pilot.
   A Nicaraguan statement identified the pilot as Capt. Edwin
Estrada Leiva and said he landed at Hernan Costa Mejia air base in
Honduras, another name for Toncontin. It said the Foreign Ministry
was in touch with Honduras about the return of the helicopter and of
Estrada, described as a ``CIA terrorist.''
   The Soviet Union has provided Nicaragua's government with about
40 helicopters and the Pentagon says 12 are Mi-25 Hind D ``flying
tanks,'' which can ferry up to 13 soldiers into combat at 200 mph.
   Mi-25s are heavily armed and were used extensively in Afghanistan.
   A New York Times report on March 27 said Chad allowed the United
States last year to examine Soviet arms it had captured from
retreating Libyan forces, including an Mi-24 Hind, in exchange for
$35 million in military aid to the African nation. The Times quoted
the Pentagon as refusing to discuss the matter.
   Pentagon sources said Wednesday an Mi-25 is worth $20-$30 million.
</TEXT>
