<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Quayle     12-07 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle, Mondale Meet to Discuss Vice Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle, investigating how as vice president
he will involve himself in fighting drugs, exploring space and
picking his staff, got some advice from Walter Mondale _ stay away
from trivia.
   Mondale, who was vice president under President Carter and the
Democratic presidential nominee in 1984, said after meeting with
Quayle on Wednesday that the Indiana senator is ``obviously serious
about this job.''
   Although Quayle was denounced by Democrats throughout the
campaign as unfit for the post, Mondale told reporters:
   ``I believe he can do it, and I believe he wants to do it. He's
been elected by the people of the United States and we all better
hope that he does a good job.''
   Mondale said he warned Quayle to resist being diverted from
significant issues into trivial pursuits.
   ``I told him I thought a big danger of the vice presidency is to
be trivialized, to be given a number of functions, to prove they're
important when in fact we have other agencies to do that work,''
Mondale said.
   ``He ought to use his time to work on the really important
matters. ... After all, Mr. Quayle might become president. He ought
to be working on issues of significance.''
   Quayle called Mondale for the meeting as he continued to solicit
advice from former vice presidents on how to handle the office. He
already has met with former President Nixon, who was vice president
under Dwight Eisenhower, and plans to see former President Gerald
Ford, who was Nixon's vice president.
   Quayle also met Wednesday with NASA Director James Fletcher and
Gen. John Piotrowsky, head of the U.S. Space Command, to discuss
space policy. Bush has said he would appoint his vice president to
head the new U.S. Space Council, a body created by Congress to shape
the direction of U.S. space policy.
   And he met with Bush transition officials Craig Fuller and Boyden
Gray. Fuller, Bush's longtime chief of staff who has said he is
leaving government after the transition, would be able to advise
Quayle on selection of his own staff. Gray, who is serving as legal
counsel to Bush's transition office and will be White House legal
counsel when Bush takes office, was discussing in part the role of
the drug czar who will be appointed by the president.
   Bush initially said he wanted his vice president to oversee the
administration's drug-fighting efforts, but recently passed
congressional legislation calls for a drug czar who is not a member
of the Cabinet. Quayle has said he would look into the propriety of
such options as having the drug czar report to him or having that
person be part of his staff, said press spokesman Jim Carroll.
   Quayle also met Wednesday with Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut
in what Caroll described as a courtesy call by the mayor who was in
Washington on other business. The meeting was not set up to discuss
whether Hudnut should succeed Quayle as the senator from Indiana,
said Carroll.
   Mondale said it was apparent Quayle had been boning up on the
vice presidency and thinking a lot about how to approach it. Quayle
sought ideas on how much time he should spend on Capitol Hill, on
administrative matters and on official functions, Mondale said.
   ``There's going to be pressure on him to take on a lot of little
functions to prove he's doing something. I said, reject that advice
and just stay on the big issues,'' Mondale said.
   Mondale and Carter were the object of harsh rhetoric from Quayle
during the presidential campaign this year, as he sought to tie
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis to what Republicans dubbed the
failed liberal policies of the past.
   Mondale said he had not been ``too flattering about him,
either,'' and indicated that was behind them now.
   Meanwhile Quayle has selected veteran Time magazine correspondent
David Beckwith as his press secretary.
   Beckwith recently covered the Bush campaign for 15 months and
said of Quayle:
   ``I've talked to him a lot over the last couple weeks. I realize
he's a lot better than his press notices would make him appear,'' he
said noting the rash of negative publicity about Quayle's past and
credentials that hit the vice president-elect when Bush picked him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
