<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Akhromeyev     12-07 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Akhromeyev,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Leader Who Accompanied Gorbachev to Summits Retires</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Red Army and AM-Summit-Akhromeyev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev supervised
intelligence and strategic missiles and earned the respect of his
Western counterparts during a 48-year military career that ended
with his retirement.
   Akhromeyev, the military chief of staff, traveled with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to his Reykjavik and Washington summits
with President Reagan and visited the Pentagon in July to meet with
U.S. military officials.
   But Akhromeyev, 65, did not show up in New York for the latest
summit, which began Wednesday, and Soviet officials there announced
that Akhromeyev had retired for health reasons. It was the same day
Gorbachev announced unilateral cuts in Soviet conventional forces.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, in New York,
denied that Akhromeyev resigned in protest over the troop cutback
plan, which Gorbachev disclosed in a speech to the United Nations.
But top Soviet military officials have opposed any reduction in
Soviet forces without corresponding moves by the West.
   The marshal will remain as an adviser to Gorbachev, Gerasimov
said.
   Akhromeyev's resignation was not immediately reported by the
Soviet press, and no successor was named.
   Akhromeyev supervised military intelligence and strategic nuclear
weapons on the Soviet general staff before becoming its chief in
September 1984.
   U.S. counterparts who sat across the table from him during the
1986 Reykjavik, Iceland, summit said he earned their respect.
   ``He was tough and determined, but he was trying to get an
agreement,'' one senior U.S. official said on condition of anonymity.
   After the talks failed to produce an agreement, Akhromeyev said
of his American counterpart Paul Nitze, ``I thought I could outlast
him, but I didn't.''
   Akhromeyev, during his trip to the Pentagon, said the Soviet
Union was reorganizing its military in line with a policy of giving
it a more purely defensive character, but that the changes would
take time. Gorbachev, in his U.N. address, also talked about the
switch to a defensive posture.
   At a news conference in June, Akhromeyev, who held top military
posts under former President Leonid I. Brezhnev, criticized
Brezhnev's foreign policy. ``We used to be too forthright in our
reaction to the arms race pursued by the West,'' he said.
   He blamed the Reagan administration for starting the arms race
but said the Soviets should not have been so willing to respond in
kind.
   Akhromeyev, a burly man with a strong voice that commanded the
meetings he had with foreign journalists in Moscow, abruptly
replaced Nikolai V. Ogarkov as chief of general staff. Ogarkov was
an advocate of turning to new military technologies instead of
building more nuclear warheads.
   Six months after Akhromeyev took the job, Gorbachev became the
Soviet leader and began his active search for arms agreements with
the West.
   Gorbachev fired Defense Minister Sergei L. Sokolov in May 1987
after amateur pilot Mathias Rust of West Germany threaded Soviet air
defenses to land a small private plane on Moscow's Red Square.
   But he promoted Dmitri T. Yazov, a strong supporter of extending
Gorbachev's reforms to the military, over Akhromeyev and several
other senior officers as the new defense minister.
   Akhromeyev has been in the Soviet military since 1940. In August
1942, during some of the grimmest days of World War II for the
Soviet Union, he was discharged from the naval academy and sent to
the army front line.
   There he gained wide experience infantry and tank troops and
worked his way up the ranks. He became a full member of the
Communist Party Central Committee in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0189 </DOCNO>
