<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Bush-Barge     12-07 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Barge,335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President-Elect, Future Secretaries are Business Partners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and two long-time friends he has
named to his Cabinet are partners in a Texas barge company, an
investment that earned the president-elect more than $20,000 last
year.
   Bush, Secretary of State-designate James A. Baker III, and
Commerce Secretary-designate Robert Mosbacher Sr., all are limited
partners of Hollywood LPG No. 2 Ltd., one of several limited
partnerships run by Houston-based Hollywood Marine Inc., state
records show.
   Bush in 1987 reported $20,773 in income from the company. The
money was listed as ``passive income'' on his federal tax return,
meaning Bush has no say in business decisions. The investment also
is listed on his annual financial disclosure forms, which are
reviewed by government ethics officials.
   ``We think it's an honor to have them'' as part of the company,
said Robert Egan, vice president and secretary of Hollywood Marine.
   Hollywood LPG No. 2 Ltd. was formed in 1978 and at the time owned
four barges, according to records filed with the Texas Secretary of
State.
   Bush and Baker each were given 2.2 percent ownership of the
company for an investment of $50,000 apiece. Mosbacher was assigned
4.7 percent interest for $105,000. Hollywood Marine was assigned 67
percent ownership for an investment of just $1,000, a routine
arrangement with general partners.
   None of the three men has an active role in the business, Egan
said. Other limited partners include other Mosbacher family members
and friends. Egan said the group was put together by Mosbacher.
   Mosbacher has raised campaign funds for Bush in every political
race he has entered since his second unsuccessful campaign for the
Senate in 1970. Mosbacher served as Bush's finance chairman during
the presidential campaign and raised nearly $20 million. He also was
chairman of the Republican Party's ``Team 100,'' which raised $24
million from individuals and corporations in $100,000 donations.
   Baker resigned as treasury secretary earlier this year to manage
the Bush presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
