<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Summit-CityScene 1stLd-Writethru a0690 12-07 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-City Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Gorbylock'' Finally Descends on Manhattan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Traffic problems develop, top 6 grafs, pickup 5th pvs bgng
``People aren't''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas shoppers and power lunchers went about
their business Wednesday as if Mikhail S. Gorbachev had never left
the Kremlin, but his late-afternoon motorcade finally plunged
Manhattan traffic into dreaded ``Gorbylock.''
   For the morning rush-hour, warnings of gridlock evidently scared
enough motorists to produce a ``significant drop in volumes'' all
over the city, according to Transportation Department spokesman
Victor Ross.
   ``I came this morning across the 59th Street Bridge. Queens Plaza
looked like the Sahara. The only thing that was missing were the
camels,'' said Ross, who earlier had issued dire traffic predictions.
   But those predictions were fufilled when Gorbachev's motorcade
took its afternoon tour of Wall Street, midtown Manhattan and Times
Square, said Deputy Transportation Commissioner Sam Schwartz.
   ``Those people who did come in got caught,'' said Schwartz during
the height of the ``Gorbylock'' at about 5:15 p.m. ``It's little
consolation to them that there was a 15 percent dropoff in traffic.''
   Earlier in the day, up and down the Gorbachev midtown Manhattan
motorcade route, the story was the same. Sure, Gorbachev's coming,
but whaddaya want me to do about it?
   ``People aren't really talking about it yet. Maybe later on,''
said Patrick Coan, an employee at the Charivari store on West 57th
Street _ one of the streets on the route of the blocks-long
Gorbachev motorcade Wednesday afternoon.
   Although the store's front window was completely done in red,
Coan said it had nothing to do with Gorbachev's impending arrival:
``Nobody else has picked up on that. Actually, it's just to
encourage people to have a red Christmas instead of a white
Christmas.''
   As the Soviet leader addressed the United Nations, assistant
manager Tim Higbie of the Barnes and Noble book store on Seventh
Avenue confirmed ``some of his books are around here,'' although
they weren't selling particularly well.
   Higbie seemed unimpressed that Gorbachev would later pass the
store. There were no plans to put his tomes on the ``book for a
buck'' table; his ``At The Summit'' would still run buyers $16.11,
he said.
   As President Reagan and Gorbachev sat down for their afternoon
repast on Governors Island, power-lunchers and tourists around the
city sat down for their own meals.
   The manager at the Russian Tea Room, facing what one waiter
confided was an overbooked lunch hour, couldn't be bothered with
Gorby-talk. At the Hard Rock Cafe, the British and American flags
flew _ no sign of the Soviet hammer and sickle _ over the heads of
dozens of tourists waiting to eat.
   Outside the Henri Bendel store on West 57th Street, doorman
Charles Rome opened a limousine door and let a patron inside,
blissfully unaware that 45 limos carrying Gorbachev, his wife Raisa
and assorted Soviet associates would soon be cruising by the
exclusive women's clothing store.
   ``No. Down this street? I heard he was in town, but I didn't know
he was coming through here,'' said Rome, a Manhattanite who also
observed traffic on the crosstown street was lighter than usual.
   Tourists filled midtown to visit the usual holiday hot spots:
Radio City Music Hall and the Rockefeller Center Christmas tree and
skating rink. Shoppers packed Bloomingdale's and Macy's, oblivious
to warnings of traffic jams and rumors of a shopping spree by Raisa
Gorbachev.
   ``We've got the typical pre-Christmas crowds. The store's very
crowded,'' said Bloomingdale's spokeswoman Miraed Smith. ``Of
course, we're right near a subway stop, bus stops, and the Soviet
embassy.''
   Even the out-of-towners weren't too concerned about Gorbachev's
trip around town. Sixty-nine students from Martin Luther King High
School in Philadelphia were at the Cort Theater to see the matinee
of ``Sarafina!''; they had no plans to look for the Soviet leader
when it was over.
   ``We're getting out, getting on the bus and going home,'' said
Sam Colson, a chaperone with the group. ``We won't see Gorbachev _
nothing personal.''
</TEXT>
