<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Summit-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0784 12-07 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0784,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Superpower Lunch `Productive,' No Gorbachev-Bush Summit
Set</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 24 grafs to UPDATE with Bush assessment of meeting.
Picks up 11th graf pvs, bgng: `While carving ...' Edits from bottom
to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush said Wednesday that
the superpower luncheon with President Reagan and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev was ``a good, productive meeting'' and that
there was no pressure now for him to have his own summit with the
Kremlin leader.
   Describing the two hours of talks on Governors Island in New York
Harbor, Bush said, ``There was no pressing on substantive details,''
although he said there were some substantive discussions.
   Bush said he made clear to Gorbachev that he wanted to continue
the progress that's been made during the Reagan administration in
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   With his national security team still being assembled, Bush said,
``I also made clear that we needed some time and he understood that.
He didn't seem to have any problem with that at all.''
   As the three leaders parted in New York, Bush told Gorbachev, ``I
enjoyed the meeting. Hope to see you soon.''
   Afterward, Secretary of State George Shultz said Bush was ``quite
active in the discussion during the luncheon.''
   He said Bush's presence provided proof of the desire on both
sides to continue the dialogue that Reagan and Gorbachev had begun.
   Bush said that once his national security team is in place and
the administration's strategy has been set, Secretary of
State-designate James A. Baker III would contact NATO allies and
consult with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``At an appropriate time a meeting between me and General
Secretary Gorbachev can be discussed,'' Bush said. ``But there's no
pressure on that. The main thing is to formulate our plans and move
them forward so we have progress. That's what I want.''
   Asked if the timing of a Bush-Gorbachev summit had been
discussed, he replied, ``No, there wasn't any discussion of it at
all.''
   Outside the luncheon, Bush played a decidedly low-key role,
remaining in the background for the most part as Reagan and
Gorbachev greeted each other in their fifth and final meeting.
   In a visible demonstration of his status, Bush rode in the
limousine jumpseat, with two translators, facing backward as he
accompanied Reagan and Gorbachev on a brief ride to a departure
ceremony on the island.
   Bush seemed at ease in the presence of the superpower leaders.
   Clowning around, Bush pretended he was going to pitch himself
into New York Harbor from a waterside platform when photographers
shouted to the trio to keep changing position as they viewed the
Statue of Liberty.
   Smiling broadly, Bush seemed bemused as Gorbachev talked at
length about the luncheon at the conclusion of the departure
ceremony.
   Neither Reagan nor Bush commented then, but Bush volunteered a
statement to reporters upon his return to Washington.
   Standing under the wing of Air Force Two, Bush said, ``I think it
was a good, productive meeting. It was really, in a sense, a salute
to President Reagan, giving him an opportunity to thank General
Secretary Gorbachev.''
   Saying that some substance had been discussed, Bush said,
``Generally, it worked out as well as I had hoped.''
   Bush said Gorbachev seemed very upbeat after the meeting. ``It's
not surprising. I felt the same general feeling there. There's no
question that Mr. Gorbachev is a very different individual from his
predecessors. He's a warm human being, and people see that.
   ``He's committed to change,'' Bush added.
   He said Gorbachev's speech to the United Nations earlier in the
day, in which he proposed a 500,000-man cutback in Soviet forces,
``had some positive elements in it, and I think that he felt that
that had gone well.
   ``So why shouldn't he feel good?'' Bush said. ``He and President
Reagan had had a very good relationship, and he was saying farewell
to a man with whom he's worked very closely.''
   Asked specifically about the troop cutback proposal, Bush said,
``It's a good decision,'' adding that he would have to see the
specifics of the proposal.
   ``But the general idea of a reasonably substantial, unilateral
reduction is fine. There's no way that that can result in a balance
of forces, but still it's a step, and so applaud it as a positive
step.''
   He said it did not compel the United States to do anything.
   While carving out a secondary role for himself, Bush and others
have noted that Gorbachev is aware who will be president on Jan. 20,
when Reagan leaves office.
   ``The next U.S. administration headed by President-elect George
Bush will find in us a partner who is ready _ without long pauses or
backtracking _ to continue the dialogue in a spirit of realism,
openness and goodwill, with a willingness to achieve concrete
results working on the agenda which covers the main issues of
Soviet-U.S. relations and world politics,'' Gorbachev said in his
address to the United Nations.
   When Reagan greeted Gorbachev on the steps of the two-story,
brick Admiral's House on Governors Island, Bush remained inside the
building for a few moments, allowing the two leaders to pose for
pictures together.
   Bush then quietly stepped outside and joined Reagan and
Gorbachev, shaking hands with the Soviet leader.
   Gorbachev greeted the vice president effusively, taking Bush's
hand in both of his.
   While Reagan and Gorbachev answered several questions, Bush
declined to speak.
</TEXT>
