<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gorbachev-WorldReax     12-07 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-World Reax,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Hails Arms Reduction Pledge; Communist Allies Quiet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Europe welcomed Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
pledge Wednesday to reduce Soviet conventional forces, but tempered
the praise with warnings that the Warsaw Pact still will have
military superiority over NATO.
   Television in communist Poland carried footage without comment of
the Soviet leader announcing at the United Nations in New York that
he will reduce troop levels by 500,000 and remove 5,000 tanks and
other arms within two years.
   Jacek Czaputowicz, co-founder of Poland's anti-nuclear Peace and
Freedom Movement, said in Warsaw the announcement could be the
``first step'' in pulling Soviet troops out of Poland.
   East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary, from whose territory
50,000 Soviet soldiers and 5,000 tanks are to be withdrawn, made no
comment.
   An official statement in London said Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, the most hawkish head of a NATO government, ``warmly
welcomed'' Gorbachev's pledge and will discuss it with him next week
during his stop in Britain en route home.
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner said in Brussels it
``seems to be a step in the right direction'' but that considerable
imbalances would remain.
   The 500-share index of London's Financial Times reversed a slump
and rose 1.99 points to close at 997.29. The dollar jumped initially
on hopes a Soviet cutback would mean reciprocal U.S. defense
reductions and a shrinking of the American deficit, but fell back
when dealers realized it was too soon to know.
   Widespread selling of gold resulted from the dollar's surge,
pushing the bullion price in London and Zurich down $4 to about $423
an ounce.
   Mrs. Thatcher's ``first reaction was that she warmly welcomed the
cuts in forces and armaments proposed by Mr. Gorbachev as an
important step toward securing a better balance of conventional
forces in Europe in view of the Soviets' present overwhelming
superiority,'' said a statement from her office at 10 Downing Street.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl now sees a ``good chance to reach
conventional weapons stability in Europe,'' said Friedhelm Ost,
chief spokesman for the West German government.
   Rupert Scholz, Kohl's defense minister, said Gorbachev must
follow up with ``actual and verifiable withdrawal of troops and
reduction of forces.''
   Franz Vranitzky, chancellor of Austria, called Gorbachev's
statement ``a courageous and constructive proposal.''
   Former British defense secretaries Michael Heseltine,
Conservative, and Denis Healey, Labor, disagreed in a television
debate about how enthusiastically to welcome Gorbachev's pledge.
   Heseltine said: ``If you're suggesting that, because he has made
a gesture which leaves him with vast superiority in conventional
forces I should say that there is no further threat, that is naive
to a fault.
   ``Even after Mr. Gorbachev has carried through all the reductions
he has promised ... he will have 3{ times as many artillery pieces
as NATO, 2{ times as many tanks, double the number of men and double
the number of aircraft.''
   Healey said the Soviets no longer are a threat and that no Soviet
government, even Josef Stalin's, ever intended to invade Western
Europe.
   ``The important thing now is, we have the chance of working
together with the Russians to create stability and peace in
Europe,'' he declared. ``We ought to grab it with both hands.''
   Paul Rodgers, an analyst at the Department of Peace Studies in
Bradford, northern England, said Gorbachev has the ulterior motive
of sabotaging Western agreement on modernizing nuclear forces. NATO
has not yet agreed on what to do after intermediate-range missiles
are withdrawn from Europe under the U.S.-Soviet treaty.
   ``It is going to make it much more difficult for NATO to agree on
a decision to modernize nuclear weapons,'' Rodgers said.
   Henry A. Kissinger, national security adviser and secretary of
state under President Richard M. Nixon, said in New York: ``I think
it's an important speech. The tone was positive and many of the
ideas were very worthwhile for examination, so I think it's a good
basis for relations after the new administration takes over in the
United States.''
   Dante M. Caputo, Argentine foreign minister and president of the
U.N. General Assembly, said the speech reflected ``a sort of new
philosophical approach in Soviet foreign policy, and I think this is
very, very important. I think this speech is going to very important
in the next decade.''
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney of Canada said the troop cuts
``will begin to reduce the imbalance in conventional forces which
have concerned Canada and its allies in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization for so long.''
</TEXT>
