<1ST_LINE>r w AM-People-Christensen     12-07 0115</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Christensen,120</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputy Attorney General Harold Christensen, the
No. 2 official in the Justice Department, is to be married Tuesday
in a ceremony in the conference room next to his office.
   Christensen, 62, a widower, is marrying Jacquita Corry, a former
assistant dean at the University of Utah college of law.
   Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, are expected to attend the
event, along with children from Christensen's and Corry's previous
marriages.
   The wedding ceremony will be performed by Judge Howard Markey,
chief judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the federal circuit
court, Justice Department spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade said
Wednesday.
