<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Military     12-07 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Military,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Meets with Commanders, Army Chief Rumored Ready to Step
Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin met with
his army commanders Wednesday and unconfirmed reports said Lt. Gen.
Dante Caridi, the chief of staff, would resign in a deal that
stopped the latest military revolt.
   In the four-day rebellion that ended Sunday, the third in 20
months, three military bases joined rebel leader Col. Mohamed Ali
Seineldin and several others refused to send troops against him.
   The 6th Mechanized Infantry Regiment at Mercedes, about 60 miles
west of Buenos Aires, remained in rebel hands Wednesday, apparently
because the Defense Ministry had not yet chosen a new commander.
   Maj. Hugo Avete, who rallied the base's estimated 100 soldiers
against two senior officers last weekend, ``is waiting to turn it
over to whoever the army chiefs send,'' a man who identified himself
as Avete's spokesman said in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press.
   Seineldin was questioned by a military judge. The 54-year-old
colonel was being held at a military garrison in Palermo, a northern
district of Buenos Aires. No details of the interrogation were
revealed.
   News reports, citing military sources they did not identify, said
Caridi's resignation was part of a deal under which Seineldin agreed
to end his revolt peacefully. The afternoon daily El Heraldo said
the high army command was deciding on Caridi's successor.
   Alfonsin has publicly expressed confidence in Caridi. After
Wednesday's meeting, presidential press secretary Jose Ignacio Lopez
said the general ``is and will continue'' to be the chief of staff.
   Caridi called a meeting of 28 generals and 16 colonels to
determine the situation in each of their commands and to help decide
which colonels would be promoted. Alfonsin met with the same group
later Wednesday at Government House, where he has his office.
   The meetings were to resume Thursday, the army chief's office
said in a communique.
   Carlos Menem, the opposition Peronist Party's candidate for
president in national elections set for May, said in an interview
with the independent agency Noticias Argentinas he was certain the
government made concessions to the rebels.
   ``The president said Sunday night there had been no type of
negotiation, and now he says there were two hours of talks,'' Menem
said. ``It seems that one of the conditions was the departure of
Caridi.''
   Defense Minister Horacio Jaunarena addressed the Senate in closed
session Wednesday for almost three hours. Members of the Peronist
Party asked that he explain how the insurrection was ended.
   Rebels had demanded an end to the prosecution of officers for
human rights abuses in 1976-83, during the so-called ``dirty war''
on leftists by military governments. At least 8,900 people
disappeared and are presumed dead, according to a commission
appointed by Alfonsin's civilian government.
   The rebels also demanded major changes in the defense hierarchy
and a bigger military budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
