<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Summit-Tour 1stLd-Writethru a0803 12-07 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Tour, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0803,0994</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Stops Motorcade to Greet New Yorkers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 20 grafs with Gorbachev getting out of car, gridlock
developing, new quotes, pickup 14th pvs bgng ``Times Square''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His summitry completed, Mikhail S. Gorbachev took
a 75-minute motorcade tour of Manhattan on Wednesday from the
canyons of Wall Street to garish Times Square, twice jumping out of
his limousine to greet astonished and delighted crowds.
   Though traffic was light most of the day, the dreaded
``Gorbylock'' arrived late in the afternoon once the 45-car
motorcade began snaking through the city.
   Traffic was locked up in lower Manhattan for about an hour after
the Soviet leader left the World Trade Center, where he and his
wife, Raisa, admired the view from the top of the 110-story twin
towers.
   At 50th Street and Broadway, just outside the Winter Garden
Theater, Gorbachev stopped his motorcade and jumped out to greet
people on the street.
   ``I was right there, and I yelled in Russian, `How are you,'''
said Geranno Valentine. ``He said, `Thank you, fine.'''
   ``The crowd was just going hysterical,'' said Joe Crawford, a
17-year-old high school student from Connecticut who had seen a
matinee of ``Starlight Express'' at a nearby theater. ``It was
fantastic, truly something fantastic to see someone like that up
close.''
   Gorbachev also briefly stepped out of his limousine at
Bloomingdale's, at Lexington Avenue and 59th Street, but despite
advance speculation that Mrs. Gorbachev planned a shopping
expedition, she remained in the car.
   The drive, which followed a luncheon meeting on Governors Island
with President Ronald Reagan and President-elect George Bush,
included glimpses of the New York Stock Exchange, Times Square with
its glitter and garbage, and busy 57th Street with Carnegie Hall and
the Russian Tea Room.
   All along the route, people gathered to get a glimpse at the
visiting dignitary. Crowds were thickest at Times Square, where the
scene resembled an early New Year's Eve gathering.
   At the World Trade Center, the entourage sped to the top of the
city's tallest building, standing nearly a quarter-mile high _ and
gazed out at the city's spectacular skyline as the sun was setting
into a bank of clouds.
   As the lights from skyscrapers around the city winked on, Mrs.
Gorbachev commented, ``How beautiful, how beautiful,'' said Port
Authority spokesman Mark Marchese. The group could see a distance of
25 miles.
   Marchese said Gorbachev asked where Kennedy Airport was and
picked out Governors Island by himself. When officials pointed out
the Empire State Building, the Soviet leader quipped that he had
heard of it.
   ``What I particularly liked about the city, is this is a unique
city, a city of splendid identity and architecture,'' Gorbachev said
in response to reporters' questions. ``You see different areas in
the city that have their own special identity.''
   ``We're very pleased by the fact that thousands of New Yorkers
have come out to see us,'' he added. ``We saw their faces, we saw
their eyes, their friendliness ... We are grateful for this warm
hospitality.''
   During the half-hour stop, Gorbachev endured a long speech by
Port Authority Chairman Philip Kaltenbacher. He appeared either
bored or tired and was seen several times twiddling his thumbs.
   The Soviet leader said his visit to the World Trade Center was
``symbolic'' because it serves as a center ``to promote
international economic and commercial cooperation.''
   Though he could have stopped in time to ring the closing 4 p.m.
bell at the New York Stock Exchange, Gorbachev's motorcade breezed
past the financial mecca.
   His long, black limousine, decked with a red Soviet flag on the
fender, slowed slightly as it turned onto Broad Street where the
exchange is located, just long enough for the crowd standing 10-deep
behind police barricades to proffer a hearty cheer.
   ``It looked like a new car show,'' said onlooker Brendan Murray,
27, an office manager for a brokerage firm. ``I hope he got a good
laugh out of it. He got half a hundred stock brokers to stand out
here for an hour and a half, and all we saw were his cuff links.''
   ``I just saw Gorbachev,'' a messenger said after the motorcade
had passed. ``I'll never wash my eyes again.''
   Times Square was ready _ with all its glitz, glitter and garbage,
for which there is no equivalent in the Soviet Union.
   The famous electronic billboard in the middle of Times Square
flashed a red hammer and sickle, with the message: ``Welcome,
General Secretary Gorbachev.''
   The greeting was sandwiched between advertisements for the movie,
``My Stepmother is an Alien'' and for U.S. News and World Report.
   XXX-rated movie theaters sported their usual fare, including
``Frisky Wives II.''
   ``This is the most exciting moment of my life, for two
superpowers to be in New York,'' said Lorenzo Hudson, a 23-year-old
security guard from Brooklyn.
   ``I'm supposed to be to work at 6 o'clock, but if I don't see
Gorby before then I won't go to work today.''
   Earlier in the day, the Gorbachevs toured the United Nations
where the Soviet leader addressed the world body.
   Outside the U.N. they were greeted by some 1,000 demonstrators
protesting conditions for Jews inside the Soviet Union, and
supporters of dissidents from the Baltic states, Ukrainians, Afghans
and Armenians.
   Some 56 people were arrested for crossing police barricades and
charged with disorderly conduct.
   Raisa Gorbachev did a little sightseeing of her own after an
afternoon luncheon with first lady Nancy Reagan and incoming first
lady Barbara Bush, visiting the Estee Lauder beauty shop on Fifth
Avenue.
   The city did not go to great lengths to spruce itself up for the
dignitaries' visit, other than to warn motorists to use mass
transit. For the most part, commuters listened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
