<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Summit-WTCText     12-07 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-WTC Text,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Gorbachev's Remarks at World Trade Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the comments made by Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev during a ceremony at the World Trade Center
observatory Wednesday. He spoke after receiving gifts from officials
of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   ``I thought we were here just as tourists, and that was nice to
be here as a tourist almost half a mile over New York.
   ``I'm very impressed by this city and by its architecture, its
bridges, by all that I've seen, the water. I've learned something
about the history of this city.
   ``I've been told about the history of the building of the
Brooklyn Bridge. The story of the building of this bridge is, in a
way, I think, similar to the story of the development of the great
expanse that is the United States.
   ``But one thing that I'd like to say is that it is certainly
symbolic that we are here in this building of the World Trade Center
that serves to promote international economic and commercial
cooperation.
   ``We have mentioned the Soviet fair that will be opening. I think
that political dialogue and political relations between our
countries should be supplemented by an expansion of our commercial
and economic ties. I think this is a very solid basis for a better
development of our relations.
   ``I think you have said quite appropriately that both our two
peoples share a desire to improve their relations. They both want to
know each other better.
   ``It is, I think, the task of political leaders to make policies,
to shape their policies, based on the will of their people. And this
is what I've tried to do today in my address to the United Nations.
   ``All Americans must know that our people deeply respect the
American people. All Americans should know that the Soviet people
want to cooperate with them. They want to have exchanges with them.
Our people want to live in peace with the Americans.
   ``I think we are now at the threshold, present at the birth of a
new phase in our relations, a phase that promises many good things
for both our nations.
   ``And this informal gathering, and the good atmosphere that I see
here is, I think, also a sign of the kind of change that we are
seeing in our relations. I'm sure that we can talk, that we can
discuss things and find solutions to any problem.
   ``Let me share with you some of the impressions about the meeting
I've just had with the president and vice president,
president-elect. It was a very open meeting, in a good atmosphere.
We shared the view that what we have been able to begin over these
years should be continued. This is very important.
   ``So I think our two peoples can look forward to good prospects.''
</TEXT>
