<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Summit-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0765 12-07 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0765,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Adopts Wait-And-See Attitude on Soviet Troop Reduction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Reagan speech</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, taking a wait-and-see
attitude toward Mikhail S. Gorbachev's pledge to unilaterally reduce
conventional forces, declared Wednesday night that U.S. officials
must exercise caution as East-West dealings enter ``this critical
junction.''
   Reagan said he was pleased with the tone and substance of the
luncheon talks with his counterpart on Governors Island in New York
Harbor, but that ``fundamental differences between our countries
remain in many areas.''
   At the conclusion of their fifth and final summit, Reagan toasted
the Soviet president for ``what we together have accomplished and
what you and the vice president after Jan. 20 will accomplish
together.''
   Asked how the meeting had gone, Reagan replied: ``Read our
smiles.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the lunch was ``very
enjoyable'' and that the participants ``told a lot of stories.''
   Later, in a speech to the American Enterprise Institute, a
conservative think tank, the president said that freedom is on the
march around the world while totalitarianism is on the decline. And
he said: ``I am proud to say I am still an anti-communist.''
   ``And I continue to be dedicated to the idea that we must trumpet
our beliefs and advance our American ideals to all the peoples of
the world until the towers of the tyrants crumble to dust,'' Reagan
said.
   While applauding Gorbachev's announcement of a sweeping reduction
in Red Army ground forces, Reagan said he wants to see how well the
Kremlin follows through on that commitment.
   ``About the Soviet unilateral troop reduction, I can only say
that if it is carried out speedily and in full, history will regard
is as important _ signficant,'' he said.
   The president devoted only one sentence in a 4{-page speech to
the initiative that Gorbachev had announced hours earlier at the
United Nations in New York, although Reagan initially said that he
``heartily'' approved of the measure.
   President-elect George Bush, who joined Reagan and Gorbachev at
the luncheon table, declared that the Soviet decision was a good
one. ``You've got to look at the specifics, but the general idea of
a reasonably substantial unilateral reduction is fine,'' he said.
``There's no way that that can result in a balance of forces, but it
still is a step, so applaud it as a positive step.''
   U.S. officials said the slashing of 500,000 troops from the Red
Army would still leave the Soviets with a heavy advantage over the
NATO alliance in ground troop strength, where they already held a
roughly two-to-one edge.
   Gorbachev, talking to reporters before parting company with
Reagan and Bush, urged the United States to ``take certain steps''
in response to his announcement, but he did not elaborate on that
point.
   In his Wednesday night speech, Reagan went to great lengths to
defend the peace-through-strength foreign policy that he has pursued
over the last eight years.
   ``Let us remember, too, that at this critical junction, our
responsibilities grow more, not less serious,'' he said. ``We must
remain strong and free of illusion _ for only by doing so can we
reach out and embrace this new era and transform this hope of peace
and freedom for all the world into reality.''
   Reporting on his talks with Gorbachev, Reagan said, ``I think we
both expressed satisfaction in what we have achieved in recent
years. But we also recognized that fundamental differences between
our countries remain in many areas. And determined efforts by both
sides will be necessary in the months and years ahead to overcome
such differences.''
   ``Over the years, I've been described as an inveterate
optimist,'' he said. ``An eternal optimist, a reflexive optimist, a
born optimist, a canny optimist, a cagey optimist, even as
`defiantly optimistic.'''
   ``I am an optimist because I believe we have proved with our
policy of peace through strength that when we are strong, peace and
freedom will prevail,'' he said. ``This November, the electorate
told us they agreed.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan traveled to New York separately on
Tuesday and had lunch with Gorbachev's wife, Raisa, and about 20
other women while Reagan and Gorbachev were on the island.
   Reagan is expected to face questions about the meeting, as well
as other issues, Thursday night in what is likely to be his last
news conference as president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
