<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Drops Snow Across the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow piled up Wednesday in northeastern Colorado, southeastern
Wyoming, the Nebraska Panhandle and parts of New Mexico as a winter
storm moved across the West toward Texas.
   Fort Collins, Colo., received 8 inches of snow by Wednesday
afternoon.
   Snow totals reported earlier Wednesday included more than 4
inches at Bellview, Colo., 4 inches at Sheridan, Wyo., and Dayton,
Wyo., and 3 inches at Lander, Wyo.
   At noon, 3 inches of snow had fallen at Alliance, Neb., and 2
inches at Scottsbluff and Kimball, Neb.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Wednesday night and Thursday
for much of western Texas and the Panhandle.
   By early afternoon snow was falling from Montana across eastern
Idaho, eastern Utah, Colorado, Wyoming, western Kansas and western
Nebraska, as well as Upper Michigan. Rain showers extended from the
upper Texas Gulf Coast across southwest Missouri.
   Almost half an inch of rain fell at Dallas and Fort Worth, Texas,
during the 6 hours up to 1 p.m. EST.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at International Falls, Minn., and Warroad, Minn., to 84
degrees at McAllen, Texas. The low temperature for the nation
Wednesday morning was 9 degrees at Devils Lake, N.D.
   The national weather forecast for Thursday called for
temperatures to be much cooler from the northern and central
Atlantic Coast across the Mississippi Valley, the Plains and the
southern Plateau.
   High temperatures should be in the teens from Minnesota across
eastern Montana, 20s and 30s from New England across the Great
Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the middle Mississippi Valley, from South
Dakota across northwest Texas, from New Mexico and the northeast
half of Arizona across the remainder of Montana, and from northeast
Nevada across eastern Washington. Temperatures should reach the 60s
and 70s from South Carolina across northern Florida, over the
central Gulf of Mexico states, from southern Louisiana across
southeast Texas, and southwest California, and near 80 in southern
Florida.
</TEXT>
