<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Akhromeyev, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0716,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gerasimov Says Resignation of Chief of Soviet General Staff Due to
Health</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New with Gerasimov comments at news conference; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, who has voiced
opposition to unilateral cuts in Red Army conventional forces,
resigned as military chief of staff Wednesday, the day Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced a cutback of 500,000 troops.
   Soviet foreign ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov confirmed
that Akhromeyev had resigned but said the marshal's decision was
based on poor health, and was not in protest of Gorbachev's move.
   ``He supported the proposals in the speech,'' Gerasimov said.
   Akhromeyev was among top Soviet generals who opposed a unilateral
reduction in the Kremlin's troop strength, arguing that the cuts
should be done simultaneously with reductions by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   ``For health reasons, he decided to retire,'' Gerasimov told a
news conference. ``It was merely a coincidence,'' he said of the
timing of the resignation.
   Gerasimov speculated that the unspecified health problems stemmed
from injuries Akhromeyev suffered in World War II.
   Akhromeyev will continue to serve as a military adviser to
Gorbachev, said Gerasimov.
</TEXT>
