<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Nuclear 1stLd-Writethru a0741 12-07 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Politicians Say `Economic Pressure' Led To Cover-Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Toepfer quote on Biblis
accident possibly getting out of control, possibility of
investigation. Pick up 6th pvs, `Biblis operators...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition politicians said Wednesday
that economic pressure may have led officials to cover up a nuclear
accident a year ago at a reactor in central West Germany.
   In the northern part of the country, officials said another
nuclear accident occurred nearly seven months ago. They said
investigators are determining whether the utility took too long to
report that incident.
   In Parliament, Federal Environment Minister Klaus Toepfer told a
committee there is an ``urgent need'' to better inform people about
nuclear accidents, and Chancellor Helmut Kohl demanded a ``complete
explanation'' of the Dec. 16-17 Biblis accident.
   The just-disclosed incident at Biblis nuclear power plant in
Hesse state has prompted charges of an attempted cover-up from
opposition parties and environmentalists.
   Toepfer has said he did not hear about the accident until Oct. 12.
   ``Under improbable but thinkable circumstances, the reactor could
have fallen into a state that would have been difficult to
control,'' he said.
   Marlene Muehe, his spokeswoman, said Wednesday that the
government may review the reliability of the utility that operates
the Biblis plant, Rheinisch-Westfaelische Elektrizitaetswerke. But
she did not say what such a review could lead to.
   Biblis operators allowed a malfunctioning valve to go uncorrected
for 15 hours, and a small amount of radioactive steam was released
into the atmosphere when they finally tried to rectify the problem.
   Environmentalists allege the accident could have led to a
meltdown of the Biblis reactor core. But energy officials insist the
plant has emergency systems to prevent this.
   The incident was disclosed this week by the American nuclear
industry newsletter, ``Inside the NRC.'' NRC is a reference to the
U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   Federal legislator Klaus Lennartz suggested ``economic pressure''
to keep the plant open may have played a role in any cover-up. The
disclosure has prompted widespread demands that authorities shut
down the reactor.
   Closing down an atomic power plant costs $570,000 per day,
Lennartz told reporters. ``Atomic energy personnel are under
tremendous economic pressure,'' he said.
   The utility company operating Biblis plant,
Rheinisch-Westfaelisches Elektrizitaetswerk, denies it tried to
conceal information.
   ``The utility notified not only the authorities, but also the
residents in the area,'' said company spokesman Heinz-Josef Franken.
   Lower Saxony state officials, meanwhile, said a leak occurred at
the atomic power plant in Stade city May 27 and the incident was not
reported for three days.
   State officials said the incident was given an ``urgent'' rating
_ the same as Biblis _ but they have not further described what
happened.
   Preussenelektra, the utility that runs the Saxony plant,
acknowledged the incident but said no radioactivity escaped from the
plant and there was never any serious danger to the public.
   A company statement said a valve in the non-nuclear part of the
plant failed but was repaired quickly.
   Werner Hemmer, environment minister for Lower Saxony state, said
state officials did not hear of the accident until three days later.
   But the company denied trying to hide the incident and also
rejected charges that reactor operators took too much time shutting
down the plant.
   Guenther Jansen, energy minister in Schleswig-Holstein state, has
charged that Stade operators did not shut down the reactor until
ordered to by federal inspectors.
   Stade is 15 miles west of Hamburg and Biblis is 30 miles south of
Frankfurt in the heavily populated Rhine River valley.
</TEXT>
