<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Women'sShelterShooting     12-07 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women's Shelter Shooting,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, 2 Wounded in Shooting At Battered Women's Shelter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman opened fire in a battered women's shelter
Wednesday, killing a shelter worker, wounding two other people and
barricading herself in a room for 90 minutes before police persuaded
her to give up.
   Denver police said Juanita Whitaker, 40, surrendered at the
Brandon Center after an officer convinced her she would not be
harmed and promised to buy her some hair curlers that she wanted.
   When the shooting began, mothers grabbed their small children and
ran out into the falling snow without taking time to put on coats.
About 35 to 40 people were in the shelter at the time, said Dianna
Kunz, president of Volunteers of America Colorado Branch, which
operates the center.
   Whitaker was being held in the Denver City Jail without bond for
investigation of first-degree murder. She was scheduled to be
arraigned Thursday.
   Police identified the dead woman as Jeannie Archuleta, 24, of
Denver, who had begun work at the shelter less than two months ago.
   Two people were in serious condition at Denver General Hospital,
said hospital spokeswoman Lisa Duchon. Ken Sanchez, 29, a shelter
counselor, was shot in the abdomen. A 31-year-old woman who was not
identified because she was a shelter client suffered a leg wound.
   Police spokeswoman Anne Montoya said Whitaker was despondent over
personal problems and soon was going to have to leave the shelter,
where she had lived since Nov. 18.
   Kunz said clients can remain at the shelter up to 90 days but did
not know whether Whitaker had been told to leave. She said the woman
had spent time at the shelter a year ago.
   Police said Whitaker also had been upset about the handling of a
sexual assault complaint she had lodged Nov. 23. Police said there
had not been enough evidence to bring charges in the alleged
incident, which occurred at a friend's house.
   Sgt. Phil Dinan, who persuaded the woman to surrender, said, ``I
would say it was a personal problem. She was very worried about not
having hair curlers _ and I offered to buy her some. ... I'm not
sure what her total grasp of reality is.''
   Whitaker's roommate at Brandon Center said Whitaker became
agitated when she was unable to see a counselor Wednesday morning.
   ``The next thing we knew she got mad because the counselor wasn't
there,'' said the roommate. ``She decided to go out and shoot
people.''
   Whitaker apparently opened fire with a pistol in the shelter's
foyer about 8:45 a.m. and then barricaded herself in a basement
room, police said.
   Despite being shot in the abdomen, Sanchez managed to telephone
police.
   Police closed off a three-block area around the shelter during
the standoff.
   Kunz said guns or any other weapons are forbidden inside the
center, which VOA has operated at one site or another for 92 years.
Police had not determined when Whitaker brought the weapon into the
shelter.
   The center's 70 to 75 residents were sent to other shelters
pending completion of the police investigation.
</TEXT>
