<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Protest     12-07 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Protest,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Officials Seem Ready to Allow Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's communist officials
agreed tentatively to allow an independent rally, which they have
not done since reform leader Alexander Dubcek was ousted in 1969,
dissident leaders said Wednesday.
   One activist, Jiri Dienstbier, said rally organizers and city
officials reached a provisional accord Wednesday to allow a
demonstration marking Saturday as the 40th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   Dienstbier, who belongs to the Charter 77 human rights movement,
said authorities were expected to make a final decision Thursday.
``It looks as if it is permitted,'' he said.
   If the gathering takes place without police interference, it
would be the first time in nearly 20 years that independent groups
gained permission for a rally in Prague. In 1969, authorities ousted
Dubcek in the wake of a Soviet-led invasion provoked by his reforms,
known as the ``Prague Spring.''
   Another Charter 77 source, who spoke on conditon of anonymity,
called the tentative approval of a demonstration ``a small step'' by
authorities toward engaging independent groups in dialogue.
   Authorities told organizers Tuesday that the demonstration will
not be permitted as requested in Prague's central Wenceslas Square,
the sources said.
   But Charter 77 member Milos Hajek said he and two other group
members went Wednesday to Prague's municipal government to discuss
an alternative location.
   The other Charter 77 source who spoke on condition of anonymity
said a second discussion with authorities later Wednesday resulted
in a tentative agreement for a demonstration in a small square about
a mile from the center of Prague.
   Saturday's demonstration was called by the Charter 77 movement;
the Committee for the Unjustly Prosecuted, known as VONS; The
Movement for Civil Freedom; the Independent Peace Association; and
Czech Children.
   Authorities banned a rally called by the same five groups on Oct.
28, the 70th anniversary of Czechoslovakia's independence. About
5,000 people defied the ban by gathering in Wenceslas Square, but
police dispersed them with batons, dogs, tear gas and water cannons.
   Police also put down a demonstration on Aug. 21 after about
10,000 people marched through Prague to mark the 20th anniversary of
the Soviet-led invasion of 1968.
   Saturday's demonstration is planned to coincide with a two-day
visit beginning Thursday by French President Francois Mitterrand. He
plans to meet with several leading dissidents Friday.
   Back in Paris on Saturday, French authorities have planned their
own celebrations of the human rights anniversary. Lech Walesa,
leader of Poland's banned Solidarity labor movement, is scheduled to
attend.
</TEXT>
