<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuperfundSettlement     12-07 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superfund Settlement,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$66 Million Settlement by 100 Firms to Clean Up Suburban Waste Dump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 companies that dumped hazardous
waste into a suburban landfill agreed Wednesday to a $66 million
settlement of a federal lawsuit to clean up one of the nation's
worst toxic dumps.
   The agreement, filed as a consent decree with the lawsuit in
federal court, addresses a decade of concerns over the 190-acre
Operating Industries Inc. landfill in Monterey Park, which took
municipal and industrial waste between 1948 and 1984.
   Dan McGovern, regional administrator of the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, said the settlement was one of the largest ever
achieved by the agency and a ``landmark'' for the federal Superfund
cleanup program.
   ``The decree represents a significant commitment by the 119
participating companies to clean up the contamination for which they
are responsible and to thereby protect the health and restore the
environment,'' he said.
   The settlement outlined by U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner and other
officials at a news conference calls for $32 million in payments
from some settling defendants and $34 million worth of cleanup work
from others.
   About 190 companies are responsible for 80 percent of the waste
put into Operating Industries, McGovern said, and the government
will begin issuing administrative orders to compel action by those
that didn't settle.
   The settling companies will build a plant to treat leachate,
liquid moving through the ground, to prevent contamination of water
supplies around the dump, which is 10 miles east of downtown and
surrounded by 53,000 residences.
   Neighbors have complained for years of health problems they
believe stem from the dump, which is bisected by the Pomona Freeway.
One side is a 150-foot mound of solid waste and the other is a flat
area where liquids were dumped.
   ``We think that it's a long time coming,'' said Hank Yoshitake, a
representative of Homeowners to Eliminate Landfill Problems, which
represents 460 families living in the neighborhood.
   The EPA has identified wastes buried there as including such
toxins as benzene and vinyl chloride.
   Dr. Kenneth Kizer, director of the California Department of
Health Services, said the site is a cauldron for potential health
problems for the community, but there is no indication that those
problems have come.
   Settling companies included the petroleum, aerospace, airline,
food products, steel and paint industries.
   The Superfund Act imposes liability for hazardous waste cleanup
costs on those who sent material to dumps, even if they did so
legally.
   Sixty of the settling companies have formed the OII Steering
Committee to undertake the cleanup. Committee chairman Jeff
Zimmerman lauded the agreement.
   ``The settlement embraces fully the spirit of the Superfund law
in bringing the government and the private sector together to
produce more effective and efficient cleanup plans for a landfill
which, while it was legally accepting a great variety of wastes over
its history, must now be addressed,'' he said.
   Zimmerman said it would be more costly to wage a legal battle
against the government than to settle, and in any event the money
would be better spent on cleaning up Operating Industries. He urged
other companies to join in.
</TEXT>
