<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia-Bomb     12-07 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Bomb,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Thrown At Congressional Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb shattered windows and damaged the
facade of the congressional building while Congress was in session
Wednesday evening. No injuries were reported.
   The legislative session was suspended after the bomb was thrown.
Congressional leaders condemmed the bombing and the violence that
has shaken this city of 1 million over the last two days.
   Peru's naval attache to Bolivia, Captain Juan Vega Llona, was
gunned down on Tuesday in the city center by a man and a woman who
described themselves as members of the Revolutionary Workers
Movement.
   The bomb explosion was heard throughout downtown La Paz and
damaged the front of the congressional building, which is across the
street from the presidential palace.
   ``The government commits all its efforts to investigate and
punish those responsible for this attempt against democracy,'' said
Interior Minister Juan Carlos Duran.
   Congressman Mario Rueda Pena said that if the violence continues,
``there exists the danger of a coup.'' He said that if necessary,
the government should declare a state of siege to ``control the
terrorism coming from the cocaine trade.''
   Shortly after the explosion, police received several telephone
calls indicating other bombs would go off in the congressional
building. No other bombs were found.
</TEXT>
