<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Rust     12-07 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Rust,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors End Investigation of Young Daredevil Who Flew Into
Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITZEHOE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Wednesday they have
dropped their investigation of Mathias Rust for his daredevil,
unauthorized flight into Moscow that embarrassed the Soviet military
last year.
   Rust was freed from a Soviet prison on Aug. 3 after 14 months. He
was sentenced to four years for buzzing the Kremlin and landing in
Red Square, but officials released him early.
   West German prosecutors in the northern city of Itzehoe were
conducting their own probe into whether Rust endangered air traffic
and committed other violations.
   But in their statement Wednesday, they said the investigation was
being dropped because of the time Rust spent in the Soviet prison.
   Rust flew a small Cessna aircraft from northern Germany to the
Soviet Union, landing on Moscow's Red Square on May 28, 1987. He was
19 at the time.
   His unhindered penetration of Soviet air space resulted in a
shake-up of the Soviet military.
   Rust, 20, now lives with his family in Wedel, near the northern
port of Hamburg.
</TEXT>
