<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paris-Strike     12-07 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paris-Strike,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Offer Splits Paris Transit Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four moderate unions accepted a compromise Wednesday
to end a transit strike that has snarled area traffic, but the
leading union rejected the proposal and called for the walkout to
expand.
   Gerard Becker, speaking for the four moderate unions, read a
statement saying they accepted the offer and ``rejected the policy
of all or nothing.''
   The complex compromise proposal of the Paris Transit Authority
would raise base pay for transit workers by $50 a month by Jan. 1,
1990. It would also grant raises of 2.2 percent that were already
planned for 1989.
   The communist-led General Confederation of Labor, which rejected
the offer, is demanding an immediate monthly increase of $170 for
all employees. The group has asked workers on the national railroad
to walk off the job next week to back its demands.
   Three other smaller unions, who did not participate in the
strike, had accepted the management offer on Tuesday.
   The strike began last month with its strongest support among
maintenance workers. By last week, however, it had halted all trains
on the suburban express network and disrupted subway and bus traffic
throughout the area.
   Premier Michel Rocard's Socialist government called in several
hundred army trucks to help commuters travel to work.
   Transit authorities said service was improving Wednesday as more
strikers returned to work. It was not immediately clear how many
workers would heed the confederation's call to continue the strike.
</TEXT>
