<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-USJudge     12-07 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-US Judge,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search Black U.S. Judge in South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stopped and searched a
black U.S. judge after mistaking her for someone they believed was
taking photos of an anti-crime operation in a black township, police
and the judge said Wednesday.
   ``Now at least I have a taste of what life is like for blacks who
live in the (black) townships of South Africa 24 hours a day, 365
days a year, knowing the fear, the complete lack of control one has
over one's person when police are doing whatever they want to do,''
said Ladoris Cordell, a judge of the Santa Clara County Superior
Court in San Jose, Calif.
   Ms. Cordell, 39, said it was ``a frightening experience'' when
police seached her on Monday, told her falsely it was illegal to
take photographs, and ordered her to follow them in a car to
headquarters.
   A police spokesman, Col. Saui Sauerman, acknowledged it was not
illegal to take pictures, but he said police can demand that someone
identify himself anytime.
   He said police were conducting a crime-prevention operation
Monday in Soweto-by-the-Sea, a black shantytown outside Port
Elizabeth. During this time, he said, one of the police reported
that another black woman was taking photographs of the operation.
   ``They confronted this lady without the knowledge that she was a
judge from the United States,'' he said.
   Sauerman said Ms. Cordell was released without being detained as
soon as police were satisfied of her identity.
   However, Ms. Cordell, who was visiting South Africa to
participate in a conference for U.N. Human Rights Week, said: ``I
was not free to go. At one point, I was so terrified I actually
wondered if I would be seeing anybody I knew again.''
   By law and custom, South Africa lives under a system called
apartheid that establishes a racially segregated society in which
the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5
million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts,
schools and health services.
   The U.S. judge said police searched her bag without asking
permission, searched the car without giving a reason, and told her
it was illegal to take photographs anywhere in South Africa without
a police permit.
   She was told an officer had seen her photographing police but
denied having done so.
   ``While they were searching, one of the policemen said to me,
`It's not as bad here as they say it is in the U.S., is it?''' she
said.
   Ms. Cordell said police ordered her and a handful of people she
was traveling with back into their car to follow them back to
headquarters for a complete search. However, she said police
confirmed her identity over the radio during the drive and simply
told the group to leave the township.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
