<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoatCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0712 12-07 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0712,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boater's Body Recovered After Sailboat Demolished By Ship, One
Still Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with one body found, Coast Guard
calling off search for other man, quotes, details. Pickup 7th graf,
`The vessel...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard recovered the body of one boater and
called off its search for another man missing after a phantom vessel
demolished their 37-foot catamaran off Key Largo, authorities said
Wednesday.
   The body of John Zeigler of Fort Myers was spotted by an Air
Force helicopter at 5:30 p.m., but Ronald Brennan of Sarasota was
still missing Wednesday night, said Coast Guard spokesman Dan
Vogeley.
   ``Since we've found Zeigler's body, we'll probably not continue
the search in the morning,'' Vogeley said. ``The Coast Guard
searches whenever there's a hope of finding survivors. Since we
found one body and the debris we found was very splintered up, we
don't think the odds are too good that we'll find Brennan alive.''
   The Coast Guard received a cryptic notification from an
unidentified vessel around midnight saying it might have hit
something about six miles southeast of Key Largo.
   Soon afterward, the crew of the Sawa Sawa reported that their
sailing companion, the Suli Suli, had disappeared after what looked
like a pleasurecraft, shining a spotlight, passed by in the opposite
direction, Vogeley said.
   The first debris was found by the Coast Guard at 9:30 a.m. about
six miles east of Key Largo, carried there by Gulf Stream currents,
and the crew of the Sawa Sawa confirmed the wreckage was from its
companion boat. The two boats had left Marathon sailing for Gun Cay
in the Bahamas.
   ``Normally if something is hit, you'll find large pieces of the
boat, but what we're finding in this case suggests the boat that hit
them was very large because we're finding very small pieces of
debris,'' said Coast Guard Petty Officer Joe Dye.
   The Coast Guard dispatched a Falcon jet, a helicopter and two
boats to search for the missing men.
   ``The vessel that originally reported that they hit something did
not give their name, and we're attempting to locate them also,'' Dye
said.
   ``The rules of the road state that a mariner is required to stop
and render assistance to somebody in need. Regardless of whether
they hit them or not, they are required to stop and assist them,''
he said. ``He obviously knew he hit something, so he should have
stopped and checked it out. He might have been able to help them.''
   Asked about the likelihood of finding the other vessel involved
in the collision, Dye conceded, ``It's going to be difficult unless
the guy wants to come forward. Right now we don't have any specific
information on the type of boat it was or where it was going.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
