<DOCNO> AP881207-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2340EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cardenas 1stLd-Writethru a0812 12-07 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cardenas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0812,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Opposition Leader Would Work With Government to Cut Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with additional comments; PICKS
UP
3rd graf pvs bgng, `It is estimated,' but SUBS penultimate graf to
DELETE 2nd full reference to Gorbachev</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Mexico's leftist opposition said
Wednesday that he would work with newly inaugurated Mexican
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to cut Mexico's huge burden of
foreign debt, but not on anything else.
   ``We consider Salinas and his government are illegitimate and
this makes for difficult relations,'' Cuauhtemoc Cardenas said in
his first appearance in the United States since Salinas was
inaugurated Dec. 1.
   Cardenas, who was defeated by Salinas in the recent elections,
added that he believes economic conditions will bring about Salinas'
resignation and new elections. He contended that Salinas did not win
the majority he claims.
   Cardenas noted Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's suggestion
that payments on some debts ought to be delayed by as much as 100
years, saying, ``We would support any solution that establishes
priority for Mexico's economic growth and improvement of social
conditions.''
   Any new curb on Mexico's worsening living standards would
endanger social peace, he said.
   Cardenas said the heavily indebted country can no longer continue
in present conditions. He said social risks and tensions are
increasing day by day.
   ``It is estimated that salaries have lost at least 50 percent of
their real purchasing power'' over the last five years, he said. He
added that unemployment has reached unprecedented levels, rising
from 1 million in 1982 to 6.5 million today.
   Cardenas, the son of former President Lazaro Cardenas, told the
Overseas Development Council that new terms should be negotiated
with creditor banks to ease Mexico's debt burden. The council is a
private organization dealing with Third World problems.
   ``The main contribution from the world financial community has
been more loans with which to service the debt,'' he said. Debt
service consists largely in payments of interest.
   Mexico, which owes more than $102 billion, is the largest debtor
in the Third World after Brazil. Much of its debt is owed to U.S.
banks. The country has recently had a $3.5 billion loan from the
U.S. Treasury.
   ``Mexico needs to grow economically _ and, in the short term, the
only resources available to do so are being used to service the
debt,'' Cardenas went on.
   He estimated that since 1983 Mexico had transferred $66 billion
abroad without obtaining any real goods or services in exchange.
   The speech was written before Gorbachev earlier on Wednesday
proposed to the United Nations a delay in the poorest countries'
debt repayments for as long as 100 years. Mexico, where incomes
averaged $1,820 last year, is not usually classed among the poorest
countries.
   For the somewhat better-off debtors, Gorbachev proposed a new
international organization to buy up debt at a discount _ a proposal
similar to one in the trade law President Ronald Reagan signed last
August.
</TEXT>
