<HEAD>Mayor Defeats Brother In Small-Town Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of this town of 1,600 people
narrowly defeated his brother Wednesday to win re-election after a
sibling campaign rivalry.
   Only about half the expected 600 voters turned out to decide the
race between Mayor Ben Stewart, 39, and his brother, Bob Stewart,
33. The vote was 168 for the mayor, 154 for his brother in the
non-partisan race.
   Ben Stewart, who has been mayor for eight years, called the
contest ``a very sad, regrettable, unfortunate situation.''
   Bob Stewart, who has been on the town council for eight years,
said his brother had told him he did not intend to seek re-election.
Both were surprised to see each other show up on the first day of
qualifying for the $100-a-month job.
   ``A lot of people are friends of both of us, and this has made it
hard,'' Bob Stewart said.
   Residents of the town, located between Atlanta and Augusta, said
the brothers' disagreement went beyond politics. Bob Stewart, who
runs an insurance company, had filed a complaint in Superior Court
over the distribution of part of their late father's assets.
</TEXT>
