Ma is cellist and not violinist.</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Musicians Came Two By Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a bass and a voice. Simple, right? Well, not
really for Rob Wasserman, who traveled all over the world to record
``Duets,'' his new album of twosomes with such artists as Aaron
Neville, Rickie Lee Jones, Lou Reed and Stephane Grappelli.
   He used a basic formula for the 12 songs on ``Duets'': The artist
selected the tune, the location and an instrument of his or her own
preference. But only Wasserman and the singer could appear on the
finished recording.
   ``There was no official producer on most of the tunes,'' he said,
``just me one-on-one with the artists. It's a real intimate album;
it sounds like that. It's got its own uniqueness.''
   Wasserman sought a range of styles for ``Duets,'' from Neville's
soul to the pop vocals of Jones, Reed's heady rock and the jazz
interpretations of Grappelli. The songs range from the Hoagy
Carmichael standard, ``Stardust,'' sung by Neville, to Jennifer
Warnes' version of the Leonard Cohen composition, ``Ballad of the
Runaway Horse.''
   ``It was challenging because I didn't just want to become an
accompaniest,'' said the 35-year-old bassist in a recent interview
at the SIR studio.
   ``I really focused on every song being different. Some tunes it
was more appropriate to play the simplest possible bass lines. On
other songs, I was all kind of roles.''
   He also was in all kinds of places. ``Duets'' was recorded in Los
Angeles, London, San Francisco and Texas. ``This has been more than
an album, it's been a journey, an adventure.''
   The record is a progression, numerically, for Wasserman. In 1983,
he recorded ``Solo,'' an album featuring only his bass playing. The
enthusiastic response for that work encouraged Wasserman to add
vocals on his next LP.
   ``I didn't really want to jump from the solo record to a band,''
said Wasserman, a native of California who lives in Marin County.
``I'd worked with a lot of singers on and off for a lot of years and
I realized that that was a great combination. For me that's always
blended really well if you find the right voices.
   ``I didn't know a lot of people on the album before I did it,''
he admitted. ``Sometimes I didn't get to play musically with them
until the session. There was that risk of walking into the studio
and not knowing whether you're ever going to hit it off.''
   Also performing on ``Duets'' is Dan Hicks, former leader of ``Dan
Hicks and His Hot Licks,'' who covers ``Gone With the Wind.''
   ``He was one of the first working jobs I had after I got out of
music school,'' Wasserman recalled.
   ``When I joined the band, most of the time it was just me and
him. He ended up being the first duet I ever played in. I asked him
to be on this record because I felt he was one of those unique
artists who hasn't had a recording out in quite a while.''
   Reed's appearance on the album came about in true storybook
fashion. Wasserman, who needed to record a few additional songs to
fill the album, was in a bar in Copenhagen when Reed walked in.
   ``The guitar player I was with said, `That's Lou Reed.' I had a
demo of the album with me. I went to him and gave him the tape and
figured that's the last I'll ever see of him.''
   Not exactly. He called Wasserman less than 15 minutes later. ``He
had heard the Aaron Neville piece and was flipped out.''
   And Reed, whose songs include ``Heroin'' and ``Walk on the Wold
Side,'' decided to record the standard, ``One for the Road.''
   ``I thought it was a great selection. He was also considering
`These Foolish Things,''' said Wasserman. He and Reed gave the song
a rock treatment.
   ``We didn't want to really do it in a jazz mode. I said, `I'll
play the chords on the bass.' We made up this primal, stripped down
kind of groove. It's still just two people.''
   They did it in one take.
   However, he spent the longest time working on the Warnes track.
   ``She's a very hardworking and intense character,'' Wasserman
said. ``She wanted every word to be perfect. With Jennifer, every
word had to be sung correctly. It had a lot of sculpturing to it.
She did a lot of incredibly subtle background singing.''
   An hourlong video of ``Duets'' is being filmed. The Neville
segment and the Reed segment _ with singer-songwriter-actor Tom
Waits as a bartender _ have already been shot.
   Next, he'd like to do a ``Trios'' LP, recording a piece with soul
queen Aretha Franklin and classical cellist Yo Yo Ma, He also
envisions a combination of himself with rocker Van Morrison and
Rickie Lee Jones.
   Of course, Wasserman would still like to do a solo LP.
   ``It would probably be a live concert solo album,'' he said. ``I
would like to do it when I have a new set of solo, bass songs.
   ``To me, all this is exciting.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Dec. 12</NOTE>
