<1ST_LINE>a a AM-LaughlinBoom Adv17   12-07 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laughlin Boom, Adv17,0927</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sat AMs, Dec. 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tiny Gaming Resort Town Continues to Grow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUGHLIN, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gaming whiz Steve Wynn stood in the
sun-baked parking lot of his latest casino acquisition recently and
enthused: ``Laughlin reminds me of what Las Vegas was 40 years ago.''
   Wynn isn't alone in the attachment America's gaming giants have
developed for this fast-growing gambling community, nestled along
the scenic Colorado River near the southern tip of Nevada.
   What once was a tiny bar and a handful of slot machines hidden at
the end of an isolated road has been transformed into one of the
premier growth areas in this booming gambling state.
   Giants of the hotel-casino industry such as Holiday Inn, Ramada,
Hilton, Circus Circus and Golden Nugget are clamoring to get a piece
of the Laughlin action.
   The 1988 visitor count is expected to be up by one-third from the
estimated 1.5 million a year ago. Casino revenues are forecast to
surpass those of Lake Tahoe, the No. 3 market in the state after Las
Vegas and Reno, in a year or two.
   Bolstered by balmy temperatures, ``No Vacancy'' signs abound
throughout the winter months.
   ``Welcome Snowbirds'' flashes a 20-foot-high neon sign atop Don
Laughlin's Riverside Resort and Casino, the flagship of the
ever-growing list of casino resorts here.
   It was Laughlin, 57, who happened across this remote area while
flying along the Colorado River in a private plane in 1966. He
spotted an out-of-the-way, rundown bar and paid $225,000 for the
saloon, a blackjack table, a dozen slot machines and eight
boarded-up motel rooms _ four of which became the temporary home for
the Laughlin family.
   Giving the town his name wasn't Laughlin's idea. When postal
officials asked for a name for the patch of real estate 20 years
ago, Laughlin suggested Casino, noting a town on Nevada's northern
border was named Jackpot.
   The inspector, of Irish descent, balked at the idea and opted for
Laughlin, calling it ``a good Irish name.''
   For many years, Don Laughlin's motel-casino was the only game in
town because of the remote location and competition from Las Vegas,
95 miles to the northwest.
   The town came alive in the early 1980s, with gaming revenues
climbing to $41 million by 1981, doubling to $80 million by 1983 and
hitting $242.4 million in 1987.
   Lake Tahoe recorded $309.5 million in gaming revenues in 1987,
while Reno had $552.5 million and Las Vegas hit $2.237 billion.
   Location plays a major role in Laughlin's stunning growth.
   The town is about 280 miles _ the same distance as Las Vegas _
from most Southern California cities, the markets that feed Southern
Nevada's voracious appetite for gamblers.
   Gaming giants sat on the sidelines for years while land
speculators touted the area as ``the next Las Vegas.''
   Suddenly, the major players began to make their move two years
ago, when the town had 1,600 hotel rooms. Today Laughlin has 4,118
rooms at nine resorts, with 3,000 new rooms to be completed in the
next 12 to 18 months.
   The first major player to move here was Circus Circus, the
family-themed gaming empire with operations in Las Vegas and Reno.
The company built an $80 million 1,238-room hotel and casino in the
shape of a Mississippi riverboat. The facility, with smokestacks
soaring 21 stories high and paddlewheels 90 feet in diameter,
dominates the waterfront.
   ``Not since Noah has anyone built such a big boat in the middle
of the desert,'' quipped Bill Paulos, the hotel's general manager,
when the company opened the facility on a blistering July 1, 1987.
   Last June, Ramada set up shop across busy Casino Center Drive,
the main drag that was a sleepy two-lane street six years ago and
now carries four lanes of cars and campers, bumper-to-bumper, around
the clock.
   The $60 million Ramada Express features an early Americana
railroad theme, with a steam engine train toting passengers around
the 406-room hotel and casino.
   Harrah's, the gaming arm of Holiday Inn, opened the Mexican-style
Del Rio in July. The $65 million, 446-room resort became the ninth
hotel-casino in Laughlin.
   Wynn, who owns the Golden Nugget in downtown Las Vegas and is
building a $550 million resort on the Las Vegas Strip, said Laughlin
couldn't be ignored any longer.
   He bought the Nevada Club casino from Del Webb Corp. for $40
million in May, taking over Oct. 1 and announcing plans to build a
$70 million, 1,100-room, 20-story hotel on the site.
   Add to the list of high rollers the Hilton Corp., which announced
in September it would build a $127 million, 1,200 room hotel and
casino in Laughlin, with construction set to begin next year.
   Most workers in Laughlin still commute from Bullhead City, Ariz.,
across the Colorado, a town built to house workers building the
Davis Dam, which was completed in 1953.
   As for Laughlin itself, its population is now 3,400, up from just
94 four years ago.
   The visitor count is expected to top 2 million this year,
compared with 17 million in Las Vegas, 6.8 million in Reno-Sparks
and 5 million in the Lake Tahoe basin.
   ``We average 20,000 visitors a day in the winter months,'' said
Dan Tucksen, executive director of the Laughlin Chamber of Commerce.
The figure jumps to 50,000 on weekends.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sat AMs, Dec. 17</NOTE>
