<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Japan-Supercomputer     12-07 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Supercomputer,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fujitsu To Market World's Fastest Supercomputer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujitsu Ltd., Japan's largest computer maker, has
started receiving orders for its newly developed supercomputer that
has the world's fastest processing speed in a single processor, a
company spokesman said Wednesday.
   The highest performance version in the eight-model series FACOM
VP2000 has a processing speed of 4 gigaflops, or 4 billion floating
point operations per second (FLOPS), in a single processor,
spokesman Isao Hirano said.
   To date, a supercomputer with a capacity of 3 megaflops was
considered the fastest, Hirano said.
   He said Fujitsu's new supercomputers can also use the UNIX, a
popular operating system developed and licensed by American
Telephone and Telegraph Co., in addition to Fujitu's own operating
system, known as MSP.
   Fujitsu would not disclose the sales price of the new
supercomputers, but ``most of the usage of the new computers will be
in the form of rentals because of its expensive software,'' Hirano
said.
   Rental fees will range from 38 million Japanese yen, or around
$314,000, to 80 million yen, or $661,000, per month.
   Fujitsu, which unveiled Japan's first supercomputer, the FACOM
VP-100@200, in July 1982, expects to sell 200 new supercomputers
over the next four years, according to Hirano. The company began
receiving orders Tuesday, he said.
   Supercomputers are large, complex devices that perform a variety
of electronic chores at lightning speed. They have been mainly used
for scientific and technological calculations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
