   A study by two Federal Reserve Bank economists
predicts increasing worldwide demand for oil will push OPEC
countries to full capacity and prices above $30 a barrel during the
1990s.
   But after adjusting for inflation, the higher price level will
still amount to only 60 percent to 80 percent of the peak price of
oil reached in 1981, according to an advance copy obtained Tuesday
of the study by economists Stephen Brown and Keith Phillips of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas.
