<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-07 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talk of East-West Breakthrough Ignites Rallies in Stocks, Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev would offer
dramatic peace initiatives enabling the United States to cut
military spending energized the financial markets, pushing down
interest rates, bolstering the dollar and rallying the Dow Jones
industrial average for the second straight day.
   Traders said rumors swept the markets Tuesday that Gorbachev, who
flew to New York to address the United Nations and confer with
President Reagan, would announce a significant proposal aimed at
letting both superpowers concentrate less on defense and more on
economics and trade.
   If so, traders reasoned, the United States would have more
flexibility in finding ways to reduce its staggering budget and
trade deficits, which the markets view as a fundamental risk to the
U.S. economy.
   The Gorbachev speculation was felt primarily in the bond market,
a sensitive barometer of inflation and interest rates. The
Treasury's closely watched 30-year issue surged more than $20 for
every $1,000 in face value and its yield tumbled to 8.9 percent from
9.12 percent late Monday. It was the largest one-day rally in about
three months.
   Declining interest rates, in turn, made stocks a more attractive
investment and pushed prices up sharply on Wall Street, where the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 25.60 points to 2,149.36.
That followed a 31.48 point jump Monday.
   The sudden enthusiasm for U.S. securities strengthened the dollar
as well, pushing it up against all major currencies.
   The market rallies eclipsed the other major economic event of the
day, the wide-ranging talks held by the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade in Montreal, where deadlocked talks on farm subsidies were
suspended with no progress reported.
   There was also little movement on other contentious issues: trade
in services such as banking and insurance, and protection of
intellectual property such as copyrights, patents and trademarks,
emissaries to the conference said.
</TEXT>
