<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Outlook, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technical factors continued to dominate the
energy futures market, where prices of crude oil and heating oil
headed higher.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
12 cents higher Tuesday at $15.46 a barrel, after falling 30 cents
on Monday. Other contract months also rose.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Tuesday,
the January contract for wholesale home heating oil closed 0.24 cent
higher at 48.60 cents a gallon. The contract had fallen 0.22 cent in
the previous session.
   But January unleaded gasoline, which lost 1.13 cents Monday, fell
another 0.09 cent to 44.35 cents.
   Analysts said technical factors dominated the market Tuesday, as
they had in Monday's session, in the absence of any market-moving
news.
