<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USX-Icahn     12-07 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USX-Icahn,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Moves On FTC Announcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl Icahn has been cleared by the
Federal Trade Commission to boost his 11.4 percent stake in USX
Corp., but his intentions remain unclear.
   Executives at USX's headquarters declined to comment on Tuesday's
announcement, while a secretary at Icahn & Co. in New York said
Icahn was unavailable for comment.
   FTC spokeswoman Susan Ticknor said the agency reported Tuesday in
the Federal Register that on Nov. 25 it granted Icahn an early
release from restrictions of the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act affecting his
further purchase of USX stock. The act enables federal regulators to
review antitrust implications of major stock purchases.
   The Pittsburgh-based company's stock rose $1.25 to $29 a share
after the announcement, then settled back to $28.50, up 75 cents for
the day on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``I think it's a lot to do about nothing,'' said steel analyst
Charles Bradford at the investment firm Merrill Lynch & Co. ``One
thing is pretty clear, that Icahn's postion at USX, although it
looks better today than it did yesterday ... isn't one of his better
investments.''
   Bradford said Icahn bought the stock at $23 or $24 per share.
   Icahn will have a year from Nov. 25 to buy additional stock
without reapplying for FTC permission, Ticknor said.
   Andrew Gray, an oil analyst for the investment firm Donaldson,
Lufkin & Jenrette, ``Icahn now has more flexibility or apparent
flexibility than he had before this release.''
   But Icahn has shown little inclination to move against the
company since acquiring his shares and threatening in October 1986
to make a tender offer for USX.
   ``He showed an extreme amount of patience. I never really
believed it would go this long. It's over two years,'' Gray said.
   Since Icahn appeared on the scene, USX has announced plans to
sell its transportation division and certain real estate, but has
not unveiled any major corporate restructuring to fend off an
unwanted takeover attempt.
   ``I don't think that's what people are looking for,'' Gray said.
``We're looking for bigger things. If you look at USX stock in the
energy group, it's probably been one of the worst performers ... in
1988.''
   Higher crude oil prices and renewed profitability at USX's steel
division could make the stock attractive to investors, and the
company-mandated retirement of Chairman David Roderick in May could
be misinterpreted as a chink in USX's armor, Gray said.
   In addition, Icahn could raise additional money if Texaco Inc.
follows through on suggestions it will reward shareholders in the
first quarter, he said.
</TEXT>
