<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0018 12-07 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0018,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expectations On U.S.-Soviet Talks Push Shares To Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs of background and analysis at bottom. A version
moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expectations of progress in U.S.-Soviet talks on
arms reduction pushed share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today
past 30,000 points for the first time ever. The U.S. dollar rose
moderately against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
30,050.82 after gaining 381.44 points, or 1.29 percent. The index
advanced throughout the day, then shot up 263.41 points in the final
hour of trading.
   ``Expectations of higher prices in the market were really strong
as the index approached the 30,000-point mark,'' said a dealer at
Daiwa Securities.
   ``Market players seemed to be buying issues simply in order to
achieve a 30,000-point Nikkei,'' said another trader with a major
securities firm.
   ``I knew the index would make the 30,000-point mark sooner or
later, but its gain at the last moment was just amazing,'' said the
trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   An analyst at Nomura Securities said the Nikkei's big gain in
Tokyo followed an overnight rise in the Dow Jones industrial average
in New York.
   ``Traders speculated that the Reagan-Gorbachev talks might lead
to arms reduction, and they thought a cut in arms spending would
reduce U.S. deficits,'' he said.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev is visiting the United States,
where he will meet President Reagan and address the U.N. General
Assembly.
   Market participants were also encouraged by Tuesday's
announcement that Japan's gross national product jumped 9.3 percent
on an annual basis during the July to September quarter, after a 3.3
percent annual rate contraction in the April to June quarter, the
analyst said.
   The measure of the value of the nation's goods and services rose
2.2 percent over the previous quarter.
   On the foreign exchange market, investors bought dollars
following the currency's overnight rise on Wall Street, dealers said.
   The dollar's strength in New York was believed to be largely due
to expectations that the United States and Soviet Union would reach
an agreement on reducing conventional military forces.
   Recent bearish sentiment toward the dollar on the Tokyo market
has eased because of the U.S.-Soviet talks, said Takamasa Yamasaki
of Daiwa Bank.
   ``The dollar is no longer bearish. Many speculative investors
were increasingly buying the currency, outweighing selling by some
trading companies,'' Yamasaki said.
   The dollar was also helped by speculation that the U.S. budget
deficit would shrink if the United States cuts military spending,
said a dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Michael Boskin, chief economic adviser to President-elect George
Bush, reportedly said Bush will ``take strong action on the deficit
on the spending side of the budget.''
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita said at a regular press
conference today that currency rates have stabilized but that
Japan's central bank remains willing to take appropriate measures
whenever necessary, a bank official said.
   The Nikkei now stands about 13 percent above the pre-crash high
of 26,646 points marked on Oct. 14, 1987, while the Dow Jones
industrial average on the New York Stock Exchange is struggling to
regain crash losses more than 13 months after Black Monday.
   Despite optimistic prospects, cautious analysts warned share
prices are way beyond the market's own energy and expressed concern
about a possible plunge.
   ``What goes up is destined to come down some time,'' said Josen
Takahashi, a chief analyst at Mitsubishi Research Institute, a noted
think tank in Tokyo.
   He said the current market strength is caused by a huge sum of
funds poured into stocks by land speculators looking for new targets
of investment after land prices peaked last year.
   Once the funds were withdrawn from the market, he said, stocks
could suffer a major setback.
</TEXT>
