<HEAD>EEC Starts Proceedings Against Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Wednesday it started legal proceedings against Spain for failing to
open its tobacco industry to outside competition.
   In a statement, the EEC's executive commission said Spain should
have set quotas for the import of tobacco from the 11 other member
states as soon as the country joined the EEC in 1s had not been taken.
   Under the terms of Spain's entry, the government was due to end
the country's tobacco monopoly by Dec. 31, 1991.
   If Spain does not take measures to open up its tobacco industry,
the commission can take the case to the European Court of Justice.
