<HEAD>Jewelry Concession Company Bought by Management</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of Finlay Fine Jewelry, which operates
jewelry concessions in stores across the country, announced
Wednesday they had bought the company for $217 million.
   Finlay had been part of the company Seligman & Latz Inc., which
was taken private in 1985 and which also operates beauty salons and
cosmetic departments in stores.
   Harold Green, who led the original buyout of Seligman & Latz,
will serve as chairman of a new holding company, Finlay Enterprises
Inc., while David Cornstein, president and chief executive of
Seligman & Latz, will serve in those positions in the new firm.
   Westinghouse Credit Corp. provided financing for the transaction.
   Finlay has more than 500 leased jewelry concessions in more than
45 store groups nationwide. It had sales of $265 million in 1987.
