<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-China-AutoIndustry Adv12   12-07 1015</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Auto Industry, Adv 12,1046</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Dec. 12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>China's Auto Industry Moves Into Drive</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3 of Dec. 5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is moving its fledgling auto industry into
overdrive, thanks to the influx of foreign money and technology, but
the goal of challenging other world leaders in the industry is still
a long way off.
   This year China will make up to 560,000 vehicles, all trucks and
buses except for 30,000 passenger cars. By the year 2000, passenger
car output is expected to jump from 700,000 to 1 million.
   By contrast, more than 15 million cars and light trucks were sold
in the United States in the 1988 model year.
   The increase in Chinese production will come about almost
entirely through joint ventures with foreign automakers, with the
focus on three ``production bases'' in the northeast city of
Changchun, Shanghai and central China's Hubei province.
   The challenge of satisfying the groe committed to using more local
parts, but
localization is generally only around 25-30 percent because of
difficulty in finding Chinese suppliers with quality goods.
   Michel de Riviere, deputy manager of the commercial division of
Guangzhou (Canton) Peugeot Automobile, said local content of only 6
percent in his plant is one reason their small station wagons have a
price tag of $20,000, equivalent to more than 60 years of a Chinese
worker's annual pay. They hope local parts will reach 20 percent
next year, he said.
   Riviere said it takes five Chinese workers to do the job of one
in most foreign factories because of low technology levels.
   ``The workers are bright and capable,'' he said, but the industry
``is still in a very early stage.''
   Chen acknowledged that the industry, which employs 1.5 million
people, ``probably has the lowest productivity rate in the world.''
   Chen said China, which now sells about $30 million in the $40
billion-a-year world auto-component market, hopes to export more
parts and eventually plans to sell some vehicles abroad.
   But he stressed the main purpose of entering overseas markets
will be to raise China's competitive levels in cost, service and
quality.
   Chrysler Chairman Iacocca, during an October visit, agreed that
improved quality is a must for the Chinese industry. He said he told
his Chinese partners, ``you must get quality up. Quality comes up,
productivity comes up, costs go down and the world will recognize
you as an exporter. If you don't do that, you can't play.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Dec. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
