<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-China-SovietReforms Adv11-1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0993</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Soviet Reforms, Adv 11-1st Ld-Writethru,1027</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Dec. 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Can Gorbachev Learn from China's Experience with Economic Reforms?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, Gorbachev, who ... political opposition., to
CORRECT to Konstantin Chernenko sted Leonid Brezhnev. This also
moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Mikhail S. Gorbachev maneuvers between
conservatives and radicals to shake up the Soviet government and
economy, China's reform experience can serve as both an
encouragement and a warning to him.
   Free markets, private enterprise and incentives have tremendously
stimulated China's backward economy and for the most part ended food
shortages _ also goals of President Gorbachev.
   But a decade into its economic reforms, China faces its worst
inflation in 30 years, irrational growth patterns, provinces and
cities that ignore central directives and rampant black marketeering.
   Chinese leaders say they are at a turning point, and that only if
these problems are overcome can they proceed with more advanced
reforms in prices, wages and other areas.
   Although China and the Soviet Union have many differences,
experts from both countries say the Chinese experience can yield
lessons for Gorbachev.
   ``It is impossible for them (the Soviets) to avoid all mistakes,
they can only hope to make fewer mistakes'' than China, said Liu
Qingjian, an economist at China's Institute of Soviet and East
European Studies.
   China began its reforms in 1978, when the thrice-purged
revolutionary veteran Deng Xiaoping gained control of the Communist
Party following the death in 1976 of Chairman Mao Tse-tung.
   Deng focused on reorganizing the economy _ breaking up communes
in favor of family farming,   ...
   Only in 1987 did China begin systematic government reorganization
and make limited concessions to democracy, such as multi-candidate
balloting in party-controlled elections. Political discussion
remained tightly limited.
   Gorbachev, who rose to power on the death of Soviet leader
Konstantin Chernenko in 1985, took the opposite approach. Unlike
China, where the political and economic chaos of the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution left many people open to change, the Soviet
Union presented him with a suspicious public as well as strong
political opposition.
   Gorbachev's method has been to open Soviet society to
unprecedented, frank criticism of the status quo, while proposing
constitutional changes in the presidency and parliament that would
strengthen his hand against opponents.
   But Soviet experts at China's Institute of Soviet and East
European Studies maintained in recent interviews that Gorbachev's
glasnost, or openness, has succeeded in enthusing only a handful of
intellectuals.
   To win over ordinary Soviets, they said, Gorbachev must take a
leaf from Deng's book and offer tangible benefits.
   Most of Gorbachev's economic proposals, including leasing farm
land ton,'' said
economist Liu.
   Free markets, at the heart of China's new prosperity, are
small-scale and expensive for consumers in the Soviet Union.
   A shopper in a typical Chinese city can choose from dozens of
small vendors, private and state-run, in buying a wide array of
fresh fruit and vegetables. Soviet shoppers often wait in long lines
for scant selections.
   ``If Gorbachev cannot improve the well-being of the Soviet people
... his position and his reforms will be weakened,'' said political
scientist Zhu Ruizhen.
   Deng tackled his reforms in one area at a time. He waited until
the breakup of communes had been justified by several good harvests
before making changes in the industrial sector.
   But Anton Vassiliev, an economist and first secretary at the
Soviet Embassy in Beijing, said this piecemeal approach has caused
many of China's current economic problems.
   ``This is perhaps one of the important exssiliev said.
   For example, Chinese factory owners buy most of their raw
materials at prices set by supply and demand, but face state
ceilings when they sell their products. They have authority to hire
and fire but only the most rudimentary of labor markets exists.
   Dozens of Chinese provincial and city governments have been
authorized to borrow money for capital construction projects, but
bankers have no corresponding power to regulate credit.
   Market confusion, flourishing black markets and steadily rising
inflation, now officially pegged at 26 percent, are among the
results.
   Vassiliev said Moscow has put greater emphasis on planning
coordinated change in various sectors.
   China also offers a lesson in the dangers of decentralizing too
much, he said.
   Cities and provinces given special economic autonomy have
developed rapidly, but they also have duplicated projects
unnecessarily and competed for scarce raw materials, fueling
inflation.
   When Chinese leaders this fall ordered a slowdown to curb
inflation, many local governments ignored the order.
   In agriculture, too, China may have decentralized too much.
Family farming has been popular but it has hampered the introduction
of machines and high-tech methods needed to increase yields.
   The Soviet Union has no comparable special economic zones,
although some economists have proposed them. However, Gorbachev has
already witnessed reform's splintering effects, as nationalists in
the Soviet Baltic states have taken advantage of glasnost to press
for political autonomy.
   China's Soviet experts said the turmoil created by Gorbachev's
political restructuring reveals a volatility in the Soviet
population that may make later economic reforms much more difficult
than in China.
   ``The Chinese people are more obedient,'' said political
scientist Wang Qi. ``If the Soviet Union were experiencing the
(economic) problems China has now, there would be riots.''
   Both countries have a stake in each other's reforms.
   Chinese intellectuals hope that if Gorbachev's political reforms
work, it will give a push to promoters of glasnost in China.
   If China's economic programs succeed, said Vassiliev, ``it will
generally show that socialism does have potential for development
and that the problems that exist now in Soviet society can be
solved.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Dec. 12</NOTE>
