<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Sears-ExtraCredit     12-07 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sears-Extra Credit,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Offers More Credit to Boost Holiday Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. says it has extended
billions of dollars of additional credit to 10 million Sears
charge-card holders in hopes of boosting holiday sales and clearing
out inventory.
   The aggressive move by the nation's largest retailer comes amid
price-cutting by many merchants to spur sales for the important
Christmas selling season.
   Sears said Tuesday that in the past month it has notified 10
million cardholders, or 40 percent of all active Sears-charge
accounts, that their credit limits had been raised by an average of
50 percent.
   The customers were chosen because they were deemed both
creditworthy and likely to use the extra credit, Sears said.
   The company said it also lengthened the repayment period for
those accounts to 36 months from 30 months, thereby reducing minimum
monthly payments by at least 20 percent.
   Sears had $13 billion in loans outstanding to its store card
holders, or an average of about $515 an account, at the end of 1987.
   Although Sears made the move ``to enable customers to have more
purchasing power at Sears stores in the holidays,'' the extra credit
is permanent and not just available during the holiday season, the
company said.
</TEXT>
