<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HollyFarms-Tyson     12-07 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Rejects Tyson Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of Holly Farms Corp., intent on
pursuing a proposed merger with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.,
rejected another buyout bid today from rival poultry processor Tyson
Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark.
   The rejection was the latest development in a takeover attempt
begun by Tyson in October.
   ``The proposed merger with ConAgra is superior to Tyson's cash
and stock proposals,'' Holly Farms president R. Lee Taylor said in a
statement.
   Tyson has offered cash and a stock exchange to Holly Farms
shareholders that the Arkansas company values at $1.1 billion. Tyson
offered $54 a share in a hostile takeover or a cash-plus-stock deal
valued at $57 a share in a friendly merger.
   Holly Farms' board of directors urged the company's shareholders
to reject those offers and to go along with the ConAgra proposal
announced last month.
   The ConAgra merger approved by the Holly Farms board calls for an
exchange of stock valued at $1 billion. The per-share value of that
deal would depend on market prices at the time ConAgra and Holly
Farms stockholders approved the arrangement. At the time the
proposal was announced, the value of the merger to Holly Farms
stockholders would have been about $55 a share.
   Tyson has filed suit in state court in Wilmington, Del., to block
Holly Farms' merger with Conagra.
   Tyson is the nation's largest poultry processor and Holly Farms
is the second largest. Holly Farms' proposed merger with ConAgra
would make ConAgra the largest.
</TEXT>
