<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0303</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced slightly today in a
muted response to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's speech at the
United Nations.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose more than 57
points Monday and Tuesday, picked up another 1.96 to 2,151.32 by
noontime today on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 676 up, 591 down and
534 unchanged.
   The dollar rose, interest rates fell and stock prices climbed
Tuesday on anticipation of the conciliatory actions that Gorbachev
announced in his speech today, including reductions in military
forces.
   They presumably open the way for the United States to cut its
defense spending as well, reducing inflationary pressures and
narrowing the government's budget deficit.
   But as often happens, analysts said, investors turned more
cautious today when their expectations were fulfilled.
   Some traders apparently cashed in on the market's recent gains,
following the old Wall Street precept ``buy on the rumor, sell on
the news.''
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone & Telegraph
rose [ to 29|; Sears Roebuck was unchanged at 40\; International
Business Machines dropped ] to 121}, and General Electric was down [
at 45{.
   Jefferies Group rose [ to 11\ in the over-the-counter market. The
company said it and some of its employees bought a large block of
Jefferies shares from Primerica Inc.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.19 to 155.97. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .20 at 297.56.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 81.34 million shares at noontime,
up from 64.15 million at the same point Tuesday.
