<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Diamond-Star-UAW     12-07 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diamond-Star-UAW,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diamond Star Workers Vote to Join UAW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just three months after the first cars rolled
off the line at the new Diamond-Star Motors Corp. plant, assembly
line workers have voted to join the United Auto Workers union.
   Diamond-Star spokesman Robin Skiles said today the automobile
manufacturer was officially recognizing the UAW as the bargaining
agent for plant workers.
   ``The UAW will represent some of our workers,'' Ms. Skiles said.
``The authorization cards were certified yesterday.''
   Diamond-Star is a joint venture of Chrysler Motors Corp. and
Mitsubishi Motors of Japan, and its management team is a
Japanese-American mix. Employees have received extensive training in
Japanese manufacturing methods and philosophies which stress a team
concept and company loyalty.
   ``As we have said all along, the question of unionization was to
be determined by our employees,'' Katsuhiko Kawasoe, Diamond-Star
executive vice president, said in prepared remarks.
   ``We are confident that the harmonious environment present here
at Diamond-Star will not change and labor cooperation will
continue,'' Kawasoe said.
   The American Arbitration Association certified that a majority of
Diamond-Star's 872 factory workers had signed cards authorizing UAW
representation.
   ``We are delighted to welcome the DSM production and maintenance
associates into the UAW,'' said a statement from the union president
Owen Bieber and other officials at the UAW's Detroit headquarters.
   ``Now, they have made their decision and we agree to recognize
the UAW as their exclusive bargaining representative.''
   The UAW officials praised Diamond-Star officials for ``their
sensitivity to American institutions and traditions _ in short,
their respect for the `American way of doing things.'''
   The 33 security guards at the plant voted to join the United
Plant Workers of America union.
   The $650 million plant began production of a new two-door sports
coupe in September. The vehicles, which are front-wheel drive, will
be marketed as the Plymouth Laser and the Mitsubishi Eclipse.
   Next summer, Diamond-Star will begin making a four-wheel drive
model of the Laser for the Eagle division of Chrysler to be called
the Talon.
   The 2 million-square-foot plant is a state-of-the-art factory,
which features 470 robots.
   The plant is projected to employ 2,900 people and produce 240,000
a year when it reaches full production capacity next fall.
</TEXT>
