<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   12-07 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Up 4.3 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher at Wednesday's close after
a late rally inspired by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's proposal
for a unilateral cut in Soviet conventional forces.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 4.3
points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,771.7 at the close, above the low of
1.9 points off, but well below the session peak of 10.5 points up.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 6.2 points higher at
1,451.0.
   Volume was a moderate 490.1 million shares, up from 466.4 million
shares a day earlier.
   After opening higher on previous gains in New York and Tokyo, the
London market drifted downward for most of the trading session as
the stronger prices were not supported by sufficient buying activity.
   But the London market rallied again off its lows at late
afternoon, lifted by the news that Gorbachev proposed a substantial
cut in Soviet conventional armed forces.
   Gorbachev's proposals triggered a rise in the dollar but only a
slight advance on Wall Street, as players focused on the
implications for the U.S. budget deficit.
   The new Bush administration should find it easier to cut defense
spending and so deal with the deficit problem, some analysts
speculated.
</TEXT>
