<DOCNO> AP881207-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TradeTalks 2ndLd-Writethru f0047 12-07 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0047,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Enter Final Day Of Talks In Disarray</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with new material throughout on stalemate continuing;
no pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MTL2 of Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ministers from the United States and Europe raced
toward a deadline in trade talks Wednesday, as delegates from the
Third World appealed to them for statesmanship to break a deadlock
over farm supports.
   The United States and the 12-nation European Ecoomic Community
have been deadlocked for the past four days of ministerial trade
talks and mediation efforts thus far have failed to break the logjam.
   Ricardo Zerbino, chairman of the Uruguay Round of trade talks,
held informal contacts with the two sides and drafted proposal
papers. He also convened delegation heads from more than 90
countries late Tuesday and expressed his concern about the lack of
progress in the talks.
   The EEC-U.S. dispute revolves around a demand by the United
States that all 96 member states of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade eliminate their subsidies for farmers.
   The EEC, with a much larger rural population and strong farm
lobbies, is only willing to reduce the subsidies but not to cancel
them.
   Adopting a proven tactic to generate progress on their last
scheduled day of talks, both sides announced their delegation heads
would leave Montreal by midday Thursday.
   ``It always works. They sit up all night and get an agreement,''
said one veteran observer of international negotiations.
   Canadian Minister of International Trade John Crosbie told
reporters late Tuesday that after four days of talks ``no one has
yet blinked, but I'm hoping to see an eyelid quiver before too many
more hours go by.''
   But Australian Trade Minister Michael Duffy said he was not
hopeful of progress before the end of the mid-term review of the
Uruguay Round of trade talks. The four-year round, begun in 1986 in
Punta del Este, Uruguay, is designed to update the 40-year-old
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The mid-term review brings together ministers from some 100
nations who are seeking to emerge from their talks with instructions
to their negotiators for the final two years of the round.
   The stalemate over the farm issue was holding up progress in
other ministerial groups negotiating over the inclusion of services
and copyrights in the GATT agreement, which regulates international
trade.
   GATT spokesman David Woods said some headway was made in those
groups, but it would not be reflected in any final Montreal
statement because of the ``linkages'' made by delegates to settling
the agricultural issue.
   Jose Concepcion, head of the Philippines delegation, said ``it is
a sad thing for the world when two powers put developing countries
at a standstill'' because of their fight.
   ``We have appealed to them to exercise statemanship that will
give substance to the act of faith that launched this round in Punta
del Este'' Uruguay two years ago.
   The agricultural subsidies, while of relatively minor value in
dollar terms in the international market, are a volatile political
issue.
   For the United States, elimination of price supports would ease
the drain on the federal budget. The government has poured as much
as $27 million annually into subsidies every year.
   For the Europeans, elimination of price supports would endanger
the EEC's common agricultural policy and incur the wrath of powerful
farm lobbies.
   ``Our common agricultural policy has to ensure a living for
family-owned farms,'' said chief EEC negotiator Willy de Clercq. He
said the EEC has some 11 million farmers compared with 2.5 million
in the United States.
   The Montreal talks are designed to review progress made so far in
the round and to provide negotiators with instructions for the final
two years of talks.
   Developing nations such as the Philippines, Brazil and India were
apprehensive that the agenda for the Uruguay Round would be dictated
by the interests of developed countries and would fail to take their
concerns into account.
   They nonetheless agreed to join the round, but significant gaps
have emerged between their positions and those of the industrialized
world in the past two years of negotiations in Geneva.
   The EEC on Wednesday championed the cause of the developing
nations, saying a U.S.-backed proposal put forth in a group
discussing trade in services failed to address the Third World's
concerns.
   Community officials said the proposal, designed to regulate trade
in such things as transportation and services, also does not take
into account the EEC's demand for reciprocal access to GATT members'
markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0274 </DOCNO>
