<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ZZZZBest     12-07 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-ZZZZ Best,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minkow Unlikable but Innocent, Defense Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense attorney implored jurors today not
to convict former teen carpet-cleaning tycoon Barry Minkow on stock
fraud charges merely because they dislike him.
   ``The presumption of innocence doesn't apply only to defendants
who are likable,'' said defense attorney David Kenner as Minkow sat
watching him from the counsel table.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, you may well not like Barry Minkow,'' he
told jurors in the defense's closing arguments.
   ``You may think Barry Minkow is a cad ... emotionally immature.
You certainly wouldn't want Barry Minkow to go out with your
daughter,'' he said.
   ``But none of those things removes from him the presumption of
innocence,'' said Kenner.
   The attorney then began a point-by-point answer to the
government's allegations that Minkow swindled big investors and
small ones out of millions of dollars with his ZZZZ Best
carpet-cleaning company. Kenner admitted there is no question that
Minkow defrauded investors, but he claimed the young man was the
victim of mobsters who manipulated his every move.
   On Tuesday, a prosecutor delivered a stinging closing argument in
which he denounced Minkow as a ``pathological liar'' who was
compelled by greed rather than mob threats when he bilked investors
in his ZZZZ Best empire.
   ``He knows how to get sympathy, and with all that guile and
deceit he stole more than a thousand gang members could with his one
little briefcase,'' assistant U.S. Attorney Gordon Greenberg said
Tuesday.
   Greenberg was the first lawyer to offer final arguments in the
four-month-old securities fraud trial.
   After Kenner's arguments and a prosecution rebuttal today, the
case was to be submitted to jurors.
   Minkow, whose company became a hot Wall Street item before it
collapsed in scandal, has said he was a naive youth manipulated by
mobsters who beat him and made death threats to get their way.
   Minkow, who launched his business at 16 in his parents' garage,
became familiar to millions of Californians through his television
ads.
   He is charged with 57 counts of securities, credit card and mail
fraud in a swindle that cost investors millions. Major banks and
securities firms lost money along with individual investors.
</TEXT>
