<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Torchmark-KCLife     12-07 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Torchmark-KC Life,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Denies Injunction in Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Wednesday to
intervene in Torchmark Corp.'s hostile takeover battle for Kansas
City Life Insurance Co. by rejecting a request for a preliminary
injunction.
   The decision was seen as a major setback for Torchmark although a
company lawyer said the Birmingham, Ala., firm would pursue its
offer to Kansas City Life's stockholders of $47.50 a share, or
approximately $347 million.
   U.S. District Judge Scott O. Wright refused Torchmark's request
to block Kansas City Life and its principal owners from buying more
of the company's stock; to force Kansas City Life to provide
confidential information about the comany, and to require Kansas
City Life to hire new financial advisers and set up a special
committee of directors to review the $47.50 offer.
   ``Despite the decision of the court today, Torchmark believes
that the interest of all involved in our effort to acquire the
Kansas City Life Insurance Co. would be best served through direct
negotiations between our company and the leadership of Kansas City
Life,'' Torchmark President Jon Rotenstreich said in a statement
Wednesday.
   The court ruling means Kansas City Life and its principal owners,
the families of J.R. Bixby and W.E. Bixby, are free to buy more
shares of Kansas City Life's common stock. The Bixby families
control 48.8 percent of the company's stock and could gain a
majority of the stock by buying several thousand shares. The Bixbys
have not publicized their plans.
   Torchmark had asked the court to prevent the company and the
Bixbys from buying any stock to maintain a ``level playing field''
while Torchmark tries to gain control interest in the company.
Torchmark is barred from buying stock on the market until its tender
offer to all stockholders expires next Wednesday.
   Kansas City Life directors met today to consider the $47.50
offer, but Fred Spar, a public relations spokesman in New York, said
he was not sure when a decision would be reached.
   Torchmark sued Kansas City Life on Nov. 16, the same day it
offered $43.50 a share for all of Kansas City Life's stock. Kansas
City Life's directors recommended stockholders reject that offer,
but Torchmark countered with the $47.50 bid.
</TEXT>
