<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TradeTalks-People Bjt   12-07 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Talks-People, Bjt,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeutter and DeClerq: Lions In Winter</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European is white-haired, tall, full of joie
de vivre. The American is intense _ people say his name rhymes with
fighter. Willy de Clercq and Clayton Yeutter are facing off this
week for the last time on the international stage.
   This week's brawl over farm subsidies at the GATT free-trade
talks here is in the grand tradition of the two men who have battled
each other with relish for four years.
   Although both men will leave office early next year, neither is
coming across in Montreal as a lame duck. Lions in winter would be a
better description.
   When it is all over, though, the two may actually miss each other.
   ``De Clercq sees this with a bit of nostalgia. They have had some
good fights with each other,'' said his spokeswoman, Francoise Le
Bail-Elles.
   Yeutter, 57, the U.S. trade representative, is the kind of person
who went from high school through a doctorate without ever getting
less than an `A.'
   He studied for his doctorate in agricultural economics and his
law degree simultaneously while also managing a 2,500-acre farm in
Cozad, Neb., and ranked first in both programs.
   Yeutter is proudly a free-marketeer: In his last job before
becoming trade representative in July 1985, he was president and
chief executive of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the world's
second largest futures market.
   It was announced early on here that Yeutter had asked to have a
typewriter delivered to his hotel room _ apparently so he could keep
working after everyone else had gone to bed.
   In contrast to the super-achieving Yeutter, the 61-year-old de
Clercq is a gregarious politician whose negotiating instincts grow
out of his 30 years in the fractious world of Belgian politics.
   De Clercq is the 12-nation EEC's commissioner for external
relations and trade policy. He is also Belgium's deputy prime
minister and minister for finance and foreign trade.
   De Clercq, who enjoys bantering with reporters, said before talks
started that he hoped U.S. negotiators had come like Santa Claus
with a bag of realistic proposals.
   The un-Santa-Claus-like Yeutter, in contrast, has not spoken to
the press. When President-elect Bush announced Carla Hills as his
successor, Yeutter's praise for Mrs. Hills was delivered by a deputy.
   What the two men share is a fierce stubbornness at the bargaining
table.
   ``They're both very effective people and they're both very well
respected,'' said William Crosbie, a Canadian policy adviser at the
GATT talks.
   Neither was available Wednesday for an interview.
   Yeutter enjoys one advantage over de Clercq: Since he represents
only one government, he has more room to maneuver.
   ``De Clercq has 12 mother-in-laws. He has always to listen very
closely to what his mother-in-laws have to say,'' said Bernhard
Zepter, a deputy negotiator for West Germany.
   The last official meeting between Yeutter and de Clercq is likely
to be this Friday in Belgium, where they will attend a U.S.-EEC
ministerial meeting.
   The directions they will take from here reflect their differences.
   Yeutter, who will leave office along with President Reagan, has
held exploratory talks with several companies about high executive
posts, including the Wall Street firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   De Clercq, in contrast, is sticking to politics. He will run for
a five-year term to the European Parliament. The election is in
June, and he is almost certain to win.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0279 </DOCNO>
