<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Soviets-PepsiAds     12-07 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Pepsi Ads,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepsi-Cola To Shoot TV Ad in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev spoke of
improving chances for peace and lobbied for better trade relations
with the West, Pepsi-Cola Co. announced plans Wednesday to shoot its
first television commercial in Russia.
   The Somers, N.Y.-based soft drink maker said it planned to film
the entire commercial with an all-Soviet cast starting next week in
and around Moscow. The film crew will be a mix of Americans and
Soviets.
   The announcement came as Gorbachev addressed the United Nations,
met with President Reagan and President-elect George Bush and toured
New York.
   The ad, which will employ about 20 Soviet actors and actresses
speaking Russian, is intended to show the shared interests of Soviet
and American teenagers.
   Tod MacKenzie, spokesman for Pepsi-Cola, said it will be clearly
evident from the locations selected for the ad that it was shot in
Russia.
   MacKenzie declined to disclose when the company planned to
broadcast the commercial, but he said it could be used on Soviet
television or carry subtitles in English or other languages for use
in the United States or any other country where Pepsi-Cola products
are sold.
   MacKenzie also declined to disclose which Pepsi-Cola products
would be featured in the ad.
   MacKenzie said he knew of only one other American product _
Dannon yogurt _that had been advertised in a commercial shot
entirely inside the Soviet Union. The commercial, which featured
some long-living Soviets who loved yogurt, was aired in the early
1970s.
   Pepsi-Cola is no stranger to the Soviet Union. Its soft drinks
have been marketed there since 1974, and earlier this year the
company was one of the first Western concerns to buy time for ads on
Soviet television.
   The commercial will be directed by Leslie Dektor, who is known
for using a shakily moving camera and grainy film footage in ads for
clients such as Levi's 501 jeans and American Telephone & Telegraph
Co.
   The work will be overseen by Pepsi-Cola's ad agency, BBDO Inc. of
New York.
</TEXT>
