<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0137</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market eked out a small gain today in a
subdued response to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's speech at the
United Nations.
   The dollar rose, interest rates fell and stock prices climbed
Tuesday on anticipation of the conciliatory actions that Gorbachev
announced in his speech today, including reductions in military
forces.
   That presumably opens the way for the United States to cut its
defense spending as well, reducing inflationary pressures and
narrowing the government's budget deficit.
   But as often happens, analysts said, investors turned more
cautious today when their expectations were fulfilled.
   Some traders apparently cashed in on the market's recent gains,
following the old Wall Street precept ``buy on the rumor, sell on
the news.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
