<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContinentalChairman     12-07 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Chairman,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naming of Corr as Continental Chief Fits Lorenzo Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The naming of D. Joseph Corr as chief executive
officer of Continental Airlines should help the carrier's
performance and it also fits into Frank Lorenzo's strategy for
maintaining the airline as a separate entity, observers said
Wednesday.
   Lorenzo, chairman of Continental's parent Texas Air Corp., named
Corr on Tuesday to replace him as chief of Continental. Lorenzo will
remain a director of the Houston-based airline, while Martin Shugrue
will remain as president.
   Corr, 47, is a former president of Trans World Airlines Inc. and
was a close associate of financier Carl Icahn, TWA's owner.
   Some airline analysts said they were not sure of the precise
significance of Lorenzo's move, but they believed it bolstered his
strategy for Continental.
   Corr brings to Continental the ability to squeeze profits out of
languishing companies, the analysts said. Continental, often an
industry leader in cutting air fares, has experienced financial
turbulence but recently started to show improvement.
   Corr is ``a good, hard-nosed manager,'' said John Pincavage, who
follows the industry for the investment firm PaineWebber Inc.
   Corr and Shugrue could complement each other well, he said, since
Corr is adept at overall company strategy while Shugrue, a former
top Pan Am Corp. executive, is ``one hell of a day-to-day operating
guy.''
   In announcing Corr's appointment, Lorenzo called him ``a superb
manager who has improved the performance of several companies.''
   As president of TWA beginning in April 1986, Corr helped lead the
carrier from potential bankruptcy back to profitability.
   He accomplished the same at ACF Industries Inc., a St.
Louis-based company controlled by Icahn, where profits increased
fourfold between 1983 and 1986.
   Julius Maldutis, airline analyst for Salomon Inc., called Corr
``a very bottom-line oriented, pragmatic businessman.''
   Pincavage said that by naming Corr as Continental chairman,
Lorenzo also could be aiming to reinforce the separation between
non-union Continental and its sister carrier Eastern Airlines. The
militant unions at Miami-based Eastern have been pushing for a
merger of the two Texas Air carriers, which could pave the way for
the unionization of Continental.
   In his announcement, Lorenzo said the selection of Corr
``emphasizes Texas Air's commitment to managing our airlines
separately.''
</TEXT>
