<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ToyStudy     12-07 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Study,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Rate Toys Through Play</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHEL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study that let children play with 19 toys
for five days before rating them for their ``playability'' has found
the top toy to be a video camera manufactered by Fisher Price.
   The toy company's ``PXL 2000 Camcorder'' allows children to make
video recordings and play them back. The toy finished ahead of
another Fisher Price toy known as ``Star Stage,'' which has a
microphone and stage lights for putting on a show, according to
Duracell U.S.A., a Bethel-based battery manufacturer that sponsored
the study.
   ``The survey results confirm that children will play with toys
they can learn from, but only if they don't look like school work,''
said Kendall Park, N.J.-based toy consultant Ruth Roufberg, who
conducted the study.
   Roufberg said the children preferred toys they knew how to use
without explanation. Toys that teach geography and deductive
reasoning were among the top-ranked toys, while toys that dealt with
optics experiments and fossils were among the lowest-ranked items.
   Roufberg said the two low-rated toys both contained ``school-like
booklets,'' which she speculated was a reason for their rankings.
Roufberg said her study also found that children disliked games that
involved rules or concentration.
   The six lowest-rated toys were science project kits and strategy
board games. However, the study found that the ratings of board
games increased by the final day, indicating these toys take more
time to appreciate, she said.
   The study involved more than 1,700 hours of testing by 352
children at 15 test sites across the country between Oct. 3 through
Oct. 24. The median age of participants was 7.5 years, with the
range between 5 and 9.
   Roufberg prescreened 1,000 toys for their educational merit and
play value to come up with the 19 used in the study.
   In the study, each child played with the toys for at least one
hour a day for five days. Children were then asked in one-on-one
interviews to choose their favorite toys.
   The study found that eight of the top ten toys were the same for
boys and girls.
   ``I didn't think boys and girls would show so much similarity,''
Roufberg said in a telephone interview Wednesday.
   The study didn't examine preferences based on age, but Roufberg
said that she would like to make that a part of future research.
   Combining the results for boys and girls, the top toys were: PXL
2000 Camcorder, Star Stage, Remoco's ``Footnotes,'' Hasbro's ``Body
Rap,'' Milton Bradley's ``Bed Bugs,'' Fisher Price's ``Discovery
Globe,'' Milton Bradley's ``Guess Who?,'' Fisher Price's ``Magic
Scan,'' Western Publishing's ``Shrieks & Creaks'' and Hasbro's
``Road Hogs.''
   The remaining nine, in order were: Ohio Art's ``Zaks,'' Parker
Brothers' ``Yoshi's Puzzle,'' Tedco's ``Reflecto,'' Bushnell's
``Light Fantastics,'' Playscapes' ``Sprint,'' Ravensburger's ``Up
The River,'' Educational Insights' ``Dinosaurs & Fossils,''
Pressman's ``Wordsearch,'' and Ravensburger's ``Guess My Name.''
   Eight of the toys tested require batteries, Duracell said. But
the company said its only role was to sponsor the study, not to
select the toys or have a role in designing the research.
   The toys rated top to bottom by girls were: Footnotes, Star
Stage, Camcorder, Discovery Globe, Bed Bugs, Guess Who?, Magic Scan,
Body Rap, Shrieks & Creaks, Reflecto, Yoshi's Puzzle, Zaks, Sprint,
Up The River, Light Fantastics, Road Hogs, Guess My Name, Wordsearch
and Dinosaurs & Fossils.
   The list of best toys according to the boys were: Camcorder, Body
Rap, Star Stage, Bed Bugs, Road Hogs, Guess Who?, Shrieks & Creaks,
Footnotes, Discovery Globe, Zaks, Magic Scan, Yoshi's Puzzle, Light
Fantastics, Dinosaurs & Fossils, Sprint, Reflecto, Wordsearch, Up
The River and Guess My Name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
