<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AmalgamatedSugar     12-07 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amalgamated Sugar,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Company Buying Amalgamated Sugar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristar, a British sugar producer, has signed
a tentative agreement with Valhi Inc. to acquire its Amalgamated
Sugar subsidiary, it was announced Wednesday.
   The purchase price was undisclosed, but Dallas-based Valhi said
the sale would bring it an after-tax gain of $185 million. The sale
must be approved by the boards of directors of Bristar and Valhi.
   Bristar is the food division of S&W Berisford PLC, which also
owns British Sugar, one of Europe's leading beet sugar companies.
   Bristar has said that it intends to retain Amalgamated's current
management. The sale will not result in any noticeable changes in
the company's beet sugar operations, said Amalgamated President
Allan M. Lipman Jr.
   ``I think we'll operate on our own,'' he said.
   Amalgamated is among the U.S. leaders in beet sugar, accounting
for 9 percent of domestic sugar production. While it is based in
Ogden, Amalgamated mostly operates in Idaho and Oregon.
   Amalgamated was founded in 1897 by David Eccles as Ogden Sugar
Co. It employs 75 workers at its Ogden operations and another 1,125
full-time and 1,600 seasonal workers, mostly in southern Idaho.
   The company is finishing an anticipated record year in sales and
earnings, recording $19.1 million in profit on sales of $295.6
million through the first three quarters of 1988.
   Amalgamated has had an informal relationship with British Sugar
dating back 40 years, and Lipman has known managers of the company
for some time, he said.
   British Sugar officials approached Lipman about a possible buyout
in October, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
