<DOCNO> AP881207-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 1758EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Local560 Bjt   12-07 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Local 560, Bjt,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Control of Union Ends With Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's first experiment in
taking over a mob-run union ended Wednesday with one of the nation's
largest Teamsters locals electing officers allied to the corrupt
regime ousted four years ago.
   ``I think it's a real disaster for the future of the labor
movement ...,'' said Clyde Summers a labor law expert at the
University of Pennsylvania.
   But other labor observers said the very existence of a
legitimately contested election at Local 560 justified the interim
rule by a court-appointed trustee that preceded the vote.
   ``Newcomers represent the revitalization of the political process
in this local,'' said Linda Kaboolian, a fellow at Harvard
University's Kennedy School of Government who has researched the
Local 560 trusteeship for a year.
   ``That they didn't win isn't the final word on the future of
Local 560,'' she said.
   The election also could affect the Justice Department's suit
against the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, which seeks to
oust the parent union's board and establish a trustee to keep out
corruption and establish elections.
   ``Certainly it's a good example of a potential backlash against a
trusteeship,'' said Goldberg.
   The Teamsters for Liberty ticket, which includes two relatives of
ousted officers of Local 560, captured 65 percent of 4,530 ballots
counted Tuesday and early Wednesday in balloting that brought an
unusually high turnout among the local's 7,600 members.
   Teamsters for Liberty opposed the court-appointed trusteeship,
which was imposed in 1986 after U.S. District Judge Harold A.
Ackerman found in a Justice Department lawsuit that organized crime
had ruled the Union City-based local for more than a quarter-century.
   He ordered removal of the local's executive board.
   Ballots were mailed on November in the local's first contested
election in 23 years.
   Danny Sciarra and Mark Sheridan led the winning slate to become
the new president and vice president.
   They are relatives of former officers Michael Sciarra and Joseph
Sheridan, who this fall were barred from running because of ties to
the old leaders. The new officers have said they will rely on and
consult with their kin in running the union.
   The trustee, Edwin H. Stier, a former prosecutor, will monitor
the local for at least three months, after which the new
seven-member board must report to Ackerman on its activities. The
judge also kept indefinite jurisdiction over the board.
   Attorney Harvey Weissbard, who represented Michael Sciarra and
Joseph Sheridan, said the vote's results were a clear vindication of
his clients and a rejection of the trusteeship.
   ``I think clearly the vast majority of the members ... really did
not appreciate having the trusteeship thrust upon them,'' he said.
``I just think that the whole concept is ill-conceived.''
   Summers said the local's history of violence and intimidation at
the hands of the Genovese organize crime family might have helped
bring about the result.
   The opposition, an independant rank-and-file group that arose
during the trusteeship, had little chance to gain support if members
saw ``no guarantee of one's life, limb and future work'' following
the old leadership's victory, Summers said.
   Michael Goldberg, a visiting labor law professor at the
University of Washington in Seattle, said the race might have been
closer if the shop stewards, many of whom were beholden to the old
regime, had been replaced.
   ``It just demonstrates how difficult it is for any remedy to
succeed when you have 30 years of entrenched and autocratic
leadership,'' Goldberg said.
   Arthur L. Fox, a Washington, D.C., lawyer who represents
dissident Teamsters, said Michael Sciarra and Joseph Sheridan were
well-known and liked and considered experienced by the membership.
Their visibility coupled with better organized and financed
Teamsters for Liberty probably contributed to the ticket's victory,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881207-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 0814EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-07 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0557</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deadlocked talks on farm subsidies were suspended
as U.S. and European negotiators reported no progress on
agriculture, the stickiest issue in broad-ranging free-trade talks
that involve more than 100 nations.
   There was also little movement Tuesday on developed nations'
proposals for free trade in services such as banking and insurance,
and protection of intellectual property such as copyrights, patents
and trademarks.
   Cabinet ministers are meeting here to give political thrust to
the final two years of the four-year Uruguay Round of free-trade
talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush, who has pledged to
give trade a top priority, filled the government's top two trade
policy jobs with Texas oilman Robert Mosbacher as commerce secretary
and lawyer Carla Hills as U.S. trade representative.
   The vice president, announcing his latest choices Tuesday, said
he was completing his economic team with the naming of Stanford
economist Michael Boskin as chairman of the Council of Economic
Advisers.
   Bush also told reporters he had decided to ``take the offensive''
on coming up with a budget strategy that attacks the federal deficit
without new taxes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance industry officials told Congress that
California's recently approved initiative slashing auto insurance
rates was ``no mandate'' and would do nothing to control soaring
premiums.
   But consumer activist Ralph Nader and the author of California's
Proposition 103 told the same House panel Tuesday that the measure
is an important first step toward reining in high insurance costs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ The chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board says
that before year's end regulators ``will have dealt with the worst
cases'' of the troubled savings and loan industry and that with $30
billion more they could tackle the others.
   However, members of the National Council of Savings Institutions
gave a more somber picture of the industry on Tuesday, saying that
FHLBB Chairman M. Danny Wall might be underestimating the cost of
removing the 511 insolvent thrifts nationwide.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court spared the coal mining
industry from paying potentially billions of dollars in black-lung
benefits, but it ruled that some miners who worked less than 10
years may seek disability pay.
   The 9-0 decision Tuesday shields coal mine operators from paying
as much as $13.6 billion to a group of miners estimated to number up
to 155,000.
   At the same time, the court ruled, 5-4, that from 8,000 to 10,000
miners with pending claims are eligible to seek hundreds of millions
of dollars in benefits. That smaller group of miners consists of
workers with less than 10 years of work in the mines who say they
have been disabled by black lung disease, a respiratory ailment
caused by prolonged inhaling of coal dust.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. says it is lowering
its basic interstate long-distance rates by 3.9 percent as part of
an overall package of price cuts.
   The announcement Tuesday by Washington-based MCI, the
second-largest long-distance telephone company, came six days after
industry leader American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and No. 3 US
Sprint Communications Corp. announced cuts averaging 3.8 percent and
3.85 percent, respectively.
</TEXT>
