<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FoxFined     12-07 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fox Fined,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twentieth Century Fox Fined $500,000 for Contempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twentieth Century-Fox Film Corp. and one of its
executives were given maximum fines by a federal judge in Manhattan
Wednesday for violating a 1951 anti-trust agreement.
   U.S. District Judge Edmund L. Palmieri fined the film company
$500,000 and handed another $5,000 penalty to the manager of a Fox
regional office for illegally restricting the distribution of films
in the Midwest _ in violation of the 37-year-old agreement with the
government.
   Previously, Palmieri found the company and Leila J. Goldstein,
manager of Fox's Indianapolis-Milwaukee-Minneapolis office, had
engaged in block booking, the practice of pressuring theater owners
to show less lucrative films in return for exhibition rights to box
office hits.
   Palmieri made that finding following a bench trial last month at
which testimony showed Ms. Goldstein directed Fox employees to book
blockbuster hits only at theaters where Fox's less desirable _ and
less profitable _ films were scheduled to play first.
   The judge ruled that Fox ``flagrantly and repeatedly'' violated
the consent agreement which provided that Fox would not enter into
any license ``in which the right to exhibit one feature is
conditioned upon the licensee's taking one or more other features.''
   The films involved in the block booking allegations included
``Prizzi's Honor,'' ``Cocoon'' and ``Black Widow.''
   The 1951 agreement settled protracted court action in which the
Justice Department accused Fox and seven other major companies of
illegal practices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
