<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-07 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Falter On Gorbachev Remarks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's announcement of a unilateral
reduction of armed forces in Eastern Europe sent gold futures prices
down about $5 a troy ounce Wednesday on New York's Commodity
Exchange, analysts said.
   Futures prices of other precious metals also declined while
copper futures leaped on renewed concerns about tight supplies.
   On other markets, energy futures were mostly higher; grains and
soybeans were mixed; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
stock-index futures advanced.
   Many investors consider gold and other precious metals relatively
secure investments in times of political unrest and economic
distress.
   Gorbachev's visit to New York was perceived as a signal that
superpower tensions were easing, prompting many speculators to
unload gold futures contracts, analysts said.
   ``It's almost as if good news for everybody else is bad news for
gold,'' said James Steel, a metals analyst with Refco Inc. in New
York.
   Gorbachev's announcement of planned military cuts in a speech to
the United Nations General Assembly also contributed to the sell-off
in the precious-metals markets on ideas that a reduction in Soviet
military spending ``could lead the United States to finding a
convenient avenue to reducing its budget deficit through cutbacks on
the military side,'' said Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Steel said a meeting scheduled for Thursday among finance
ministers from the seven largest Western nations, including the
United States, is expected to produce an agreement to support the
dollar, a notion that spurred further selling of gold futures.
   Gold settled $4.70 to $5.40 lower with the contract for delivery
in February at $427.70 a troy ounce; silver was 2.1 cents to 3.4
cents lower with March at $6.28 a troy ounce.
   Copper futures prices soared on the Commodity Exchange following
reports of an explosion at one of the world's largest copper mines,
in Bouganville, Papua New Guinea. The incident refocused attention
on the extremely tight global supply situation, analysts said.
   ``When you get a sharp, clear news story that everyone can
understand, it kind of crystalizes everybody's simmering concerns,''
said Steel.
   Copper settled 1.80 cents to 6 cents higher with the active March
contract at $1.373 a pound and the spot December contract at $1.5725
a pound.
   Most energy futures prices headed higher in moderate trading on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, reflecting concern about crude-oil
supplies, analysts said.
   The rally was linked to lower-than-expected weekly crude supply
figures released late Tuesday by the American Petroleum Institute.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 28 cents to 33 cents
higher with January at $15.74 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent to
.52 cent higher with February at 48.21 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .59 cent lower to .41 cent higher with January at 43.76
cents a gallon.
   Wheat futures prices rose on the Chicago Board of Trade, partly
in reaction to Gorbachev's remarks at the United Nations and partly
on expectations, which were later confirmed, that a large export
offer was in the works.
   Other grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower.
   Gorbachev's remarks stirred speculation that the Soviet Union
would use money saved through reduced defense spending to buy more
U.S. grain, said John Frazier, a grain-market specialist with
Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced that it had
targeted China for 1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices and that 100,000 metric tons of subsidized wheat had been
sold to Morocco.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 3 cents higher with December at $4.23
a bushel; corn was 2} cents lower to \ cent higher with December at
$2.55\ a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to } cent higher with
December at $1.99 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 5\ cents lower
with January at $7.68 a bushel.
   Frozen pork-belly futures fell sharply for a second day on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, reflecting concerns about the extremely
large supplies overhanging the market, analysts said.
   Hog and cattle futures finished mostly higher in a day of light,
choppy trading.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent to .40 cent higher with December at
71.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with January at 82.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with December at 40.87 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .48 cent to .95 cent lower with February at
42.72 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures posted moderate gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled .95 point higher at 281.45. The
contract is worth $500 per point.
</TEXT>
