<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Prime-MAI     12-07 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prime-MAI,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Presses Bid for Prime Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. pressed its hostile bid
for Prime Computer Inc. on Wednesday, extending the deadline on its
$970 million tender offer for Prime stock and alleging that Prime's
board of directors has misled federal regulators and the public
about its takeover defenses.
   MAI Basic, controlled by New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, said
its offer to buy all of Prime's outstanding common stock for $20 a
share would remain in force until Dec. 21. The offer, made Nov. 15,
had been scheduled to expire Dec. 13.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Wednesday, Prime closed at
$17.50 a share, down 12.5 cents. MAI Basic was unchanged at $9.
   MAI Basic, a computer company based in Tustin, Calif., said the
extension of its tender offer was intended to give a Delaware
Chancery Court time to rule on a lawsuit challenging Prime's
takeover defenses, including shareholder rights and employee
protection plans. A hearing on the suit is scheduled for Dec. 9.
   MAI Basic also moved to amend the suit by adding several
allegations against Prime and its chairman, David J. Dunn.
   The amended complaint alleges that Prime instituted its takeover
defenses after LeBow met privately on Sept. 19 with Prime's former
chief executive officer, Joe M. Henson, to discuss the possibility
of a takeover. MAI Basic alleges that the defenses served no
legitimate business purpose and were designed solely to impose a
crippling cost on any hostile buyer.
   The complaint also alleges that Dunn and his investment
partnership, Idanta Partners, bought 60,000 shares of Prime stock
after LeBow met with Henson but before the takeover bid was
announced publicly.
   Prime, based in Natick, reported earnings of $33.4 million, or 69
cents a share, on revenue of $1.16 billion for the first three
quarters of this year. MAI Basic reported earnings of $18.7 million,
or $1.25 a share, on revenue of $302.9 million.
</TEXT>
