<FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-88 2300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0313 12-07 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0313,0268</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, Nikkei
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar surged against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices retreated on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The Nikkei stock average of 225 issues, which surpassed the
30,000-point level by closing 381.44 points higher Wednesday, lost
178.26 points, or 0.59 percent, sinking back to 29,872.56.
   The dollar, which opened at 123.40 yen, was changing hands at the
same rate in late morning, up 0.97 yen from Wednesday's close of
122.43 yen.
   After opening higher following overnight gains in New York and
London, the dollar fluctuated between 122.95 yen and 123.48 yen,
trading above the 123.00-yen level for the first time since Nov. 16,
when it opened at 123.58 yen.
   There was little movement after the currency market opened, said
Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Although the dollar in New York rose sharply following news of
a possible Soviet arms reduction in Europe, players in Tokyo don't
believe the dollar's uptrend will continue much longer,'' she said.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, in an address Wednesday to the
United Nations, pledged a unilateral reduction of Soviet troops and
a cutback in conventional arms.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei average slid back mainly
because of profit-taking and the higher dollar, said an analyst with
Nomura Securities.
   He said many traders, who bought cheaper stocks in spot trading
and sold issues in futures trading to collect profits from the
difference, were mainly selling in spot trading Thursday, pushing
prices lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
